<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P>

<H5><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></H5>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</FONT><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="#anchor338406">Suit cites chemicals for
illnesses</A></FONT></B></P>

<DL>
  <DD>LAKE CITY--(EnviroWorld)-- Occidental Chemical Corp. and PCS Phosphate
  have been named in separate worker's compensation claims stating that long-term
  chemical exposure has caused physical and mental damage, the Gainesville
  Sun reported.The two claims were filed with state Department of Labor and
  Employment Security offices in Gainesville and Jacksonville.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>Three men -- Jesse Nash, Gary Pittman and Clinton Vann -- claim that
  exposure to chemicals used at the White Springs plant has caused them illness
  and prevents them from working.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>PCS Phosphate bought Occidental's plant in Oct. of 1995.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The men are asking to be declared permanently and totally disabled
  allowing them to collect the highest amount of worker's compensation. They
  say they suffer from symptoms that include severe muscle weakness, memory
  loss and respiratory problems.
</DL>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor4554486"></A></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor4554486">DEP to seek new permits for Rodman project</A></H3>

<DL>
  <DD>PUTNAM COUNTY--(EnviroWorld)-- The Florida Department of Environmental
  Protection will have to resubmit its request to obtain permits to drain
  the Rodman Reservoir, the Gainesville Sun reported.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The permit application was questioned because it did not conform to
  the general permit application requirements. The DEP will file an individual
  permit request which allows for water quality rules to be waived temporarily.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The Ocklawaha River was dammed in the 1960s in preparation for the
  Cross-Florida Barge Canal. The DEP wants to remove the dam to restore water
  flow to the river and return the area to its natural state of floodplain.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>Some residents oppose draining the reservoir due to its popularity
  as a fishing spot. Opponents challenged the permit last year, leading to
  administrative hearings on the project.
</DL>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor4556644"></A></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor4556644">St. Petersburg considers regional utility</A></H3>

<DL>
  <DD>ST. PETERSBURG--(EnviroWorld)-- The City of St. Petersburg is still
  considering whether to become a member of the proposed regional water utility,
  the St. Petersburg Times reported. Pinellas County Commissioner Steve Seibert
  appeared before the council on Thursday to lead a discussion of the plan.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The city council voted to continue more detailed discussions on how
  the regional water utility would work.
</DL>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor4558008"></A></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor4558008">Clinton pushes for penny tax on sugar; opens
door for bullet train</A></H3>

<DL>
  <DD>WASHINGTON--(EnviroWorld)-- President Clinton announced his proposed
  budget on Thursday which includes a penny-a-pound tax on sugar to help
  raise $35 million a year to restore the Florida Everglades, the Miami Herald
  reported.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The administration is also proposing a 163 percent increase in federal
  spending for Everglades and Florida Bay restoration. It wants to spend
  $331 million to buy land, increase restoration projects and fund environmental
  research for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The Clinton administration's proposed budget also includes a plan to
  loan money to states that develop a transportation plan of national significance,
  the Miami Herald reported in a related story. The plan could provide Florida
  with the opening it needs for the construction of a high speed train between
  Tampa, Orlando and Miami.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>Florida wants the federal government to pitch in $300 million towards
  the project and agree to back the bonds needed to build the train.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>If Congress backs the project and the Florida Legislature agrees to
  commit $6.5 billion over the next 40 years, the Florida Overland eXpress
  hopes to have Miami-Orlando service by 2004 and a Tampa connection by 2006.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>Florida Transportation Secretary Ben Watts says that if the federal
  government does not back it, he will &quot;pull the plug&quot; on the project.<A
  NAME="anchor78858"></A>
</DL>

<H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor78858">PEER suit against Army Corps may be settled</A></H3>

<DL>
  <DD>WASHINGTON D.C.--(EnviroWorld)--The Army Corps of Engineers has made
  a settlement offer in the suit filed 1/29 by the Florida Keys Citizens
  Coalition and by Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility., according
  to the Holland &amp; Knight Daily Environmental Report. The plaintiffs
  have alleged that the Corps has failed to enforce wetlands laws in the
  Keys.
</DL>
</BODY>
</HTML>
