er plans to help businesses cut through red tape as well as her  views about a recent survey by a national watchdog group, the St. Petersburg  Times reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>At the Senate Committee on Governmental Reform and Oversight, Wetherell  referred to a recent survey by Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility   as a &quot;cheap shot&quot; that was &quot;full of innuendo.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>In the PEER, survey many employees claimed that the DEP is more concerned  with protecting the powerful than the environment. Half of those surveyed  also said that polluters are often influential in DEP policy, and nearly  half said the agency doesn't rigidly enforce environmental laws.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Wetherell took Wednesday's gathering, which called on several agency  heads to report ways state bureaucrats could benefit business, as a chance  to criticize some of her employees.  She said that her aims at helping  both businesses and the environment have been misunderstood and the survey  points to the bothersome fact that the DEP has &quot;some employees who  don't believe they work for the public.&quot;   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Wetherell said the survey showed there was a &quot;communication breakdown&quot;  at the DEP and that she plans to &quot;provide a management communication  plan to ensure that these rumors that are flying around will stop.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Wednesday was the first time Wetherell had commented publicly on the  PEER survey's findings, which were released last month.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor429118"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor429118"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Santa Fe River is Alachua County'sbest wildlife habitat</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE--(EnviroWorld)--According to a recent study by an environmental  consulting firm, the woods surrounding the upper Santa Fe River are the  most important wildlife habitat area in Alachua County, the Gainesville  Sun reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The study, commissioned by the Alachua County Department of Growth  Management, evaluated 47 natural areas, excluding government-owned conservation  lands, and ranked Santa Fe at the top of the list. While earlier studies  only evaluated uplands, the new study incorporated more areas, including  wetlands and commercial pine forests, into its ranking.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Although the study was not driven by a particular policy or program,  it will be a good tool for ordering natural areas for purchase, a local  land acquisition supporter said.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Alice Reuman, a senior planner in the Department of Growth Management,  said the study will be useful for decision making within county government  by providing &quot;a biological basis for any action the county might want  to take to protect its natural resources.&quot;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor431258"></A><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor431258"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Collier County leaders unhappyover loss of water board representative</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>COLLIER COUNTY -- (EnviroWorld) --  Collier County leaders are upset  that Gov. Chiles did not appoint anyone from the county to the governing  board of the South Florida Water Management District, the Naples Daily  News reported.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Former board member and Collier resident Valerie Boyd said she would  ask Gov. Chiles to change the rules in order to require that one of the  district's nine board seats be filled by a board member of Collier County's  Big Cypress Basin.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The current law requires that one board member be appointed from Collier,  Lee, Charlotte, or Hendry counties. Bill Hammond, a Lee County resident,  has been selected. Hammond's connections to the Collier environmental community  include his position on the board of the Naples-based Conservancy of Southwest  Florida, and on the board of the CREW Trust.  Hammond expressed his assurance  Tuesday that Collier County will maintain a strong voice on the water district  governing board.      <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Pending the approval of the Florida Senate during the upcoming legislative  session, the new board members will take their seats at the water board's  March meeting.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor432953"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor432953"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Ruling favors Miami Beach inbattle over restoration project</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>MIAMI BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- A two-year-old court battle between  Miami Beach and Golden Beach may have ended in favor of Miami Beach, the  Miami Herald reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>A judge's recent decision will permit the Army Corps of Engineers to  begin a beach restoration project to provide sand to Miami's withering  beaches.  Golden Beach has long sought to prevent the initiation of this  project, fearing damage to the reefs to due to excessive digging.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>In adherence to the judge's decision, no dredging may begin until all  precautions to protect the reef are in effect.  Golden Beach officials  are now considering whether or not to file another appeal.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;</DL><P><A NAME="anchor434229"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor434229"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Tallahassee editorial: Wetherellneeds to listen</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- An editorial in the Feb. 5 Tallahassee  Democrat provided advice to Department of Environmental Protection Secretary  Virginia Wetherell: &quot;listen better.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The  editorial states that, despite reliability problems, the recent  employee survey by Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility made  at least one salient point: the appearance of political influence persists  at the department.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;Dueling philosophies may well be at play (in causing fallout  among some DEP employees). But 400 to 800 demoralized employees -- many  of them technicians and scientists -- can paralyze an agency. The worst  thing Wetherell could do would be to try to discredit, underestimate or  even undermine those who believe the agency is faltering as natural landscapes  disappear.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;What she must do is listen better ... to the disaffected front  line. To do otherwise would be to ignore all recent trends toward excellence  in management that focus on consensus, empowerment and respect for employee's  knowledge.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor435864"></A><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor435864"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Opponents to Keys Sanctuarybelieve in government, industry conspiracy</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Opponents to the formation of a Keys  Marine Sanctuary are spreading what they claim is evidence of a plot to  buy all private land in the island chain and convert it into a Walt Disney  owned theme park, the Gainesville Sun reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The evidence includes stories for the New York Times magazine and ABC-TV's  &quot;20/20&quot; that were never aired, but which are being illegally  circulated in South Florida.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Those stories investigate the claims of Keys residents who say they  were strong armed into selling their land to the Nature Conservancy. When  they refused to sell, criminal pollution charges were quickly filed against  them by Monroe County law enforcement officers.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Representatives of the government agencies and corporations accused  of participating in the conspiracy said there was no truth to the reports.  But Peter Anderson, secretary-general of the Keys' separatist group, the  Conch Republic, said that enough circumstantial evidence existed to warrant  an investigation.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;There appears to be an awful lot of smoke, and it seems prudent  to see if there's a fire,&quot; he said.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor437349"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor437349"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>UF to dispose of deadly chemical</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- A 20-pound cylinder of pentaborane,  discovered last year in the University of Florida chemistry department,  will be disposed of locally, unless someone wants to buy it, the Gainesville  Sun reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>University, federal, military, and local officials all met Wednesday  to figure out what to do with the extremely hazardous substance. They decided  to remove the chemical from its storage place in the Austin Cary Forest  March 6, and hydrolyze it. Details of the plan must still be worked out.  The chemical could also possibly be purchased, if researchers come forward,  but officials said they would not ship the chemical to any distant hazardous  waste disposal sites.<BR>  </DL><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
