business for about $400 million, operations  in France, Spain and Austria and other, non-specified assets and real estate.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>WMX also approved the return of its former name, Waste Management Inc.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor523470"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor523470">Ship grounds on Keys reef</A></H3><DL>  <DD>FLORIDA KEYS--(EnviroWorld)-- A 600-foot ship remains grounded off  the Florida Keys as Coast Guard officials work to free the ship without  causing further damage to the reef it is grounded on, the Miami Herald  reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Houston, a Transportacion Maritima Mexicana container vessel, ran  aground at about 11:45 p.m. Sunday, but waited about six hours before alerting  the Coast Guard to their situation. Federal law requires ships that run  aground to notify the Coast Guard immediately.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The ship is not leaking fuel or cargo, but is carrying hazardous materials.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The ship, on route from New Orleans to Valencia, Spain, was in an area  forbidden to ships larger than 160 feet. The area is marked on nautical  charts. </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor525233"></A><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor525233">EPA offers solution to pentaborane issue</A></H3><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE--(EnviroWorld)-- The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency  is offering to help the University of Florida dispose of 20 pounds of pentaborane,  a deadly and highly explosive chemical that has been stored at the university  since the 1940s, the Gainesville Sun reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The EPA is prepared to spend $150,000 to transport the chemical to  the Austin Cary Forest where it will be neutralized, said Christopher Militscher,  an EPA scientist and member of the National Pentaborane Task Force.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>UF has had several meetings since November about neutralizing the chemical  which explodes when it comes in contact with air. Local residents have  expressed some fears over the chemical being neutralized locally.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Gainesville Fire Chief Richard Williams has suggested that the chemical  be shipped to either Redstone Arsenal in Huntsville, Ala. or Edwards Air  Force Base in Calif., both of which have large stores of the chemical.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Militscher said both of those facilities have been issued violations  by the government and are forbidden from accepting any more pentaborane.  </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor526727"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor526727">DEP to have exhibit at state fair</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)-- The Florida Department of Environmental Protection  will have its first exhibit at the Florida State Fair February 6-17 in  Tampa.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The 15,000 square foot environmental exhibit will feature a walk through  model of an environmentally-sensitive house called &quot;Green House.&quot;  It will be complete with an energy efficient car and the yard will showcase  native plants.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The perimeter of the exhibit will include displays that  present Florida's  environmental issues and fragile ecosystems.   <DD><BR>  </DL><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
