<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT> <BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><H5><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></H5><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><B><A HREF="#anchor338406">Softmud: press reports on Everglades phosphorusare inaccurate</A></B></FONT></P><DL>  <DD>WEST PALM BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- by Mitchell Gibbs -- Reports that  the South Florida Water Management District is retreating from data on  phosphorus reductions in the Everglades are &quot;confused,&quot; according  to a district spokesman.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Feb. 2, the Washington Post reported that the district had failed to  take heavy rainfall into account when it determined runoff from sugar farms  showed a 68 percent decline in phosphorus. According to the Post, Linda  Lindstrom, the district's resource assessment division director, wrote  in a Nov. 14 memo that phosphorus declines were probably related more to  dilution from rainfall than from the pollution management practices of  farmers.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>And Feb.3, Holland and Knights Daily Environment Report stated that  the water management district had &quot;announced&quot; such a mistake.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>But Softmud spokesman John Neuharth, said no such announcement had  been made, and that the district stood by it's original data .  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;What (the Post) is referring to is a memo talking about phosphorus  concentrations in the Everglades National Park and the Water Conservation  Areas,&quot; Neuharth said. &quot;This is not a retraction on what we said  (about phosphorus reductions from farms runoff).&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Neuharth said water quality data on runoff leaving the Everglades Agricultural  Area (EAA) did take rainfall into account, and that the district still  attributed last year's 68 percent decline to better farm management practices.  The data that Lindstrom was referring to, he said, came from samples collected  alone the Tamiami Canal. According to Neuharth, the memo's point was that  the improved water quality of agricutural area runoff could not be correlated  with water quality changes in the Everglades National Park and the Loxahatchee  National Wildlife Refuge.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The district's announcement of the reductions last summer was a keystone  in arguments by the sugar industry that it was no longer polluting the  Everglades. While the district's report on water quality in the Everglades  Agricultural Area cautioned that &quot;any data evaluation conducted at  this time would provide inconclusive and possibly misleading interpretations,&quot;  Softmud's press release did not mention any specific problems with the  data, and most newspapers simply reported the 68 percent decrease.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Softmud executive director Samuel Poole told the Post, &quot;Trying  to take a year's worth of information and declare victory on that basis  is probably not a very sage thing to do.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Neuharth said that quote was accurate, and added that a longer period  of testing on runoff from the Everglades Agricultural Area was necessary  before conclusions could be drawn.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3762929"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3762929"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Industry preparing for battleagainst ozone rules</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- Industry groups opposed to new EPA rules  tightening limits on ozone pollution are investing heavily in campaigns  to fight the proposals, the Washington Post reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>According to reports in the trade press, groups are spending $5 million  in an attack on rules they say will cost more than $6 billion. More interesting  than the spending, are statements that have been attributed to various  industry spokesmen.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>For example, an unidentified oil lobbyist was quoted in a National  Journal article as saying that people should protect themselves from ozone  pollution, &quot;...avoid jogging,&quot; he said. &quot;Asthmatic kids  need not go out and ride their bicycles.&quot;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3764163"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3764163"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Stauffer to resume phosphorouscleanup</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TARPON SPRINGS--(EnviroWorld)--Stauffer Management Co. officials announced  tentative plans on Monday to resume the removal of crude phosphorous from  a plant on their property at the Pasco County line, the St. Petersburg  Times reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The process of transferring the crude phosphorous was abandoned in  October because of residents' health concerns over the operation.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Monday's meeting,which was attended by Stauffer officials, governments  officials and a few residents, left skeptics wondering how the company  would handle problems that could arise during the process. In response,  Stauffer said it will offer a telephone number for information as well  as monitor the air for changes in the area. Details regarding the public  notification system in the case of an emergency have yet to be worked out.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The 160-acre Superfund site is contaminated with 500,000 tons of carcinogenic  waste that had been dumped there for three decades before the plant was  closed in 1981. However, phosphorous is the most immediate hazard because  it can burst into flames.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Stauffer plans to issue a draft work plan to community representatives  during the week of Feb. 17 and then call another public meeting regarding  the matter.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3765828"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3765828"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Softmud gets new board members</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>SOUTH FLORIDA -- (EnviroWorld) -- Three new members to the governing  board of the South Florida Water Management District were appointed on  Monday by Gov. Lawton Chiles, the Miami Herald reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Parkland lawyer and Democratic party finance chairman Mitchell Berger,  Fort Pierce citrus grower Michael Minton, and Vera Carter, a former member  of the Orange County Commission, are the newl members.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3767337"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3767337"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>St. Johns River Water ManagementDistrict initiates web site</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>PALATKA -- (EnviroWorld) -- To keep the public informed on the District's  work, a web site is now available for internet users. The web site, http://sjr.state.fl.us,  will be updated and enhanced regularly to make as much information accessible  to the public as possible.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3768569"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3768569"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Beach driving rules predictedto decrease toll revenues</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>DAYTONA BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- Due to new restrictions<B> </B>on  beach driving, Volusia county officials are predicting a steady decline  in toll revenues, the Orlando Sentinel reported. Last year, beach driving  restrictions were approved by county officials in order to increase protection  of sea turtles and other wildlife. The new rules, which include a driving  ban on nine miles of the beach, did not take effect until the end of the  peak tourist season.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>County officials are now wondering if beachgoers will continue to pay  daily tolls or buy yearly passes in order to drive on the beach. Many officials  predict that beachgoers will opt to avoid the tolls completely and take  advantage of the free parking in the no-driving areas. Revenue from tolls  and annual passes is projected to reach only $2.7 million this year. Last  years, the county collected $3.5 million.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3769911"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3769911"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Fungus threatens leatherleafferns and farmers' profits</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>PIERSON -- (EnviroWorld) -- A fungus that was unknown in the U.S. three  years ago is now reportedly wiping out 30 percent of the leatherleaf ferns  on some farms, the Tampa Tribune reported.<B> </B>The fungus called Anthracnose  is believed by scientists to have been imported from Central America, and  since mid-1993, it has appeared on six of 10 Volusia, Lake and Putnam county  farms.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Leatherleaf ferns normally make up 72 percent of revenue for the fern  industry, and are instrumental to the cut-flower industry's biggest holidays:  Valentine's Day, Easter and Mother's Day. Farmers fear that unless the  fungus is eradicated, it will prove devastating to their bank accounts.  Growers and researchers are now experimenting with more frequent applications  of fungicide, as well as watering and improved ventilation in order to  kill the fungus and prevent it from spreading.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3771677"></A><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3771677"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Freighter crunches agroundat coral sanctuary near Key West</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>MIAMI-- (EnviroWorld) -- A 600-foot freighter, enroute from New Orleans  to Spain, ran aground Monday more than two miles inside the Florida Keys  National Marine Sanctuary, The Associated Press reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>It is unclear how much damage the world's thrid largest reef may have  sustained, and biologists cannot fully assess the damage until the ship  has been removed from the site.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The damaged section, on a shoal south of Sugarloaf Key and 15 miles  from Key West, is covered with 20 percent live tissue and home to soft  coral, stony coral and sponges.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>It has not yet been determined how the container vessel Houston, which  was traveling at 20 mph at the time of the accident, had gotten so far  off course. The Houston was traveling in an area forbidden to ships larger  than 160 feet, according to a Coast Guard report.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;It's absolutely nowhere close to where it should have been,&quot;  said Florida Keys Marine Sanctuary Project Manager June Craddick. Craddick  said that the boat was too large and way too deep into the protected area.  The nearest shipping lane to the sanctuary is at least two miles away.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Although there were several dents in the ship's hull, there was nothing  to indicate the possibility of a spillage of the 2,500 tons of fuel and  lubricating oil the ship was carrying for its own use.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The sanctuary was created in 1990 after three freighters ran aground  the reef in only 18 days.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3773408"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3773408"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Weather blamed in Lake Dorafish kill</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>LAKE DORA--Oxygen depletion following several cloudy and cool days  last week may be the cause of a fish kill that left thousands of dead bass,  crappie and catfish along the shores of Lake Dora Monday, The Associated  Press reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Sam McKinney, regional fishery biologist with the Florida Game and  Fresh Water Fish Commission, has put the numbers of dead fish in the &quot;tens  of thousands&quot; and said that residents are complaining of the foul  odor the die-off has caused. He said that it was a significant but not  a major fish kill.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>McKinney has labeled the weather, and not any toxic substance, the  culprit in the incident. The change in weather depleted oxygen in the lake  and then suffocated the fish, he said.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>McKinney said that most of the fish died last week and sank to the  lake's bottom, but it was not until the weather warmed up that they started  popping to the surface of the lake and depositing themselves upon the residential  canals lining the shore.</DL><P><BR></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
