veness  of her leadership.&quot;</DL><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor920909"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor920909"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>EPA considers break for smallbusiness' emissions</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Environmental Protection Agency's  Office of Air Quality Planning and Standards (OAQPS) may issue a rule that  exempts some small businesses from more stringent emissions rules that   are being planned, according to the Daily Environment Report.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Part of the reasoning behind the move is to simplify estimates of potential  emissions as  the EPA goes about the rulemaking process. OAQPS's Tim Smith  said, &quot;This is a segment of industry that tends to operate well below  their theoretical potential, or their theoretical potential is very hard  to determine.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The agency is likely to issue the rule for small businesses before  it tackles more controversial rules for larger sources. The small business  rule may be in the  form of emissions caps that blanket industries by broad  classes.</DL><P><A NAME="anchor922208"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor922208"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Nationwide beverage containerdeposit bill introduced in Congress</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- Citing the success of deposit laws in  increasing recycling rates in individual states, Sen. James Jeffords (R-VT)  has introduced a bill mandating a 10 cent deposit on beverage containers  in any state that recycles less than 70 percent of its containers, according  to the Daily Environment Report.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The National Soft Drink Association opposes the bill and the Container  Recycling Institute supports it.</DL><P><A NAME="anchor923376"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor923376"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>EPA asks for extension on newclean air rules</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- Environmental Protection Agency Administrator  Carol Browner will seek court approval to extend deadlines for new air  quality rules, the New York Times reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Browner wrote of the upcoming request in a letter to Ohio Governor  George Voinovich -- one of several state governors opposing the new rules.  The EPA is under an Arizona federal district court order to review its  regulations under the Clean Air Act. Last November, on deadline, the agency  announced rule proposals for tougher ozone standards and for a previously  unregulated class of air pollutants -- fine particles smaller than 2.5  microns diameter.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Browner wrote that she will seek a two-month extension, allowing more  public comment on the proposed rules, and pushing formal issuance of the  rules back to August of this year.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Industry groups have come out in strong opposition to the new rules,  saying they can't bear the expense. State and local officials are sharply  divided on the issue nationwide, especially because the pollutants are  carried long distances from their original sources.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Despite intensive scientific review of the proposed rules, Congressional  leaders have indicated they may try to use their newly gained veto powers  that apply to major federal regulations once the air rules are issued.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor924516"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor924516"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Brownfields bill would offertax cut</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- Businesses that clean up and develop  in brownfields -- areas of historic contamination -- would be eligible  for part of $2 billion in tax incentives under a senate bill introduced  Jan. 30, according to the Daily Environment Report.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The bill is sponsored by Sen. Carol Moseley Brown (D-IL) and has bipartisan  support. In addition to the tax incentive, it creates 20 &quot;empowerment  zones&quot; and 80 &quot;enterprise communities&quot; nationwide -- areas  qualifying for restoration and redevelopment aid.</DL><P><A NAME="anchor925663"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor925663"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Industries dropping from EPAprogram</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Environmental Protection Agency's  Common Sense Initiative program is on its heels as it receives widespread  criticism and the loss of two major industry participants, according to  Inside EPA Weekly Report.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>EPA Administrator Carol Browner started the program in 1993 and labeled  it a prime component of regulatory reform at the agency. But the automobile  and petroleum industries are withdrawing from the program, complaining  the program has been ineffective and would work better for small businesses.  The General Accounting Office is also reviewing the program.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>EPA officials said new industries are expected to enter the program  soon, adding to the four remaining subcommittees: iron and steel, computers  and electronics, metal finishing, and printers.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor926686"></A></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor926686"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Researchers: turtle tumors causedby man </FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- University of Florida scientists have  reported that greatest threat to the endangered green turtle is a tumor  called fibropapilloma that is probably caused by chemical runoff, The Associated  Press reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The tumor attaches itself inside the turtle's body, then grows until  it destroys the animal's organs and tissue. It is believed to be caused  by a viral infection, and researchers with the Archie Carr Center for Sea  Turtle Research said that damage to turtle immune systems, caused by chemical  runoff, has allowed the disease to become an epidemic.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>As many as 75 percent of green turtles in Florida Bay are believed  to have the tumor, and more than 50 percent in the southern Indian River  may be infected. Scientists first discovered the tumor in 1938, and noticed  the beginnings of an epidemic as early as a decade ago.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>For more information, visit the research center's website at http://nervm.nerdc.ufl.edu/~accstr/accstr.html.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor928297"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor928297"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Drums of toxins dumped in Dade</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>MIAMI -- (EnviroWorld) -- State and local environmental officials cordoned  off an area on Sunday in Southwest Dade County where 37 drums of toxic  chemicals were found, the Miami Herald reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Labels on the 55-gallon drums indicated that the leaking contents were  highly toxic. While officials must conduct tests before they will know  for sure, the chemicals may include methanol, xylene, benzyl phythlate  and a uralkyd resin solution.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;It's serious enough that you don't  want to breathe what's out  there until we find out exactly what is there,&quot; DEP spokeswoman Karin  Shoemaker told the Herald.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor929508"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor929508"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Audubon's Everglades Directorto speak</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>NAPLES -- (EnviroWorld) -- Stuart Strahl, the National Audubon Society's  Everglades Ecosystem Restoration Campaign Executive Director, will speak  at the Conservancy of Southwest Florida auditorium at 7:30 p.m. Tuesday,  the Naples Daily News reported. The auditorium is located at 1450 Merrihue  Dr., off Goodlette-Frank road.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor930682"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor930682"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Swiftmud chairman admits mistakein marketing</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>BROOKSVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Attorney Roy G. Harrell sent out letters  last December soliciting business from the governments of Pinellas County  and St. Petersburg. The trouble with Harrell's marketing plan is that he  is chairman of the Southwest Florida Water Management District, which is  currently involved in a lawsuit with those local governments.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Saying that he belatedly realized the letters could be perceived as  improper, Harrell officially withdrew the letters last week in faxes sent  to the two government's utilities directors, the St. Petersburg Times reported.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor931777"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor931777"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>More wildlife problems foundin Fenholloway</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>PERRY -- (EnviroWorld) -- Researcher at Florida A&amp;M University  have reported finding deformed aquatic bugs in the Fenholloway River, the  St. Petersburg Times reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Sowbugs and mayflies from the river had deformities on their gills,  while the same bugs from the nearby Econfina River had no such defects,  FAMU entomologist Manuel Pescador told the Times.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Other scientists have found female fish in the Fenholloway with male  sex organs. Scientists believe that pollution from the Buckeye Florida  pulp mill may be the root cause  of the animals' malformations.</DL><P><A NAME="anchor932941"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor932941"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>St. Pete agrees to allow borrowpit near Pasco wellfield</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>ST. PETERSBURG -- (EnviroWorld) -- Permits are likely to be approved  for a 21-acre borrow pit located near a Pasco County wellfield, now that  the property owners have agreed to more extensive groundwater monitoring,  the St. Petersburg Times reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Southwest Florida Water Management District had already approved  the permit when St. Petersburg stepped in with concerns about the possible  effects to the wellfield, which supplies the city with as much as 40 percent  of its pumping capacity. The Pasco County Commission approved the pit last  March.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Use of the pit for fill dirt will require that it be pumped dry, creating  the potential for lowered groundwater levels in surrounding areas. The  land's owners agreed to limits on daily pumping and will monitor groundwater  conditions twice a month. The fill dirt is for a nearby 780-acre housing  development.</DL><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor934238"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor934238"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Dantzler may run for governor</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- State Sen. Rick Dantzler (D-Winter  Haven) is considering a run for governor in 1998, the Tampa Tribune reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Dantzler has discussed the idea with Gov. Lawton Chiles, but said he  would wait until after this spring's legislative session to make an official  decision. Dantzler most visible role was as chairman of the Senate Natural  Resources Committee from 1992 to 1996. Dantzler said his moderateness could  help mend the partisan rift in the state legislature.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor936045"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor936045"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>IT announces third quarter results</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TORRANCE, Calif. -- (EnviroWorld) --International Technology Corporation  has reported its third fiscal quarter financial results, which ended Dec.  27, 1996.  According to the report, IT increased its operating income over  the previous quarter, indicating continued operational improvements based  on the company's recent restructuring.  Revenues for the third quarter  were $92.5 million compared with $104.9 million for the same quarter in  the prior year.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor937317"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor937317"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Hi-Rise gets oldest chute company</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>MIAMI -- (EnviroWorld) -- Hi-Rise Recycling Systems, Inc. has agreed  to acquire Wilkinson Company, Inc. of Stow, OH, the oldest manufacturer  of trash, recycling and linen chutes for high-rise apartment buildings,  condominiums and hotels, as well as line of architectural products.  The  74-year-old manufacturing company, which is considered the standard in  the new construction industry, has approximately 65 distributors throughout  the U.S., Canada, and foreign markets as well.  This is Hi-Rise's third  major acquisition since February 1995.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor938589"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor938589"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Malcolm Pirnie passes away</FONT></B></A></P><P>WINTER PARK -- (EnviroWorld) -- Malcolm Pirnie Jr., former chairman ofMalcolm Pirnie Inc., one of the nation's leading environmental engineeringfirms, passed away last month at age 79.  Chairman of the firm from 1970to 1987, he semi-retired in Winter Park where he remained active in engineeringfrom the Florida offices.  The firm has been in Florida since the 1920s,and is headquartered in White Plains, N.Y.</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor939954"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor939954"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>SEBC meeting is planned in twoweeks</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Invitations for the SEBC Annual Pre-Legislative  Session Breakfast Meeting have been mailed.  The meeting will be held in  Tallahassee on Feb. 11 from 7:15 to 9:30.  During the meeting Senator Jack  Latvala (R-Palm Harbor), also Chairman of the Senate Natural Resources  Committee, and Representative Rob Wallace (R-Tampa), also Chairman of the  House Rules and Regulations Committee will speak.  </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><P><BR></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
