<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT> <BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><H5><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></H5><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><B><A HREF="#anchor338406">Alachua cement plant plans solidifying</A></B></FONT></P><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- A cement plant that some local residents  have bitterly fought has cleared a final hurdle to construction, the Gainesville  Sun reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The site plan for the Florida Rock Industries portland cement plant  was approved unanimously on Thursday by the county's Development Review  Committee. While an appeal is still possible, it appears that construction  on the plant, near Newberry, can begin anyway.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Staff with the County Department of Environmental Protection had requested  the plant's emissions be monitored for dioxin in order to detect the burning  of hazardous waste, which would violate the plant's land-use permit. The  plant will burn tires, but company officials say no dioxins will be emitted.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Citizens also want emissions of fine particles to be monitored, in  anticipation of new EPA rules on such emissions later this year. Company  officials have been reluctant to comply with those requests, but indicated  they may agree to some additional monitoring.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor619491"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor619491"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Transformer blows up near troublednuke plant</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>CRYSTAL RIVER -- (EnviroWorld) -- As if having the most troubled nuclear  reactor in the Southeast weren't enough, a 400-ton, oil-filled transformer  blew up Thursday at Florida Power Corp.'s Crystal River complex, the St.  Petersburg Times reported. The explosion was felt at the complex's nuclear  reactor, three-quarters of a mile away.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>No injuries were reported, but one coal-fired generator had to be shut  down. It was not reported whether the transformer contained hazardous polychlorinated  biphenyls, or PCB's.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The incident may bring a low-level citation for Florida Power, because  the company failed to immediately report the incident as an &quot;unusual  event&quot; to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Wednesday, NRC officials gave the nuclear plant a &quot;category 2&quot;  designation, a serious label meaning the plant is being closely monitored  by the NRC. The Gainesville Sun reported that the commission is considering  further penalties against Florida Power for design problems in the reactor's  backup generators, and for security violations.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>NRC spokesman Roger Hannah told the Sun, &quot;You can tell which power  plants have had the poorest performance by how thick my file is. I've got  a big file on Crystal River.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Despite the reactor's problems, officials affirmed that it was not  a public health threat.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor621070"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor621070"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>State rejects Jax manatee protectionplan</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>JACKSONVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- The state Department of Environmental  Protection rejected Jacksonville's proposal to keep it's boating speed-zone  buffers at 300 feet, asking for 900 foot buffers instead, the Florida Times-Union  reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The current slow-speed zones, which have been in place since 1992,  allow boats to create no more than a minimal wake within 300 feet of shore.  Duval County is one of 13 Florida counties under a 1989 mandate to improve  its manatee protection efforts. In 1995, the City Council did approve a  plan which included 900 foot buffers, but would not agree to DEP-requested  revisions. Last November, the Jacksonville Waterways Commission recommended  that the city stay with its 300-foot protection zones, despite contrary  advice from the city attorney. Officials predicted the issue will ultimately  be decided in court.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Two manatees were killed in Duval County in 1996, both as a result  of crushing injuries.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor622663"></A><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor622663"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Keys visitors place high priorityon environmental quality</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>KEY WEST -- (EnviroWorld) -- A poll of tourists in the Florida Keys  found disappointment among return visitors for the decline of living coral,  water quality, and natural areas, the Miami Herald reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The two-year study, released Thursday, was conducted by the Tourist  Development Council, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Association,  and the Nature Conservancy. More than 8,100 tourists were surveyed. The  study also estimated that 66 percent of Keys visitors swim, dive or snorkel.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>In 1996, 2.54 million people visited the Keys and spent $1.2 billion.  A Nature Conservancy spokesman also recommended that Monroe County planners  add the area's 50,000 daily visitors to the resident population of 80,000  when making infrastructure improvement decisions.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor624116"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor624116"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Red-tape hampers protest ofwaste pipeline</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TAMPA -- (EnviroWorld) -- Citizens concerned about the effects of the  Buckeye Cellulose plant's waste pipeline are complaining that it's very  difficult to bend the Department of Environmental Protection's ear, the  Tampa Tribune reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>To challenge the first permit for the pipeline, which deals with wetland  construction projects, citizens must go through the administrative hearing  process, a complex procedure that takes legal expertise. But a DEP spokesman  said that, because a second permit had to be issued for wastewater discharge,  a February public hearing would be held at which informal concerns could  be aired.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The pipeline is the plant's proposed solution to its current practice  of pumping toxic waste into the Fenholloway River, which is losing its  industrial designation. The Perry, Florida plant has long been associated  with degradation of the river ecosystem, and is being blamed for the aberrant  reproductive organs present in the river's fish.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Critics of the pipeline, which would send the waste directly to the  Gulf of Mexico, say damage could be done to fragile estuaries and to endangered  sealife there.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The DEP contact for the pipeline issue is Vince Seibold at 904-448-4330.</DL><P><BR></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
