ted cost of at least $700,000. About $400,000 still needs  to be raised for the project, which will be headed by the Surface Water  Improvement and Management division of the Southwest Florida Water Management  District.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The work is expected to take two to three years and will involve the  creation of wetlands such as tidal pools and a new waterway from the Manatee  River.</DL><P><A NAME="anchor3022428"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3022428"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Crystal River nuke plant puton NRC watch list</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>CRYSTAL RIVER -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Nuclear Regulatory Commission  placed the Florida Power Corp. Crystal River nuclear plant on its &quot;watch  list&quot; because of safety shortcomings, the Miami Herald reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>In all, six reactors were added to the NRC's list of reactors requiring  special scrutiny. The list now contains 14 plants.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Problems in the Crystal River plant have been traced to one of its  emergency diesel generators, which is part of the emergency core cooling  system. The generators are supposed to activate in the event of a loss  of off-site power. The plant has been inoperative since Sept. 2 and isn't  expected to resume operation until the end of 1997.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3023674"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3023674"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Bill endorsed by EPA chiefto clean &quot;Brownfield&quot; pollution</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- A Senate bill proposing a program for  cleaning up &quot;Brownfield&quot; sites was endorsed by Environmental  Protection Agency Administrator Carol Browner, the Washington Post reported.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The goal of the bill is to provide financial assistance to state and  local governments to identify brownfields, and provide low interests loans  to businesses that plan to clean up the sites.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Browner and Sen. Frank Lutenberg,  who introduced the bill, said the  bill is not meant to replace the Superfund program.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;(W)e have a long way to go before we get a (Superfund) bill that  enjoys bipartisan support, and that can be signed into law,&quot; Lautenburg  said. &quot;We can't wait.&quot;</DL><P><A NAME="anchor3025016"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3025016"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Captive panthers to be releasedin Big Cypress National Preserve</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>MIAMI --(EnviroWorld)--Two male Florida panthers, captured six years  ago as kittens and studied in a breeding program, will be released today,  the Miami Herald reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The two cats, to be among only 30 to 50 Florida panthers still remaining  in the wild, will be released in Big Cypress National Preserve near four  big female cats in hopes they will  breed and adapt to living on their  own.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>There are no records of a big cat ever returning to the wild, after  being raised in captivity, and learning to fend for itself.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The panthers, who were raised for the breeding experiment at Gilman  Paper Co.'s White Oak Conservation Center in Yulee, will be sedated and  transported by truck today to Big Cypress, said Dennis Jordan, a coordinator  for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service's panther program. Biologists will  monitor the panthers using radio transmitters attached to their collars.</DL><P><A NAME="anchor3026590"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3026590"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Experts seek answers to newdeformed frog reports</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD> WASHINGTON--(EnviroWorld)--Scientists and researchers from several  states and federal agencies are hoping to uncover the mystery behind the  deformed frogs found in Wisconsin and Minnesota last fall, the Washington  Post reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>After extensive media coverage about the frogs in those two states,  deformed frogs have been found in nearly 12 other states and even as far  away as Japan.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Gilman Veith, associate director for the Environmental Protection Agency's  ecology division, said that there are many possible explanations for the  deformities but that data collection is the first step towards finding  a cause.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The EPA will be monitoring amphibian and reptile populations in several  of the nation's national parks as well as studying the distribution and  extent of the problem across the country.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>David Hoppe, a herpetologist at the University of Minnesota, will begin  testing deformed northern leopard frogs in a controlled environment to  determine whether limb deformities would continue be passed along to offspring.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Preliminary findings at the National Wildlife Health Center in Madison,  Wisconsin indicate parasites as a possible cause of the frog deformities,  but no other possibilities have been ruled out. </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor3028146"></A></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></FONT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor3028146"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Songbirds not singing oversun-grown coffee</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON--(EnviroWorld)--Scientists at the Smithsonian Migratory  Bird Center say that the removal of shade trees by coffee growers in Central  and South America is responsible for a decrease in the U.S. population  of songbirds, the Florida Times-Union reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Encouraged by a large demand for their product, coffee growers are  converting their fields to densely planted &quot;sun plantations&quot;  by removing  the forests and fruit groves where songbirds thrive during  the north's harsh winter months. Nearly half of Central and South America's  coffee growing land has been depleted of shade trees since 1978.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Although the decrease in the birds numbers is also linked to loss of  forest and grassland in the United States, many birds die or lack energy  to mate in the Spring if they are not provided shelter and food down south  during the winter months.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>While there is presently no label on coffees to designate that the  beans were grown in the shade of the songbird-friendly trees, packages  labeled &quot;bird-friendly&quot; have appeared in some specialty coffee  boutiques.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>An organization of concerned individuals, the Sustainable Coffee Coalition,  is currently working to implement a shade-labeling program. Larger coffee  companies, however, say they must be educated on the issue before making  any changes.</DL><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
