<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT> <BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><H5><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></H5><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><B><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="#anchor338406">Lawsuit to be filed against ArmyCorps over Key's permitting</A></FONT></B></P><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE--(EnviroWorld)--EXCLUSIVE--A public interest group will  tomorrow file a lawsuit against the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers that alleges  the federal agency illegally approved construction projects and ignored  federal wetlands protection laws in an array of development projects in  the Florida Keys.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>At the same time, the group, Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility,  will unveil a White Paper that cites hundreds of instances of shoddy or  purposefully lax wetland permitting and enforcement by the Corps and the  Florida Department of Transportation throughout Florida's Monroe County.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The report, titled &quot;Rotten at the Corps,&quot; states that &quot;According  to its own employees, the Army Corps of Engineers is presiding over the  destruction of the ecosystem of the Florida Keys.&quot; The report charges  that the Corps is deliberately ignoring federal law and allowing illegally  permitted development to destroy threatened and endangered habitat and  wildlife in the Keys.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The lawsuit will ask a federal judge to enforce the federal laws and  sanction the Corps for past misdeeds. The suit will be filed in U.S. District  Court in Miami tomorrow by attorney Gregg Goldfarb, on behalf of PEER and  the Florida Keys Citizen Coalition.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>PEER is made up of state and federal environmental agency employees  across the nation. The report and lawsuit count heavily on testimony by  whistleblowers currently and formerly employed by the Corps.</DL><P><A HREF="#anchor338406"><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT></A>&nbsp;</P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="#anchor338406"></A></FONT>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor164310"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="#anchor164310"></A></FONT></P><P><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="#anchor164310">Plane crashes with radioactivecargo</A></FONT></P><DL>  <DD>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)--A small plane that crashed into the Hillsborough  River yesterday morning was carrying low-level radioactive cargo, the Tampa  Tribune reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Tampa Fire Department's Hazardous Materials Team reported to the  site to find the small Cessna upside down with its tail protruding from  the water.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The boxed radioactive cargo, involving materials used in x-ray machines,  appeared to be intact when it was fished from the water by rescuers.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The fire department and Coast Guard also monitored the crash site,  where nearly 70 gallons of aviation fuel had spilled into the river.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor24620"></A></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor24620"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>West Coast re-elects Turanchikand Fischer</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>CLEARWATER--(EnviroWorld)--Two Hillsborough officials were re-elected  to the board of the West Coast Regional Water Supply Authority Monday,  the St. Petersburg Times reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Hillsborough County Commissioner Ed Turanchik was re-elected as chairman  of the board, and St. Petersburg Mayor David Fischer was re-elected vice  chairman.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Both men have been instrumental in pushing a plan to change the organization  into a utility. As a utility, West Coast would own and manage all of the  region's water resources. Also, the voting authority would be restructured  to give the three involved counties, Hillsborough, Pinellas and Pasco,  equal influence.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor25720"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor25720"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>St. Pete Times editorial blastsDEP secretary Wetherell, Gov. Lawton Chiles</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>ST. PETERSBURG--(EnviroWorld)--The main Sunday editorial in the St.  Petersburg Times blasted Florida's top environmental official and her boss,  Florida Governor Lawton Chiles, for poor environmental performance and  for criticizing unfavorable survey results that showed a large number of  state environmental officials think developers control regulatory decisions.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>More than 1200 of 3,300 Florida Department of Environmental Protection  employees returned surveys from the watchdog group Public Employees for  Environmental Responsibility. Of those responding, 200 said they have been  directed to ignore environmental laws and 350 said that staffers are reassigned  for being too tough on developers.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>DEP officials have responded that the survey is not statistically valid.  But the Times editorial stated that issue is beside the point.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;When you have 1,200 employees answer a survey and fewer than  400 say their boss should not be fired, then the statistical validity is  hardly pertinent. Florida's environmental superagency is in chaos.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>According to the Times, Florida Governor Lawton Chiles is largely responsible  for allowing DEP secretary Virginia Wetherell to&quot; turn the agencies  back on its environmental mission.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The editorial lists several black marks on Wetherell's record, then  takes Gov. Chiles to task for his appointment of the Secretary.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&quot;The pattern has been numbingly consistent in the three years  since Wetherell took charge, and it seems obvious at this point that Chiles  is pleased with what he sees. What is less obvious is how Chiles could  have appointed both Wetherell and her predecessor, Carol Browner, a tough-minded,  respected environmental leader who is now administrator of the U.S. Environmental  Protection Agency. Presumably he now considers the Browner appointment  a mistake.&quot;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>...the (PEER) survey has uncovered some deadly serious allegations.  ... No one in state government, not Chiles, not the Legislature, not the  attorney general, can afford to ignore them.&quot;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor29688"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor29688"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Chiles and cabinet to vote onKeys sanctuary management plan</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)--Gov. Lawton Chiles and the Cabinet were  urged on Monday to approve a plan managing the Florida Keys National Marine  Sanctuary, The Associated Press reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Because two-thirds of the sanctuary lies in state-controlled waters,  the joint state-federal management plan needs approval from the Cabinet.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Sen. Bob Graham said that the vote is the best chance for state and  federal officials to settle differences and ease residents' fears about  how the area would be protected from pollution.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>A vote on the issue is scheduled for today.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor31025"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor31025"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Court says no exclusive jurisdictionfor Public Service Commission</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- Last week's decision by the First District Court of  Appeals that counties could take over the Public Service Commission's regulatory  authority affects several counties, the Naples Daily News reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Collier, Sarasota, Polk, Hernando and Hillsborough had joined in the  case to argue their right to regulate utility rates for water services.  Those counties are served by Florida Water Services, the new name of Southern  States Utilities. The counties had been unhappy with earlier PSC rulings  that allowed Southern States to charge higher rates in some areas, in order  to subsidize lower rates in others. The PSC has since reversed that decision.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The company runs 149 water and sewer utilities statewide. In Collier  County, Florida Water Services runs water utilities for Marco Island and  Marco Shores.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor32555"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor32555"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Collier mulls changes in environmentaladvisory boards</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>NAPLES -- (EnviroWorld) -- Two proposals are in the air from Collier  County officials to improve the effectiveness of the county's Environmental  Policy Technical Advisory Board (EPTAB), the Naples Daily News reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The 11-member board has had problems recently getting county commissioners  to listen to its recommendations. Monday, Natural Resources director Bill  Lorenz recommended that EPTAB be given two seats on the more powerful Environmental  Advisory Board.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>But EPTAB chairman Bran Cornell countered that EPTAB should instead  be made a part of the Development Services Advisory Board -- a more powerful  board -- in order to balance that board's advocacy of development issues.  Other members of EPTAB said Cornell's proposal would simply result in gridlock  on the Development Board.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor33810"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor33810"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Alachua County may consider airpollution program</FONT></B></A></P><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Alachua County's Environmental Protection  Department has asked the Alachua County Commission to look into a local  air pollution program, the Gainesville Sun reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The local groundswell of opposition to a proposed cement plant, and  a popular petition for tougher air pollution rules, are signals that the  county should consider starting its own program to monitor and enforce  air pollution rules, according to department Director Chris Bird.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Bird said 15 other counties in the state now have programs to ensure  compliance with state and federal rules, and Alachua County's growth may  put it into a position where such a program is helpful. Such a program  would also be necessary if local air pollution rules were passed, but the  county attorney has indicated state law may prevent the passage of tougher  local regulations.<BR>  </DL><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
