ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></P>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Everybody is pushing for brownfields<BR>
legislation this year</FONT></H1>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>January 9, 1997</I></P>

<DL>
  <UL>
    <UL>
      <DL>
        <DD><B><FONT SIZE=-1>by Dave Newport, Editor</FONT></B>
        <DD>&nbsp;
      </DL>
    </UL>
  </UL>
  <DD><IMG SRC="../Images/brownfields.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="122" ALIGN=
  "LEFT" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" BORDER="1"><FONT SIZE=+4>B</FONT>rownfields
  are big business--almost. In this year's legislative session, many different
  interest groups are looking for ways to put the green in brownfields. Taxpayers
  look to be the source of the green--and businesses, property owners, local
  governments, and environmental consultants look to collect that green.
  In the process, these contaminated urban properties called brownfields
  look to green up and clean up themselves too. And it may not be an off
  color deal. The environment may profit too. 
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>On the national scene, several Florida cities are looking to cash in
  on federal brownfields monies. Ocala, Gainesville, Clearwater, Miami, and
  Jacksonville are just a few Florida governments who have applied for upwards
  of $100,000 each in EPA brownfields demonstration grants. Last month, the
  City of Atlanta received became the first southern city to win the EPA
  funding.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The grants are to be used to help cities clean up and redevelop abandoned
  contaminated commercial and industrial properties.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD><TABLE WIDTH="525" HEIGHT="247" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING=
  "0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="40%" VALIGN="TOP" HEIGHT="246">  <P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000" SIZE=+1>Declaring brownfields a key objective
  for 1997, the Southern Environmental Business Council has won the support
  of State Senate Natural Resources Committee Chairman Jack Latvala in its
  effort at passing a brownfields law in Florida. </FONT></B></P>

  
  <P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000" SIZE=+1>SEBC president Duane Truitt has indicated
  that Latvala will push a brownfields bill this year, in fact, Truitt reported
  that it was Latvala's number one priority.</FONT></B></TD>
<TD WIDTH="60%" VALIGN="TOP">  <P>&nbsp;But such funding has been scarce and insufficient, so this year
  several key Florida groups are pushing state legislation that will help
  free up funds and provide incentives aimed at redeveloping these blighted
  urban industrial areas.</P>

  
  <P>Declaring brownfields a key objective for 1997, the Southern Environmental
  Business Council has won the support of State Senate Natural Resources
  Committee Chairman Jack Latvala in its effort at passing a brownfields
  law in Florida. SEBC president Duane Truitt has indicated that Latvala
  will push a brownfields bill this year, in fact, Truitt reported that it
  was Latvala's number one priority.</P>

  
  <P>That support is not surprising, with groups such as the Florida Chamber
  of Commerce, the League of Cities, and the Florida Department of Environmental
  Protection all favoring and pushing for a state brownfields initiative.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
  <DD>What that law may look like is another question. Rep. J. Eggletion
  has vowed to introduce a bill modeled after a consensus draft hammered
  out by SEBC and several other groups. Truitt and Latvala both are hoping
  that one such bill will go forward without having to compete with other
  groups' bills.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>The SEBC bill sets up an appointed commission to oversee brownfields
  redevelopment and rulemaking and promote &quot;sustainable economic development
  and environmental justice, and reducing the need for taxpayer-funded cleanups.&quot;
  Only properties not under enforcement proceedings will be eligible, and
  a environmental assessment of the property must be performed. Preference
  will be given to inner-city sites.
  <DD>&nbsp;
  <DD>In return, the bill would mandate that risk-based cleanup standards
  would rule the remediation work- allowing some sites to cleanup less of
  the pollutants because long term natural degradation can complete the job.
  Another perk that pays would come from a tax credit in the amount of the
  cleanup. And in an effort at reducing bureaucracy and speeding cleanups,
  the consultants' Professional Engineer or Geologist would sign off on 
  sites once clean. DEP would then issue a No Further Action letter. Liability
  would also be reduced.
</DL>

<P><BR>
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
