<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../CoverPages/news.html">Return to Daily News Cover Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Meetings</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>-- Updated January 9, 1997--</P><H1><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H1><P>January 16 to March 28, 1997</P><H2>Nova offers marine science courses</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>Nova Southeastern University is offering several marine science courses  beginning Jan.16, running till March 28. Each course is for 3 credits.  The classes include: Fish and Wildlife Management, 5000 Days: Environmental  Futures, and Beyond 5000 Days</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Classes are taught one evening per week for 3 hours (6:30-9:30). Tuition  is $355/credit hour or $532.50 for audit. Registration for the classes  may be done at the Nova Southeastern Oceanographic Center in Dania. For  more information, call 800-396-2326 or 954-920-1909.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>January 14, 1997</P><H2>Conference looks at enviro professionals</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Environmental Professionals Action Coalition is presenting a conference  on The Future of The Florida Environmental Professional.</P>  <P>Dr. Thomas Cuba will be the guest speaker at the conference, which will  be held at the Holiday Inn in the West Palm Beach Airport on Jan. 14. There  will be a cocktail/hors d'oeuvres hour from 5 to 6 p.m. and the presentation  will begin at 6 p.m. For more information, call 813-532-0709.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>January 16</P><H2>Nova offers marine science courses </H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>Nova Southeastern University is offering several marine science courses  beginning Jan.16, and running through March 28.  The three credit courses  being offered include:  Fish and Wildlife Management; 5000 Days:  Environmental  Futures; Beyond 5000 Days.</P>  <P>Classes are taught one evening per week for 3 hours (6:30-9:30).  Tuition   is $355/credit hour or $532.50 for audit.  Registration may be done at  the Nova Southeastern Oceanographic Center in Dania.  For more information,  call 800-396-2326 or 954-920-1909.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR>January 16-18, 1997</P><H2>Gainesville hosts Jan. SSAWG conference</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The 6th Annual Southern Sustainable Agriculture Working Group Conference  and Trade Show will be held Jan. 16-18, 1997 in Gainesville. Florida Certified  Organic Growers and Consumers, Inc. will be hosting the event at the Radisson  Hotel on Bivens Lake and Wildlife Sanctuary. The conference will feature  five workshops, farm tours, a trade show, and many other events. For more  information on the SSAWG conference and trade show, call 352-377-6345.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>January 16-19, 1997</P><H2>Deerfield Beach hosts Glades conference</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Everglades Coalition is holding its 12th Annual Conference, Jan.  16-19, 1997. The event will be held at the Deerfield Beach/Boca Raton Hilton  in Deerfield Beach. For more information, call 800-624-3606.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>January 17-18, 1997</P><H2>Conference offers power to the people</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The 1997 Florida Energy Conference, &quot;Power to the People,&quot;  is being sponsored by the Project for an Energy Efficient Florida. The  conference will run from Jan. 17-18 at Florida International University  in North Miami Beach. Topics will include New Solar Technologies and Opportunities,  Electric Utility Deregulation, Energy Efficiency Alternatives, The Future  of Transportation and Consumer Empowerment. Program speakers include nationally  recognized energy and environmental experts from Florida, New York, California  and Washington D.C., as well as Florida leaders of public interest groups.</P>  <P>For more information or to register, call 904-222-0808.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>January to June</P><H2>TREEO offers ISO course through June </H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The University of Florida Center for Training, Research and Education  for Environmental Occupations is offering several courses in the ISO 14000  Environmental Management Standard: Concepts Components and Implementation.   The course format includes instructor presentations, individual and group  activities, group discussions, role plays and case study applications.   The dates and places the course will be held include:</P>  <P>	-- January 14 in Ft. Lauderdale</P>  <P>	-- March 6 in Shalimar/Ft. Walton Beach</P>  <P>	-- April 3 in Jacksonville</P>  <P>	-- May 1 in Orlando</P>  <P>	-- June 5 in Tallahassee</P>  <P>	-- June 24 in West Palm Beach  </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>For more information on the course or to register, call 352-392-9570.</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>January to April, 1997</P><H2>Seminar series addresses sustainable development in North Florida</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Center for Construction and Environment at the University of Florida,  in conjunction with the Gainesville City Commission and the Alachua County  Commission is offering the Second Annual Sustainable Development Seminar  Series to the citizens of North Central Florida. This seminar series focuses  on promoting sustainable community development and will run from Jan. 6  to April 7, on every other Monday at the Hippodrome State Theater at 7  pm.</P>  <P>The following topics will be presented at the meetings:</P>  <P>-- On Jan. 6 at 7 pm, The Natural Step: A Framework for Communities,  will be presented by Susan Burns. Burns will introduce the audience to  four system conditions of the Natural Step and how they can be used as  a framework for sustainable development in communities.</P>  <P>-- On Jan. 20 at 7 pm, Local Food Production, will be presented by Mark  Winne. Winne will present the Hartford program for local food production  and distribution and how this program is part of the national effort to  ensure food for all citizens.</P>  <P>-- On Feb. 3 at 7 pm, Local Sustainable Economics, will be presented  by Debbie Burd. She will present different aspects of a local sustainable  economy and the implementation of such an economy.</P>  <P>-- On Feb. 17 at 7 pm, Ecology of Urban Community, will be presented  by Gary Moll. He will give a presentation on the ecology of urban communities  addressing issues such as the urban flora and fauna, hydrology, soil and  air, and how other communities are implementing programs beneficial to  their urban ecology.</P>  <P>-- On March 3 at 7 pm, Citizens-Based Comprehensive Planning, will be  presented by Jamie Palmer. Palmer will present the Citizen-Based Comprehensive  Plan for Noblesville, IN.</P>  <P>-- On March 17 at 7 pm, Case Study of Sustainable City Principles, will  be presented by Dean Kubani. Kubani will present the City of Santa Monica's  Sustainable City Program.</P>  <P>-- On April 7 at 7 pm, Blueprint for San Francisco Bay Area and East  Palo Alto Neighborhood Plan, will be presented by Andrea Traber. She will  present the Blueprint for the San Francisco Bay Area and the East Palo  Alto Neighborhood Plan.</P>  <P>For more information on the seminar series, call Charles Kiber at 352-392-9029.<BR>  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>February 7-8, 1997</P><H2>FLEAC plans for conference in 1997</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Florida Environmental and Asbestos Council is planning for its Seventh  Annual Conference on Feb. 7-8, 1997 at the Delta Orlando Resort in Orlando.  Speakers from OSHA, EPA and Florida Government will present sessions detailing  asbestos, lead and indoor air quality. In addition, some exhibitors will  present the latest environmental services, instruments and products.</P>  <P>For more information, contact Perry Brake at 352-955-2022.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>March 3-5, 1997</P><H2>Conference looks at sustainability</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>Rice University &amp; The Houston Advanced Research Center are presenting  the De Lange Woodlands Conference on sustainable development.  This conference  will offer speakers and provide discussion opportunities that deal with  this comprehensive development concept.  The conference will be held March  3-5.  For more information, call 713-737-5674.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>March 7, 1997</P><H2>Search begins for winning wetland photo</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The best photograph of an American wetland can earn its shooter a $500  cash prize, and become the American Wetlands Month '97 poster.  The winner  will be announced and honored at the American Wetlands Conference, May  7-9 in Alexandria, Va.  Submission deadline is March 7 and the photo may  be in black and white or color.  Contact the Terrene Institute at 703-548-5473  for an entry form. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>March 7-8, 1997</P><H2>Tampa Spring Expo offers short course</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The 1997 Tree and Landscape Short Course will take place March 7-8 at  the Florida State Fairgrounds in Tampa during the Tampa Spring Expo. The  course will present topics important to Florida's green industry professionals.</P>  <P>For more information about the short course or the expo, call the show  sponsor, Tampa Bay Wholesale Growers Association at 813-960-1457.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>March 20-22, 1997</P><H2>Upcoming conference looks at Fla.'s future</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&quot;Florida 2020; Visions of Our Future,&quot; is the theme for the  Third Annual Public Interest Environmental Conference set for March 20-22,  1997 in Gainesville. The conference is organized by law students and faculty  members of the University of Florida College of Law. Topics to be discussed  will include climate change, population growth, transportation, energy,  agriculture, economics, the ocean, sustainable development and the future  of environmental law. Registration for the conference is $55; but for UF  students and faculty, conference registration is free. For more information,  call 352-846-1198.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>April 11-12, 1997</P><H2>Two-day meeting planned for next April</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>A two-day National Education Conference will be held April 11-12, 1997  at the Ramada Resort &amp; Conference Center in Orlando. The 1997 conference  will be a joint meeting of the National Society of Environmental Consultants  and the National Association of Master Appraisers, and will feature nationally  known speakers, educational sessions, networking opportunities, exhibits  and the latest development in appraisal and environmental real estate.  Exhibit space is currently available. The deadline to reserve exhibit space  is Feb. 15, 1997. For more information on the conference and exhibiting,  call 800-486-3676.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>May 15-16, 1997</P><H2>Conference looks at wetland systems</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Environmental Studies Center of Hillsborough Community College is  sponsoring the 24th Annual Conference on Ecosystem Restoration and Creation  set for May 15-16, 1997. The conference will provide a forum an exchange  of results from scientific research in the restoration, creation, and management  of freshwater and coastal wetland systems.</P>  <P>Those interested in presenting a paper at the conference are invited  to submit an abstract of approximately 250 words by Jan. 29, 1997. For  more information on the conference and papers, contact Frederick Webb at  813-757-2104.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>May 15-18, 1997</P><H2>Plant society plans annual conference</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Florida Native Plant Society has made plans for its 17th Annual  Conference, which will be held May 15-18, 1997 at the Radisson Hotel in  Gainesville, Fla. The Paynes Prairie Chapter will host the event, which  will include field trips on Thursday and Sunday, and workshops and programs  on Friday and Saturday.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>June 2-3, 1997</P><H2>GEMI '97 Conference helps businesses</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>The Global Environmental Management Initiative is preparing for its  1997 conference, &quot;Business Helping Business.&quot; GEMI's seventh  annual conference will provide attendees with workshops and roundtables.   Each attendee will participate in four workshops in which a GEMI member  will demonstrate how to use GEMI tools to improve a company's environmental  health and safety performance.  In addition, two facilitated roundtables  will provide an opportunity for informal benchmarking between peers.</P>  <P>The conference is scheduled for June 2-3, 1997 at the Ritz-Carlton,  Pentagon City Arlington, Virginia.  For more information, call 800-726-4853  or 703-519-2180.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../CoverPages/news.html"><B>Return to Daily NewsCover Page</B></A></BODY></HTML>
