<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../CoverPages/features.html">Return to Features Page</A> <HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104"ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></P><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Enforcement News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>--Updated January 9, 1997--</P><H1 ALIGN=CENTER><HR><IMG SRC="../Images/image117.gif" WIDTH="289" HEIGHT="75" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H1><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Summary of environmental enforcement stories from aroundFlorida</H4><H2><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H2><H2>Browner comments hurt some feelings</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B>EPA Administrator Carol Browner's criticism of some states' enforcement  efforts</B> has raised hackles. A Dec. 23 letter from the Environmental  Council of the States (ECOS) claim Browner's comments raise doubts about  her commitment to the federal-state enforcement partnership.</P>  <P>The letter was a response to statements by Browner in a December 15  New York Times article. In the article, Browner found faults with the enforcement  commitment of &quot;a number of states&quot; that have been &quot;emboldened  by the anti-environmental sentiment that began here in Congress.&quot;</P>  <P>The group asked Browner to reaffirm her commitment to federal-state  partnership.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><H2>Man arrested for killing Florida black bear</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B>A man was arrested and charged with intentionally killing a threatened  species after</B> shooting a Florida black bear, the Orlando Sentinel reported.  Ronald Gandy was arrested when officers pulled him over and found the 150-pound  male bear wrapped in a tarp in the back of Gandy's pickup truck.</P>  <P>The shooting took place south of the Ocala National Forest.  Officers  said Gandy told them he shot the bear because he thought it had been hit  by a car and was planning to contact authorities about the bear.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><H2>Criticism leveled at EPA's project XL</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B>The Environmental Protection Agency's Project XL generated critcism  at a meeting</B> sponsored by the DC Bar Environment, Energy and Natural  Resources Section, according to the Daily Environment Report.</P>  <P>University of Maryland law professor Rena Steinzor called the program  &quot;an unappealing morass of pilot projects going nowhere fast. &quot;Steinzor  has also written that the program hurts the EPA's ability to protect the  environment.</P>  <P>Industry attorney also William Pederson complained that XL was &quot;  another reason to devote more intellectual energy to major stationary sources.&quot;</P>  <P>Offering a defense EPA staffer Lisa Lund, said XL was still on the learning  curve and should be given time to improve.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><H2>Pinellas copper polluter charged</H2><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B>A former Universal Circuits employee has been charged in a federal  indictment</B> with polluting Pinellas County's sewer system with copper,  the St. Petersburg Times reported.</P>  <P>David W. Boldt is accused of dumping illegal levels of copper into the  county sewer system from 1989 to 1992 while employed by the now-defunct  Universal Circuits of Largo. </P>  <P>The company was cited over 100 times between 1987 and 1990 for illegal  levels of toxic substances in the water deposited into the county sewer  system.</P>  <P>The indictment says that Boldt rigged a monitoring device so that county  workers who checked the discharges would also get inaccurate results.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT></B>&nbsp;</P><P><BR><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../CoverPages/features.html">Return to FeaturesPage</A></BODY></HTML>
