<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../CoverPages/features.html">Return to Features Page</A> <BR></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104"ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></P><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Rules &amp; Regulations</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>-- Updated November 25, 1996 --</P><H1 ALIGN=CENTER><HR><IMG SRC="../Images/image103.gif" WIDTH="288" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H1><P><BR><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><BR>  This is a summary of the important rules and regulations being considered  by Florida's environmental agencies:</P>  <P><BR>  <A NAME="anchor297040"></A><A HREF="#anchor297040">AGENCY:</A><BR>  <STRONG><A HREF="#anchor243222">Administration Commission<BR>  </A><A HREF="#anchor239720">Department of Environmental Protection</A></STRONG></P>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><A HREF="#anchor260205"><STRONG>Air</STRONG> <BR>    </A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor267401">Coastal construction<BR>    </A><A HREF="#anchor263662">Tanks</A></STRONG><BR>    <STRONG><A HREF="#anchor253788">Water</A></STRONG><BR>    <A HREF="#anchor261871"><STRONG>Waste</STRONG> </A></P>  </BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><A HREF="#anchor261871"><BR>  </A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor235114">Northwest Florida Water Management  District<BR>  </A></STRONG><B><A HREF="#anchor219755">South Florida Water Management  District </A></B><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor224778"><STRONG>Southwest Florida Water Management District</STRONG>  </A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor232367"><STRONG>Suwannee River Water Management District</STRONG>  <BR>  <BR>  </A><A HREF="../CoverPages/features.html">Return to Features Page</A></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor243222"></A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor243222">Administration  Commission</A></STRONG></P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Uniform Procedural Rules.</STRONG></CITE> Rulemaking to  adopt uniform rules of procedure for use by all agencies. Status: Workshop  held October 24; expected to be presented to the Governor and Cabinet on  November 19 for authority to publish to proposed rules in the November  29 F.A.W.<A NAME="anchor297040"></A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A></P>  <P><BR>  </P>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor239720"></A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor239720">Department  of<BR>  Environmental Protection</A></STRONG></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor253788"></A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor253788">Water</A></STRONG></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Storm Water Policy (Chapter 62-40).</STRONG></CITE> Rulemaking  to clarify the responsibility of the water management and water control  districts under the policy. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed changes published  September 20.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Ground Water Protection (Chapters 62-520 and 62-522).</STRONG></CITE>  DEP is undertaking a comprehensive review of these rules. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  Meeting of Ground Water Evaluation Technical Advisory Committee held June  25. Another TAC is tentatively scheduled for December in Tampa.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Health-Based Surface Water Quality Criteria (Rule 62-302.530).</STRONG></CITE>  Certain environmental interest groups have requested that DEP initiate  rulemaking to revise the health-based surface water quality criteria in  this rule to reflect the consumption by average Floridians of fish and  shellfish. <CITE>Status</CITE>: DEP has granted the petition to initiate  rulemaking; initial public workshop held on September 12. Comments were  accepted until October 11 and are being reviewed. DEP will be preparing  a Risk Impact Statement for the rules.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Cross-Connection Control (Chapters 62-550 and -555). </STRONG></CITE>DEP  has drafted amendments to the cross-connection control rules. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  A draft rule is available. Notice of rule development and public workshop  to be published later this year or early next year. A Risk Impact Statement  may be prepared.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Reuse of Reclaimed Water (Chapter 62-610). </STRONG></CITE>&quot;Phase  II&quot; revisions to this rule. <CITE>Status</CITE>: DEP has completed  an internal working draft of the rule. A public workshop will be held January  14.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Wastewater Facility Permitting (Chapter 62-620).</STRONG></CITE>  Proposed repeal of rules relating to permit and variance application filing  and processing procedures. Rules to be transferred to DEP's Guide to Wastewater  Permitting. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed repeal published December 29,  1995. The repeal was challenged, and a notice of change was filed August  The challenges have been withdrawn, and the amendments will be filed shortly.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Discharges from Concrete Batch Plants (Chapter 62-621).  </STRONG></CITE>Rulemaking to create generic permit for discharges from  concrete batch plants. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Public workshop to be held  on October 17. The proposed rules are expected to be published at the end  of November.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Domestic Wastewater Residuals (Chapter 62-640).</STRONG></CITE>  The Residuals Technical Advisory Committee is meeting to consider revisions  to the rules based on new federal standards for the use and disposal of  sewage sludge (40 CFR Part 503). <CITE>Status</CITE>: DEP has completed  an internal draft of the rule; to be presented to the PCC shortly for scheduling  of a public workshop. A workshop is tentatively anticipated sometime in  January.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Phosphorous/Everglades Protection Area. </STRONG></CITE>The  Everglades Technical Advisory Committee (ETAC) is assisting DEP in developing  a numeric phosphorus criterion for the Everglades Protection Area. The  Everglades Technical Oversight Committee (ETOC) is meeting to develop strategies  for Everglades restoration and protection. <CITE>Status</CITE>: The ETAC  last met on September 19. The ETOC last met on October 30.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Marine Surface Water Reclassification (Rule 62-302.400).</STRONG></CITE>  DEP is proposing to reclassify certain marine waters of the state to reflect  the fact that the waters are being used for shellfish harvesting. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  To be presented to PCC shortly for scheduling of a public workshop. <A  NAME="anchor297040"></A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor260205"></A><A HREF="#anchor260205"><STRONG>Air</STRONG></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Title V Permit Simplification (Chapters 62-210 and -212).  </STRONG></CITE>Part V of rulemaking to simplify permitting on Title V  of the Clean Air Act, concerning general permits, exemptions, streamlined  processing and other issues. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Workshop held on September  25, and comments were accepted until October 11. Another workshop is scheduled  for November 20.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Stationary Sources - General Requirements (Chapter 62-210).</STRONG></CITE>  Proposed rules to amend list of hazardous air pollutants and amend the  definition of VOCs. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed rule published August  9; public workshop held September 12.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Air Emissions Bubble (Chapters 62-210 and -212).</STRONG></CITE>  Rulemaking to authorize creation of air emissions bubbles and to establish  requirements for such bubbles. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed rules published  September 20; a workshop will be held November 6. The ERC is scheduled  to be briefed on the rule in December, with adoption slated for January.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Municipal Waste Combustors (Chapter 62-210 and -296).</STRONG></CITE>  DEP is considering adopting the EPA rule establishing Emissions Guidelines  for Existing Sources-Municipal Waste Combustors, 40 C.F.R. Part 60, Subpart  Eb. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed rules published August 9. The rules became  effective on October 7 and 20. A Section 111(d) hearing was held as required  by EPA on October 29. To be submitted to EPA in November for approval.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Municipal Waste Landfills (Chapter 62-204). </STRONG></CITE>DEP  is considering adopting standards of performance and emissions guidelines  for municipal solid waste landfills. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed rules  published August 23. The rules became effective October 17, and the Section  111(d) hearing required by EPA will be held early next year. <A NAME="anchor297040"></A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A></P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor261871"></A><A HREF="#anchor261871"><STRONG>Waste</STRONG></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Construction and Demolition Debris.</STRONG></CITE> Proposed  rules to implement 1996 legislation that would provide for more stringent  regulation of C&amp;D debris landfills. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed rules  published August 23; approved by ERC on September 26, with minor amendment.  Public workshop to be held November 21 to consider more controversial issues.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>C&amp;D Debris Residue (RSM).</STRONG></CITE> DEP has  convened a Technical Advisory Group to address technical issues related  to the use of C&amp;D debris residue or &quot;recovered screen material.&quot;  <CITE>Status</CITE>: First TAG meeting held.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Compost (Chapter 62-709).</STRONG></CITE> DEP has contracted  for the development of BMPs for yard trash composting. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  Workshops held October 3 and 6, 1995; BMP manual is now available.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Used Oil Management (Chapter 62-710).</STRONG></CITE>  DEP is proposed to amend this rule principally with respect to permit requirements  for used oil processors. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Proposed rule amendments  published August 30; public hearing to be held on September 24, if requested.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Mercury-Containing Lamps and Devices (Chapter 62-737).</STRONG></CITE>  DEP has convened a technical advisory group to discuss possible changes  to this rule. The possible changes include amendments to conform the rule  to the Universal Waste Rule in 40 C.F.R., Part 273. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  Technical advisory group meeting held on April 17.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Dairy Waste Management.</STRONG></CITE> Technical Advisory  Committee is developing revisions to DEP rules for waste management at  dairy farms. <CITE>Status</CITE>: TAC last met on September 4.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Non-Dairy Animal Waste Management.</STRONG></CITE> Technical  Advisory Committee is developing revisions to DEP rules for waste management  at animal husbandry operations. <CITE>Status</CITE>: TAC last met on September  10. <A NAME="anchor297040"></A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A></P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor263662"></A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor263662">Tanks</A></STRONG></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Underground Storage Tanks (Chapter 62-761).</STRONG></CITE>  Proposed general revisions to DEP's rule regulating underground petroleum  and hazardous substance storage tanks. <CITE>Status</CITE>: DEP has completed  a revised working draft. A workshop is tentatively scheduled for November  13-14.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Aboveground Storage Tanks (Chapter 62-762). </STRONG></CITE>Proposed  general revisions to DEP's rule regulating aboveground petroleum and hazardous  substance storage tanks, including revised closure requirements and registration  for hazardous substance tanks. <CITE>Status</CITE>: DEP has completed a  revised working draft. A workshop is tentatively scheduled for November  13-14. The Department's Technical Advisory Committee for Aboveground Storage  Tanks will meet on November 1 in Tallahassee to discuss the agency's rule  requirements for secondary containment.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Storage Tank System Noncompliance Fee (Chapter 62-766).  </STRONG></CITE>DEP has proposed repealing DEP's rules relating to noncompliance  fees for violations of the Department's underground and aboveground storage  tank rules. <CITE>Status</CITE>: A public hearing will be held on October  31, if requested.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Petroleum Contamination Site Cleanup Criteria (Chapters  62-770).</STRONG></CITE> DEP is moving ahead with amendments to these rules  which include substantial changes required by this year's legislative session.  Rulemaking is progressing regarding no further action criteria and natural  attenuation criteria. The Technical Advisory Committee (TAC) for Petroleum  Storage Tanks Cleanup has recently formed to consider and develop various  program issues, including Risk Based Corrective Action (RBCA) principles.  <CITE>Status</CITE>: DEP held a workshop on August 15 to discuss rule amendments  and another workshop was held on October 16 and 17 in Tampa. The TAC for  Petroleum Storage Tanks Cleanup will meet on November 4 in Tallahassee  to discuss RBCA principals, including tier approaches and abbreviated Contamination  Assessment Reports.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Preapproved Advanced Cleanup Program.</STRONG></CITE>  Rulemaking is progressing regarding implementation of the Preapproved Advanced  Cleanup Program authorized by the 1996 legislation. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  DEP held a workshop on September 18 to discuss implementation of the program  and will initiate the first application period for the program on November  1.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Petroleum Contamination Site Cleanup Reimbursement Criteria  (Chapter 62-773). </STRONG></CITE>These amendments clarify Department policy  regarding the definition of incurred costs and requirements for reimbursement  of contractor markups (Rules 62-773.100, .200, .350, and .700). <CITE>Status</CITE>:  The Department will hold a hearing on October 29, if requested, to address  proposed amendments.<A NAME="anchor297040"></A><A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN  TO AGENCY MENU</A></P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor267401"></A><STRONG><A HREF="#anchor267401">Coastal construction</A></STRONG></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Coastal Construction (Chapter 62B-33). </STRONG></CITE>DEP  is proposing to add rules to this chapter relating to criteria for coastal  armoring permits for construction seaward of the coastal construction line  (CCCL). DEP has also proposed siting and design exemptions for construction  seaward of the CCCL and landward of existing armoring. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  Amendments to the coastal armoring rules, contained in proposed Rule 62B-33.0051,  as well as the proposed rule on siting and design exemptions (62B-33.0045),  were published May 3. A notice of change to the Rule 62B-33.0051 amendments  was published July 19. Two administrative petitions have been filed challenging  some of the proposed rules, alleging (among other things) that the rules  do not provide adequate protection to sea turtles and their habitat. <A  NAME="anchor297040"></A></P>  <P><A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A></P>  <P><BR>  </P>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor235114"></A><A HREF="#anchor235114"><STRONG>Northwest  Florida Water<BR>  Management District</STRONG> </A></P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Regulation of Agricultural and Forestry Surface Water  Management Projects (Chapter 40A-44).</STRONG></CITE> Comprehensive amendments  are being considered for this chapter. <CITE>Status</CITE>: The rule amendments  remain on hold.<A NAME="anchor297040"></A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A> <BR>  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor232367"></A><A HREF="#anchor232367"><STRONG>Suwannee  River Water<BR>  Management District</STRONG> </A></P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Regulation of Consumptive Uses of Water (Chapter 40B-2).</STRONG></CITE>  SRWMD is developing amendments to chapter 40B-2 to maintain consistency  with Chapter 62-40 (water policy) and clarify text. <CITE>Status</CITE>:  Draft rule language and a Basis of Review are under preparation. A public  draft is expected in shortly.<A NAME="anchor297040"></A><BR>  <A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A> <BR>  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor224778"></A><A HREF="#anchor224778"><STRONG>Southwest  Florida Water<BR>  Management District</STRONG> </A></P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Site Conditions Assessments (Chapter 40D-4).</STRONG></CITE>  Amendments to the fee schedules, permitting rules and Basis of Review for  ERP assessments were published on May 3. Status: Notices of Changes to  various sections in Chapter 40D-4, portions of Appendix 7, Basis of Review  (Chapter 40D-4) and Chapter 40D-40 became effective October 16.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Southern Water Use Caution Area (&quot;SWUCA&quot;) (Chapter  40D-2).</STRONG></CITE> Proposed amendments to Chapter 40D-2, the related  &quot;Basis of Review&quot; and Chapter 40D-8 impose significant controls  on water use and preclude new quantities from the Floridan Aquifer throughout  the designated area. Status: Awaiting decision of hearing officer regarding  rule challenges to SWUCA amendments. <A NAME="anchor297040"></A></P>  <P><A HREF="#anchor297040">RETURN TO AGENCY MENU</A> <BR>  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor219755"></A><A HREF="#anchor219755"><STRONG>South  Florida Water<BR>  Management District</STRONG> </A></P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Dade County ERP Delegation.</STRONG></CITE> SFWMD is proposing  to incorporate by reference an agreement delegating certain ERP responsibilities  to Dade County. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Rule development is ongoing.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Wetland Mitigation Ratios.</STRONG></CITE> Rules are being  developed to establish equitable mitigation ratios for melaleuca-dominated  wetlands. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Adoption is expected November 14.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Everglades Agricultural Area BMP's.</STRONG></CITE> Pursuant  to the Everglades Forever Act, the District's rules must be amended to  implement BMP's for water quality within the EAA and the Lake Okeechobee  Drainage Basin. <CITE>Status</CITE>: Adoption is projected for November  14.</P>  <P><CITE><STRONG>Programmatic Environmental Impact Statement for Everglades  Construction. </STRONG></CITE>SFWMD is preparing a programmatic EIS on  the Everglades Construction Project in Palm Beach, Martin,Hendry and Broward  Counties. <CITE>Status</CITE>: The EIES was finalized in late September.  <A NAME="anchor332717"></A></P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../CoverPages/features.html">Return to Features  Page</A></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
