<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>To Our Readers</H1>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>November 1996</I></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P><B><FONT COLOR="#006600">LAST MONTH</FONT></B>, we wrote that we were
  preparing to tell the rest of the story regarding Alan Whidby's lawsuit
  against Florida Environments Magazine [<FONT COLOR="#00BA00">EnviroWorld</FONT>'s
  print parent] for alleged defamatory statements in a June 1994 Editorial.
  Subsequent to effecting a Mediated Settlement Agreement, that suit has
  been voluntarily withdrawn by Whidby and dismissed by the Court.</P>
  <P>On these pages last month we promised to post Whidby's Deposition on
  EnviroWorld. That way, our readers could be privy to Whidby's sworn statements
  about the opportunity that he said caused him to resign from his job during
  a period when much attention was focused on his employer for its role in
  an unpopular challenge of the tanks cleanup reimbursement rule. Interested
  readers might glean other valuable facts from the testimony too.</P>
  <P>Then, late last month, our attorney received the following one paragraph
  letter from Whidby's attorney, J. Michael Huey:</P>
  <P><B>The letter</B></P>
  <P><I>Dear Sir:</I></P>
  <P><I>I assume you are aware of the enclosed article [&quot;The Price Of
  Tanks Truth,&quot; FE editorial, Oct 1996, p.16] by your client, Florida
  Environmental [sic] Inc. It appears that your client did not enter into
  the Settlement Agreement in good faith and is intent on violating the Settlement
  Agreement. Please be advised that we will proceed with an action for breach
  of the Settlement Agreement absent your immediate assurance that you have
  dissuaded your client from further disregard of our Agreement.</I></P>
  <P><I>Sincerely,</I></P>
  <P><I>[signed]</I></P>
  <P><I>J. Michael Huey</I></P>
  <P><B>Our response</B></P>
  <P>Again, so that our readers may be privy the relevant facts of this case,
  and because we have nothing to hide, we have reprinted in its entirety,
  the Mediated Settlement Agreement signed by both parties:</P>
  <P><B>Mediated Settlement Agreement</B></P>
  <P><I>As a result of the Mediation Conference held on July 16, 1996, the
  parties agreed to the following:</I></P>
  <P><I>1. Fla. Environmental Publishing, Inc. will print in its August 1996
  edition the language shown in &quot;Exhibit A&quot; attached hereto. Said
  language shall be printed in a prominent position on the &quot;op-ed&quot;
  page with a notice printed in standard &quot;call-out&quot; form on page
  1 of the edition.</I></P>
  <P><I>2. Counsel for Whidby shall review the financial statements of Fla.
  Environmental Publishing, Inc. Counsel agrees not to disclose to anyone
  the contents therein. Should the contents be disclosed, Counsel agrees
  to withdraw from further representation of Whidby against Fla. Environmental
  Publishing, Inc.</I></P>
  <P><I>3. Fla. Environmental Publishing, Inc. agrees to pay the fee for
  the mediation.</I></P>
  <P><I>4. Immediately after compliance by Fla. Environmental Publishing,
  Inc. with its obligations under paragraphs 1 and 3 of this agreement, Alan
  Whidby shall dismiss this action with prejudice.</I></P>
  <P><I>Dated this 19 day of July, 1996.</I></P>
  <P><I>Edwin F. Blanton</I></P>
  <P><I>Mediator</I></P>
  <P><B>Dismissal</B></P>
  <P>Subsequent to signing the above settlement, FEP Inc. complied with its
  commitments, Whidby's counsel withdrew the lawsuit, and the case was dismissed.</P>
  <P><B>The depositions</B></P>
  <P>We haven't been able to find any language in that Agreement that prevents
  us from publishing any materials relevant to the case.</P>
  <P>Therefore, we are currently scanning the entirety of Whidby's sworn
  deposition for publication EnviroWorld.</P>
  <P>We'll rely on our readers to sort out what the truth is.</P>
  <P><A HREF="mailto:info@enviroworld.com">for info concerning publication
  date, inquire here</A></BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
