<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Features<BR>
</H1>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><HR></H2>

<H1>OPINION</H1>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=-1>From the January 1997 Florida Environments
magazine</FONT></I><A NAME="anchor532907"></A></P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Even Browner is slaming lax state
enviro enforcement</FONT></H2>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P>COOPERATION IS SUCH A friendly fuzzy word that when politicians bat
    it around it's easy to close your eyes and believe the sun's still shining.
    </P>
    <P>Wake up, we're not on Sesame Street anymore. </P>
    <P>Last month, EPA chief Carol Browner meted out harsh criticism against
    those states backsliding on environmental enforcement. The response has
    been the whining refrain that &quot;we're all supposed to be cooperating
    here.&quot; </P>
    <P>That's the same spin we get from DEP about its retreat from enforcement.
    In its new &quot;culture,&quot; the idea is that everyone has become aware
    of the importance of environmental responsibility, and that the bad guys
    simply aren't out there anymore. All that's left is to get government off
    the backs of business, so it can implement sound environmental policies
    on its own.</P>
    <P>But, if they are honest about protecting the state's environment, then
    DEP must simply have collective amnesia. It was only in the last Congressional
    session that efforts were on the table to undermine decades of environmental
    progress. Who do they think lobbied politicians to write those laws, the
    Partridge Family?</P>
    <P>The egregious polluters are still out there, and they are as willing
    as ever to blatantly ignore the law if it makes them an extra buck. While
    a number of companies have invested in their environmental compliance departments,
    an equal number have simply doled out cash for slick public relations firms.
    Here at FE, we get are plenty of self-congratulatory press releases from
    obnoxious corporations wishing to improve their public image. What the
    DEP gets is a big grin and a knife in the back. And Florida may very well
    be on Browner's short list of problem children - but for some obvious political
    reasons, she's not saying so publicly.</P>
    <P>But in earning an investigation from Public Employees for Environmental
    Responsibility (PEER), Florida now joins a group that includes Virginia,
    Montana, and a number of other wayward federal enviro agencies. </P>
    <P>Virginia recently received, in the words of the New York Times, &quot;a
    stinging rebuke&quot; from the EPA for its treatment of Smithfield Foods,
    a company with revenues nearing $4 billion that has a habit of contaminating
    the Pagan River with fecal coliform, ammonia, cyanide, oil and grease.
    For that crime Smithfield got away with a tiny state fine of $2 million.
    Smithfield saw Virginia for the easy mark that it was, and ran with the
    ball.</P>
    <P>Unfortunately for Smithfield, the EPA has stepped in and wants a $125
    million fine. And this month, EPA unveiled a federal investigation of Virginia's
    lax  air pollution enforcement.</P>
    <P>Message to DEP: EPA wants the states to enforce the law or they will
    lose Federal program money.</P>
    <P>But DEP has paid little attention to such examples and seems to be weakening
    its enforcement backbone. Not only do officials readily admit that they
    no longer have much funding for enforcement, but DEP spokesman Joy Mills
    told FE that &quot;if someone doesn't know they're committing a crime we're
    not going to slap them with fines.&quot;</P>
    <P>Imagine telling that to the cop who pulls you over after you were going
    20 miles over the limit. &quot;I didn't know I was breaking the law officer.&quot;
    He'd probably order a field sobriety test for you.</P>
    <P>But under DEP secretary Virginia Wetherell's policy, the cop would just
    ask you &quot;cooperate&quot; in the future, you wouldn't even get a warning
    letter, and you are free to put the pedal to the metal again.</P>
    <P>DEP's real message to polluters: If you want to avoid fines and continue
    polluting, you had better play dumb. It doesn't even take much business
    savvy to use that tactic. The difference between DEP and traffic cops is
    the police don't fall for it.</P>
    <P>Browner's stance should be taken as an example of the character needed
    to run government regulatory agencies at every level.</P>
    <P>The Environmental Council of the States responded to Browner's criticism
    with a childish letter. In it, the council complained that &quot;states
    are very concerned about what appears to be a retreat on your part from
    the partnership relation.... . State commissioners ... are disappointed
    to be the objects of your apparent lack of trust.&quot; </P>
    <P>For DEP, trust is an endangered specie. Judging by early returns from
    the PEER survey, DEP's employees don't trust their own bosses. Let's see,
    EPA doesn't trust DEP leaders, Florida citizens don't trust them, and DEP
    employees don't trust them. We trust that Florida Governor Lawton Chiles
    will figure that out sometime before the Democrats lose the governor's
    mansion. </P>
    <P>Maybe.<BR>
    <BR>
    <BR>
    </P>
  </BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>&nbsp;</P>

