<P ALIGN=CENTER>&nbsp;</P>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Letters</H1>

<H1><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H1>

<H1>&nbsp;</H1>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P>March 1996</P>

<H3>Fe's article on ecosystem management 'perfectly framed' the issue</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Dear Editor:<BR>
  On too few occasions our state is fortunate to attract and keep leaders
  with foresight, wisdom, and the courage to look outside the box to find
  solutions for the state's future. Secretary Virginia Wetherell is such
  a leader. I thought your article perfectly framed the issue, &quot;DEP
  is either doing something very right-or very, very, wrong.&quot; Well,
  this is one person's opinion that the Department and it's Secretary are
  doing something very right.<BR>
  Fortunately, Secretary Wetherell has had, and I hope will continue to have,
  the courage to reinvent a system based on voluntary, incentive based programs
  that deliver a net environmental benefit for the state and its environments,
  while recognizing the need for sustainable economic growth and private
  property rights. All of this is being done without sacrificing any of the
  current safeguards or enforcement abilities of the state or the Department.<BR>
  Six more volumes of state statutes and another three hundred thousand rules
  cannot turn the tide. It is time to start again. I believe Secretary Wetherell's
  Ecosystem Management Initiative could be that new start. However, we have
  only begun to test these initiatives and it is going to take new partnerships,
  a lot of guts, the freedom to fail, and more trust than your article seemed
  to portray.<BR>
  I have been speaking on this issue and the need for reform since Governor
  Chiles was elected, and I always ask two questions of each audience regardless
  of its makeup; &quot;From the perspective of your special interest, your
  community or your industry, is our current environmental regulation system
  and growth management system working, and do you believe the current system
  will insure a sustainable state for your children or future generations?&quot;
  In almost six years, and in front of thousands of our state's citizens,
  I have only seen two hands go up.<BR>
  The next time <I>Florida Environments</I> elects to write a story on the
  Department or on Secretary Wetherell's commitment to the environment, I
  hope it will take the time to ask some of the over 300 citizens who volunteered
  to participate in the Ecosystem Management Initiative, how they feel about
  the need for change or the Secretary's commitment to environmental protection.<BR>
  I believe you will find the overwhelming majority of us in agriculture
  and forestry care very deeply about Florida's environment and no one more
  than us are dependent upon conserving it. And, while there might be a few
  friends turning away, I know there are a lot more old and new friends willing
  to stay the course. I am proud of Governor Chiles' and Lt. Governor McKay's
  continued support of Ginger, the Department and the Ecosystem Management
  Initiative. I doubt Florida has ever had three leaders so committed to
  achieving a sustainable state, preserving our quality of life, or for reinventing
  new, creative, and effective programs to achieve these goals.<BR>
  They have given our state and our citizens the opportunity to start again,
  and we are going to need all the friends we can get to get the job done.
  I hope <I>Florida Environments</I> will be one of those friends, or at
  least give all of us involved the opportunity to prove how effective incentive
  based alternatives can be to meet our state's conservation goals.<BR>
  Sincerely, <BR>
  Thomas H. Dyer<BR>
  Vice President<BR>
  Two Rivers Ranch<BR>
  Thonotosassa, FL</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR>
<BR>
<HR ALIGN=LEFT><B>FE's mangrove forecast missed the point</B></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Dear Editor:<BR>
  I want to let you know how much I enjoy reading <I>Florida Environments</I>.
  However, I was reading the February 1996 issue when I noticed in the &quot;Legislative
  Update 96&quot; article on page 16 some erroneous information under the
  heading &quot;Wetlands/Melaleuca.&quot; This &quot;update&quot; refers
  to Representative Sembler's proposed amendment to HNR PCB 96-03 and states
  that &quot;The bill, which was proposed last session and did not pass,
  would encourage the removal of this exotic species.&quot;<BR>
  Nothing could be further from the truth. By eliminating the mitigation
  requirements for the dredging and filling of lands with a 75% coverage
  of melaleuca, Representative Sembler's proposal does exactly the opposite.
  Representative Sembler's amendment provides an incentive to the landowner
  to grow melaleuca on their property by exempting them from mitigation requirements
  if their property has a 75% coverage of melaleuca. Representative Sembler's
  proposed amendment would attribute absolutely no value to these wetlands.<BR>
  I realize that the report in question was contributed by the environmental
  law specialty group at Holland &amp; Knight but I hope that <I>Florida
  Environments</I> reviews contributions to your publication for accuracy
  before printing them.<BR>
  Thank you for your time and consideration of my letter.<BR>
  Sincerely yours,<BR>
  Isabel Cosio<BR>
  Legislative Liason<BR>
  Broward County Commission<BR>
  Ft. Lauderdale</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR>
<HR ALIGN=LEFT><B>No politics in water dialogue decision</B></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Dear Editor:<BR>
  I have recently reviewed several articles from <I>Florida Environments</I>
  and <I>ProEarth Times</I> reporting on the denial by FACEE of our proposal
  for a Florida Water Dialogue. These articles imply that FACEE denied funding
  due to political pressure by interests opposed to educating the public
  on water policy issues. I have no reason to believe that is true and regret
  that the articles unfairly malign the Council and two of its members, Senator
  George Kirkpatrick and Estus Whitfield. Although we answered them, the
  concerns raised by Senator Kirkpatrick regarding the potential for duplication
  were valid and appropriately expressed. Similarly, Mr. Whitfield's reluctance
  to fund any project outside of the normal grants process is an understandable
  and legitimate position.<BR>
  The Florida Water Dialogue project would have been an extremely ambitious
  undertaking. Given the need for coordination with numerous agencies and
  local governments, and the time constraints under which we developed the
  proposal, there were certain unavoidable weaknesses in the submission that
  would have justified any member of the Council in voting to deny funding.
  I do not believe that the vote reflected any lack of interest by the Council
  in helping to educate the public on the important water policy issues facing
  our state.<BR>
  Sincerely, <BR>
  Richard Hamann<BR>
  UF Law School<BR>
  Gainesville</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR>
<HR ALIGN=LEFT><B>EPA not snubbed by DEP</B></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Dear Editor:<BR>
  The content of your Email message of January 25, 1996, entitled &quot;DEP
  top brass snub EPA, local environmental officials&quot; was carried over
  into a larger article in your most recent edition of <I>Florida Environments</I>.
  As leader of the EPA officials to which you referred in both articles,
  I want to take this opportunity to assure you that it was certainly not
  my sense that EPA had been &quot;snubbed&quot; by DEP, and to provide you
  with additional background on our efforts to create better partnerships
  between federal, state, and local environmental regulators.<BR>
  A major thrust of EPA's reinvention efforts under the leadership of President
  Clinton and EPA Administrator Browner is to create stronger partnerships
  between all levels of government in the protection of the environment.
  In discussions with FLERA about a possible meeting to explore options,
  EPA staff encouraged FLERA to invite representatives from DEP since they
  are our primary partners in the federally-delegated programs to Florida.
  Because this meeting, from my perspective, was to be largely an introductory
  meeting between EPA and FLERA, I did not expect that high level DEP representatives
  would be present since they regularly work with FLERA representatives.
  DEP was ably represented by Ernie Frey, a DEP district manager of long-standing,
  and Debbie Parrish, Director of Intergovernmental Programs.<BR>
  We are working together with DEP quite productively to improve the quality
  of our federal/state partnership. I feel that the meeting with the FLERA
  representatives gave us a much better insight to the opportunities available
  to improve our joint partnership with local governments. Success in our
  effort will result in improved environmental protection at lower cost for
  both the governmental and private sector.<BR>
  Sincerely, <BR>
  John H. Hankinson, Jr.<BR>
  Regional Administrator<BR>
  USEPA Region 4<BR>
  Atlanta</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR>
<HR ALIGN=LEFT><B>FE unfairly tainted Florida growers</B></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Dear Editor:<BR>
  Although the text of your article &quot;Do Florida growers soak workers
  in toxic brew?&quot; in the February issue of <I>Florida Environments</I>
  did not specifically say that growers require workers to mix pesticides
  with their hands or expose them to extremely dangerous conditions, the
  manner in which your graphics and headlines treated the story certainly
  would lead one to believe that farmers are ruthless violators of regulations.<BR>
  In short, the article violates the cannon of ethics of good journalism,
  although there seems to be little objective journalism left these days.
  You called dramatic attention to the fact that 38 percent of inspections
  were in non-compliance but you did little to stress that a much lower percentage
  of violations involved safety equipment or reentry.<BR>
  Your attempt to put Florida in the same corner as South America with comments
  by a member of the Pesticide Review Council did little to address the factual
  issues in Florida.<BR>
  Farmers, like other segments of industry are not perfect, but their record
  of complying with the law is substantially better than a few years ago.
  In fact, I have been involved with agriculture for 25 years and there's
  no question workers fare much better today. And, I don't ever remember
  workers being required to &quot;mix pesticides with their hands.&quot;<BR>
  Sincerely,<BR>
  Earl Wells<BR>
  Executive Vice President<BR>
  Florida Nurserymen and Growers Association, Inc.<BR>
  Orlando</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H1><A NAME="anchor749394"></A><BR>
<HR ALIGN=LEFT>LETTERS: <A HREF="#anchor749394">THIS YEAR</A></H1>

<P><BR>
</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Dear Editor:<BR>
  I have been a member of the Republican Party for many years, but I cannot
  believe the ignorance of some congressional leaders. I cannot stand idle
  when a group of narrow-minded politicians steer sound environmental policy
  toward oblivion.<BR>
  Sadly, the list of assaults on environmental issues is very long. Our leaders
  are showing tunnel-vision and lack of education. They seem to care about
  nothing but themselves and the short-term profits of certain industrial
  interests. Our country's long-term health and well-being seem not to matter.<BR>
  <BR>
  As a Floridian, I am especially concerned about the current thinking in
  Congress. By 2020, nearly 70% of the U.S. population will live in coastal
  counties, resulting in increasing stress on the natural resources along
  our coasts. The effects of pressure on the offshore environment are already
  widely felt. Water quality, fisheries yields, and tourist attractions like
  wildlife and coral reefs continue to decline. The frequency of natural
  biological hazards such as red tides continues to increase.<BR>
  <BR>
  Despite scientific evidence that human activity plays an important role
  in modifying weather and global climate, Congress is cutting the tools
  that would help us understand where we're heading environmentally. They
  are chopping funds for education, research, planned and existing environmental
  monitoring systems, and several international treaties and agreements.<BR>
  <BR>
  Leadership that the U.S. used to provide to the rest of the world is slipping
  out of our hands. While we push backwards, Europe, Japan, and even China
  and India are moving ahead, taking leadership away from us in research,
  technology, education, and the ability to manage global natural resources.<BR>
  <BR>
  This is a sad legacy. I recently joined Republicans for Environmental Protection
  (REP) to help address this trend and to help redirect current efforts to
  destroy the place we live in in the name of short-term interests. I encourage
  other concerned Republicans to contact REP at P.O. Box 7073, Deerfield,
  IL 60015.<BR>
  <BR>
  Sincerely,<BR>
  Frank Muller-Karger<BR>
  Associate Professor, Dept. of Marine Science<BR>
  University of South Florida<BR>
  St. Petersburg</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

