<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/for_web.gif" WIDTH="235" HEIGHT="85" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<HR></CENTER>
<H3>Measuring visitors</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Let's face it, life on the Web is a popularity contest. Millions
of people visit the Wired World every day. And, every day, more and more
of the people you depend on for your profitability are asking questions
about Web usage. Questions like: <BR>
<BR>
&quot;How many users are really coming to your Site?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Am I getting the best return on my Web investment?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Sure, you could tell them about the millions of hits and sessions your Site
is drawing. But, more often then not, you'll be asked: <BR>
<BR>
&quot;How does that compare with other Sites?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The way you answer these questions may well define the success of your Web
Site. You could put hundreds of hours and untold dollars into developing
measurement software that answers some of these questions. But then you'd
have to continually invest your resources into upgrading your tracking system
as things change (which they'll constantly do on the Web). And, you'll still
be at the mercy of demands for impartial, standardized measurement. <BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1952210"></A>So, for a standardized <A HREF="netcount_stats4696.html">look
at EnviroWorld's site visitor statistics</A>, NetCount's the place.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
