<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../1996%20news/Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><P><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><H3><A HREF="#anchor338406">Aquifer tax break a burden for counties</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld) -- Voters approved tax breaks for land that  is set aside to recharge aquifers, but some counties that are now faced  with footing the bill are not happy with the plan, The Associated Press  reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Floridians voted in 1988 to make the Bluebelt Law an amendment to the  state Constitution, but it took until last spring for lawmakers to pass  a law to put the plan into action. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Opponents expect the new law to cost more than $50 million a year in  lost tax revenue. The law that took effect Wednesday shifts the burden  of financing the tax exemptions from the state to individual counties.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The law says regional water management districts would determine what  land qualifies as a &quot;high water recharge area,&quot; county commissioners  would decide what sort of exemption each county would grant, and the county  property appraiser would review applications for the exemptions.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>  <A NAME="anchor460870"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT>                                             &nbsp;</P><H3><A HREF="#anchor460870">DEP scientists claim Benlate health effects</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE -- Two Department of Environmental Protection scientists  have asked the agency to investigate whether there has been a cover-up  of possible health effects of the fungicide Benlate, The Associated Press  reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Biologist Mark Murray and geologist Tom Greenhalgh say they have suffered  health problems since a December 1993 visit to a Leesburg nursery where  plants treated with Benlate had died. </P>  <P>Murray, 37, and Greenhalgh, 38, have asked DEP to conduct a criminal  investigation into whether key administrators within state agencies may  have conspired with the DuPont Co. to cover up possible environmental and  health  effects of the fungicide. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Wilmington, Del.-based chemical giant has denied Benlate is harmful  to plants or people, and spokesmen for DuPont said the company would not   comment on Murray and Greenhalgh's allegations. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The two have filed a Workers' Compensation claim with the state blaming  health problems including chronic fungus infections on exposure to an unidentified  chemical or organism at the Benlate-treated nursery. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>It had been nearly three years since Benlate DF was applied at the site.  The recalled fungicide, blamed in 1991 for massive crop damage in 40 states,  was not known to be a human health risk. </P>  <P>DuPont had paid hundreds of millions of dollars in plant damage claims  before announcing in 1992 that its research had absolved Benlate.   </P>  <P> </P>  <P>DEP officials would not comment on the compensation case, but the health  department's chief toxicologist, Roger Inman, denied his agency withheld  information from DEP. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>                                 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </P><P> &nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor466130"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor466130">Florida's wildlife could turn into big business</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ORLANDO--(EnviroWorld)-- Florida has more birds for more of the year  than most of the nation, but some say the state doesn't do enough to attract  birders or other nature lovers, The Associated Press reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Nature tourism is the fastest-growing segment of the U.S. market, increasing  30 percent a year, according to a recent industry study. In a single year,  24.7 million people travel in the United States expressly to watch birds,  a 1995 survey by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service indicates. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Each year, 15 million people travel to see to see birds and other wildlife.  Florida got 944,000 of those visitors. Also, 1.4 million Floridians traveled  within the state to watch wildlife. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Florida already has 28 National Wildlife Refuges, including one of the  most popular bird-watching spots in the world, the J.N. Ding Darling National  Wildlife Refuge on Sanibel Island. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Ding Darling boasts rare species such as the mangrove cuckoo. The refuge  is also home to several showy, easy-to-spot species as the roseate spoonbill,  a big pink wader. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Besides wildlife refuges, Florida has millions of acres of land preserved  in national parks. national forests, state parks and private ranches packed  with wonders of the sort a tourist from Germany or Illinois may never have  seen. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Earlier this year, the state created an office of ecotourism within  the state Division of Recreation and Parks. The office is to oversee cultural  as well  as natural sites and work to tie state parks to nearby hotels  and attractions for joint promotions.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>In conjunction with the new office, an ecotourism advisory committee  is working on a plan for promoting nature-based tourism and protecting  the state's natural resources.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor468701"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor468701">12,000-acre ranch in Osceola preserved by state</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ORLANDO -- (EnviroWorld) -- The St. John's River Water Management District  has obtained easements to a 12,000-acre ranch at the headwaters of the  St. John's River, the Orlando Sentinel reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The owner of the Escape Ranch, which sits along Highway 441 in southeast  Osceola County, will continue to farm sod and raise cattle on the property,  but cannot further develop the land. The easement rights cost $5.8 million,  about one-third of the price of an outright land purchase. Most of the  money, $5.4 million came from the Save Our Rivers program, with $433,000  chipped in through the USDA's Farmland Protection Program.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The ranch includes Six-Mile Creek, Ten-Mile Creek and Wolf Creek and  is heavily wooded. Among the ecosystems present are longleaf pine stands,  flatwoods, dry prairie, live oak hammock, freshwater marsh, and cypress  swamp.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor472009"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor472009">Orange may temporarily ban cell phone towers</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ORLANDO -- (EnviroWorld) -- In response to widespread complaints about  impacts on greenspace, Orange County officials may ban new radio antennas  Tuesday for three months, the Orlando Sentinel reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The move comes as the wireless electronics industry says it will needs  to quadruple the number of towers currently in place nationwide in order  to meet coming needs. There are now about 25,000 towers in the U.S., with  90 in Orange County.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Temporary bans already exist in the Orange County towns of Apopka, Eatonville,  Ocoee and Orange City. Instead of the ban, county officials may allow towers  that comply with stricter placement rules.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
