<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../1996%20news/Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><P><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor338406"><FONT SIZE=+2>U.S. coal production sets record</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>CHARLESTON, W.Va.-- (EnviroWorld) -- Domestic coal production reached  a record 1.07 billion tons in 1996, according to industry estimates released  Monday, The Associated Press reported.The 1996 totals through Dec. 28 surpassed  the 1994 mark of 1.03 billion tons, according to the U.S. Energy Department's  Energy Information Administration.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Production of lignite and bituminous coal last year was 4.1 percent  higher than 1995's production and surpassed 1 billion tons for only the  fourth time ever, the agency said.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Wyoming led the 25 coal-producing states with 279 million tons, comprising  one-fourth of the nation's production. The output was 6 percent higher  than the state's 1995 production.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>West Virginia ranked second with 170 million tons, 4.5 percent higher  than its 1995 output, and Kentucky ranked third with 149 million tons,  down 3 percent from last year, the agency said.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Eastern U.S. production rose 4.3 percent to 566 million tons, while  western production rose 3.7 percent to 504 million tons.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor1350633"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor1350633"><FONT SIZE=+2>Undeveloped waterfront in SouthFlorida sold by FDIC</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>HIGHLAND BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- A rare piece of Florida, undeveloped  southeastern coastline, has been sold to developers for $12.577 million,  the South Florida Business Journal reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Omega Development Group purchased the 17.4-acre tract, which includes  150 feet of oceanfront, from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation  and plans to build three 16-story condominiums on the site.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The land is called &quot;Hidden Harbor,&quot; and was owned from 1980  to 1989 by Paul Hoffman and Broadview Federal Savings. The owners went  bankrupt in the midst of a lawsuit against Highland Beach over zoning agreements.  The Resolution Trust Company then took over the land and the lawsuit, ultimately  receiving $5.5 million in damages from the town. After the Resolution Trust  was dissolved last year, the FDIC gained control of the land.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor1352850"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor1352850"><FONT SIZE=+2>Judge turns down Pinellas watergambit</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>CLEARWATER -- (EnviroWorld) -- A lawsuit brought by Pinellas County  against eight parties that had threatened to sue the county will be heard  in Hernando County, the St. Petersburg Times reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Pinellas attorneys had sought to have the case heard in Pinellas, hoping  for a legal advantage, but circuit Judge James Case ruled the county had  no basis for such a request. The county had argued that the legal residence  of one of the defendants was in Pinellas County; the judge disagreed, and  sent the case to Hernando, where another defendant, the Southwest Florida  Water Management District, is headquartered.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Pinellas County Commissioners filed the suit on the advice of Pinellas  water attorney Ed De la Parte. Defendants in the lawsuit had threatened,  but not yet filed, a class-action lawsuit against Pinellas for damages  to the environment they say were caused by Pinellas' overpumping of wellfields  in Pasco County.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The defendants' attorney, Henry Valenzuela, said the Pinellas lawsuit  had dissuaded other affected residents from joining in the class-action  suit against the county.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor1358805"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor1358805"><FONT SIZE=+2>Ruling favors Jax haz waste disposalfacility</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>JACKSONVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- A judge has ruled that the Jacksonville  City Council improperly denied a zoning exemption for a hazardous waste  disposal facility, the Florida Times-Union Reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The ruling helps American Environmental Services, which wants to locate  the facility in an area of North Jacksonville zoned for heavy industry.  The city is expected to appeal the decision, however.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Retired Circuit Judge Giles Lewis ruled that the city's 2010 comprehensive  plan specifically states a need for a disposal facility to mitigate the  estimated 400 tons of hazardous materials illegally dumped in area landfills  and sewers.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Nearby residents have fought against the facility since 1994.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../1996%20news/index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;