<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT> <BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><P><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor338406">PEER probe in Virginia nets federal investigation</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>GAINESVILLE--(EnviroWorld)-- On Monday, the Inspector General began  an investigation into whether the Virginia Department of Environmental  Quality has been too lenient on air polluters, according to Holland &amp;  Knight's Daily Environmental Report.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A finding that the state agency has not been enforcing the federal law  could result in the EPA taking over the state's air pollution programs.  Virginia officials claim the investigation is politically motivated.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The probe is spurred, in part, by an investigation into Virginia's Department  of Environmental Quality by the watchdog group PEER, Public Employees for  Environmental Responsibility. That probe began last Spring and led to several  spin off investigations by various agencies and contributed to the resignation  of Virginia's top environmental official.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor874873"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor874873">Sustainable communities selected</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)-- Florida Department of Community Affairs  (DCA) Secretary Jim Murley announced Tuesday the five local governments  selected to participate in the Sustainable Communities pilot project enacted  by the 1996 Legislature. The city of Boca Raton, Hillsborough County and  the city of Tampa as joint applicants, the city of Orlando, the city of  Ocala and Martin County were selected from 28 local governments to be designated  as Sustainable Communities and further sound principles of sound land planning  in exchange for reduced state oversight.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The 1996 Legislature enacted the Sustainable Communities demonstration  project to further six broad principles of community planning: restoring  key ecosystems; achieving a more clean, healthy environment; limiting urban  sprawl; protecting wildlife and natural areas; advancing the efficient  use of land; and creating quality communities and jobs. The DCA was designated  to select up to five local governments for participation in the project,  at least three of which must be located all or in part of the South Florida  Water Management District.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor877103"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor877103">Commission works to save landfill</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>INVERNESS--(EnviroWorld)-- Citrus County commissioners are looking for  ways to entice garbage haulers to use the Citrus County Landfill in an  attempt to increase revenue and pay off the remaining $5 million owed on  the facility, the St. Petersburg Times reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The landfill's largest customer, Waste Management Inc., recently started  taking its waste to a private transfer station near Ocala that offers lower  rates. The loss of Waste Management's business decreases the landfill's  regular garbage flow by about 30 percent.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The commission is considering adopting a &quot;fast-track&quot; special  assessment of $30 to $35 per household to temporarily cover the deficit.  They are also considering pursuing franchises with haulers who could guarantee  a flow of trash and money.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor879563"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor879563">Crystal River, Citrus County water deal in sight</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>CRYSTAL RIVER--(EnviroWorld)-- Crystal River and Citrus County may work  out their water-sewer disagreements tomorrow, the St. Petersburg Times  reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The agreement, years in the making, will allow the city to extend sewer  and water lines to areas outside the city limits, filling some excess capacity  at the city sewage treatment plant and generating more revenue for the  city. The county will benefit by having leaky septic tanks hooked into  the sewage treatment system.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Officials for the city and the county agree that environmentally sensitive  areas will have first priority for the extended city sewer and water service.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor881728"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor881728">&quot;Bullet&quot; train looks like a moneytrain </A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)-- Florida's proposed &quot;bullet' train  has hit some skepticism from state senators who balked at the $6.5 billion  state tab, the Miami Herald reported. Senators told Transportation Secretary  Ben Watts he would have trouble selling the deal with questions remaining  over who would ride the train and where the money would come from.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Only two of eight senators on the Senate Transportation Committee expressed  their support for the train at a hearing Tuesday.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Watts will ask the Legislature to approve $6.5 billion over four decades  to build the train. Florida wants Congress to stand behind the billions  of dollars in bonds the Department of Transportation would issue for the  train.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor883696"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor883696">Wildlife center wants to move to Pasco County</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)-- Wildlife Rescue Inc., a non-profit, Tampa-based  wildlife rehabilitation center is looking to move its facility to Pasco  County, the St. Petersburg Times reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The center is currently in battles with government officials and its  urban neighbors at its current Hiawatha Street location due to odors and  noise. The center would like to find a more hospitable home for the animals  in a natural habitat.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The director for the center, Bill Tingley, is trying to persuade east  Pasco County landowners to donate a site.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The center is in danger of losing its license due to allegations of  inadequate facilities. A hearing is scheduled for today to determine if  the center has violated the federal Animal Welfare Act.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The center is home to injured native wildlife such as raccoons, squirrels,  owls and two endangered Florida panthers.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
