Bay before man's alteration of the  landscape. The corps will also punch holes in mounds along the C-111 canal  to further mimic natural flow patterns.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Officials said not to expect improvements overnight, but, as the restoration  progresses, populations of wading birds, fish and crocodiles should increase,  and the health of seagrass beds should improve.</P>  <P><A NAME="anchor751002"></A></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor751002"><FONT SIZE=+2>Water Managers to host Evergladesconstruction workshop</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WEST PALM BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- The South Florida Water Management  District will host a construction workshop Jan. 10 at 1 p.m. for contracting  firms interested in bidding on Everglades reconstruction projects.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Presentations will include in-depth descriptions of work, schedule requirements  and business procedures.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The principal components of the projects are six stormwater treatment  areas with levees, canals, pumping stations and water control structures.  The District predicts about $200 million will be spent on various projects  in the next four years. Bid deadlines are set throughout the first six  months of 1997, with bids for Inflow and Distribution of Works for Stormwater  Treatment Area 1 due in January, and bids for Works in STA-1W due in February.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>For more information on the workshop, call 561-687-6126.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor752473"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor752473"><FONT SIZE=+2>Four Collier men catch lots ofmullet, get arrested</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P> NAPLES -- (EnviroWorld) -- Kent Brown must have hoped Marine Patrol  officials would simply take him for a very good fisherman. Only 45 minutes  into legal mullet harvesting time, officers found 10,150 pounds of mullet  on his boat, the Naples Daily News reported. Perhaps skeptical by nature,  the officers assumed Kent had got an early start. They seized the fish  and charged Kent with possession of mullet during the weekend closure,  when commercial harvesting is prohibited. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Three other men were also charged in another case. Collier County sheriff's  deputies arrested George Hamilton, Ronald Easterly and Shane Arthur when  they found the trio with 792 pounds of mullet and 400 yards of entangling  net on a 19-foot fishing boat in the Marco River.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The fish did not escape, either. Both catches were sold, with the money  to be held in escrow until the men's cases are completed.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor754847"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor754847"><FONT SIZE=+2>Manatee Sludge haulers grantedextension</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>Manatee County -- (EnviroWorld) -- According to a law set to take effect  Jan. 1, Manatee County sludge haulers were supposed to obtain county permits,  but Environmental Management Director Karen Collins recently granted a  six-month extension to seven sludge haulers, drawing the ire of some commissioners,  the Bradenton Herald reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Collins said the extensions were necessary because of a federal agency's  recent recommendation that phosphorous take the place of nitrogen as the  guiding soil contamination measurement. The action was not properly communicated  to the County Commission, however, which Collins blamed on the holidays.</P>  <P> </P>  <P>The explanation did not appease Commissioner Joe McClash. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;It amazes me how we could pass a law and a director would decide  not to enforce the law because of (problems with) one section,&quot;  McClash  said.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Other commissioners said they only learned of the extensions in the  newspaper.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Residents of the community of Duette have been complaining for years  about heavy truck traffic on their rural roads and unpleasant odors resulting  from massive sludge dumping near their homes. Their complaints prompted  the new laws which require detailed operation and conservation plans of  the haulers.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Although Commissioners fear they cannot retract the extension granted  by Collins, they are hoping to find a way to solve the sludge problem indefinitely  to prevent similar situations from occurring.  The long-term solution proposed  is an upgrade in the county's level of sewage treatment. The upgrade would  be expensive, but the result would be high quality sludge that causes no  environmental problems and can also be used as fertilizer.  </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor757317"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor757317"><FONT SIZE=+2>Another dredge for Clam Bay mangrovesrestoration</FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>NAPLES -- (EnviroWorld) -- Consultants will ask for another Band-aid  in their efforts to restore a mangrove forest in Clam Bay, the Naples Daily  News reported. As has happened each spring for several years, consultants  hired to restore about 46 acres of mangroves will rush a request through  state and federal regulators for emergency permits to dredge sand in Clam  Pass. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Due to the development, water flow through Clam Bay has been altered,  causing Clam Pass to repeatedly clog with sand, and mangroves to die. The  die-off was first noticed in 1992, and has spread from 7.4 acres to its  present size. Scientists with the consulting team said the short-term dredging  is necessary until a more permanent, environmentally acceptable alternative  can be found.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Restoration efforts have shown some signs of success. Saltwort has taken  root in ten-acres of dead mangroves. Colonization by that plant improves  soil conditions and helps mangrove seeds take root.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
