ministration in implementing the new law.  &quot;It changes the paradigm on how we deal with drinking water in the  United States.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor64567"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor64567">Tit for tat: DEP probes PEER</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)--EXCLUSIVE--by Dave Newport, Editor--If one  secret of a good defense is a good offense, then the Florida Department  of Environmental Protection is responding well to the investigation of  its management by a group called PEER, Public Employees for Environmental  Responsibility, a national environmental employee watchdog organization.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Two months ago, PEER announced plans to investigate &quot;numerous allegations&quot;  it had received that DEP staff had been instructed to deliberately violate  or stretch standards or policies in order to benefit certain members of  the regulated community, according to PEER field director Tom Weis. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>But before PEER got started with its investigation, DEP's investigators  probed PEER. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>According to an internal PEER memo obtained by EnviroWorld, DEP Crime  Intelligence Analyst Priscilla Zachary called PEER in late November and,  without identifying her objective, began &quot;fishing,&quot; the memo  states. PEER staffer Rob Perks fielded the first call. After he sensed  the call had a hidden agenda, he joked with Zachary that she must be doing  &quot;opposition research,&quot; the memo continues. At that point, she  admitted she was with DEP &quot;internal investigations&quot; and that  &quot;the Secretary [Wetherell] asked us to check into your group.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Zachary, a retired Air Force Captain, had just been hired by DEP after  20 years in the military. Her military background includes stints as &quot;Senior  terrorist analyst primarily responsible for Europe, Middle East, and Africa...[and]  liaison with CIA, DIA, FBI,&quot; and related intelligence organizations,  according to her state personnel records.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Zachary's boss says it was not investigation, but an &quot;inquiry.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;We want to see what the credibility of the group is,&quot; says  DEP inspector General Pinky Hall, who oversees the internal investigations  unit.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Hall denies that Wetherell authorized the probe but does admit that  Zachary may have cited the Secretary's name.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;It's kind of a standard way to get information on the phone,&quot;  Hall told EnviroWorld.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Zachary's direct supervisor, Major Roy Dickey, said it was DEP Chief  Counsel Perry Odom who asked about PEER although &quot;we do work under  the authority of the Secretary.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;We're trying to find out what their [PEER's] role is,&quot; Dickey  said. &quot;If allegations are made that DEP employees have violated the  law, it is our job to investigate those allegations.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Dickey said he had a staff of five sworn law enforcement officers, who  worked 122 cases in 1996. The cases all involve DEP employees and range  from trivial to criminal. The officers have access to state and federal  law enforcement computers through which background checks can be run on  the employees involved. Dickey said no such background check was run on  any PEER personnel.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>DEP spokesperson Joy Mills said the PEER inquiry was &quot;natural background  work.&quot; She said she &quot;doubted&quot; that Wetherell had authorized  the Inspector General's inquiry. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;Heck, I got on the Internet and looked for some information about  who they are and so forth,&quot; Mills said.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>In December, the Washington D.C.-based PEER began their probe by sending  surveys to DEP employees' homes, conducting brown bag meetings with DEP  employees and investigating complaints privately. PEER has conducted several  similar probes of other state and federal environmental agencies. [See  related story published 1-8-97].</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><BR></B></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor256765"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor256765">Survey: DEP staffers cite poor morale as topagency problem</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)--EXCLUSIVE--By Dave Newport, Editor-- State  environmental agency employees are ready to talk - and write - about the  the lack of worker morale and instances of alleged favoritism in granting  permits, according to a national group investigating Florida's top enviro  agency.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The national environmental employee watchdog group PEER, Public Employees  for Environmental Responsibility, last month circulated a questionnaire  to Florida Department of Environmental Protection employees asking for  their opinions on a range of issues regarding DEP's performance.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;They are pouring in,&quot; said PEER attorney Jeff Ruch. &quot;We've  received about 1,200 so far. About 20 a day are still coming in,&quot;  Ruch told EnviroWorld in early January.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>PEER in early December sent out over 3,400 surveys to DEP employees'  homes. The survey is part of PEER's investigation of allegations that DEP  leaders order staff to violate or stretch environmental rules in order  to favor certain members of the regulated community.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>DEP secretary Virginia Wetherell has pledged full agency cooperation  with PEER in its investigation.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Ruch says that PEER is in &quot;very heavy tabulation&quot; mode with  the surveys. &quot;We haven't seen such a heavy response since we did [EPA]  Region 1,&quot; Ruch said. &quot;There we had about 60 percent response.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>With over a 35 percent response rate and counting, Ruch said a few trends  are beginning to emerge. According to an analysis of over 400 surveys'  comments, the top DEP problem areas are:</P>  <P>1) Poor staff morale was the highest rated concern.</P>  <P>2) Lingering concerns over the merger of the two environmental agencies  that created the DEP.</P>  <P>3) Mismanagement: Many negative comments about TQL [Total Quality Leadership].</P>  <P>4) Environmental ethics and enforcement concerns.</P>  <P>5) Ecosystem management: concerns that the concept may be good but implementation  is suspect.</P>  <P>6) Leadership: concerns that top DEP officials don't put the environment's  best interest first.</P>  <P>7) Key people: &quot;Nevin Smith's name comes up the most,&quot; Ruch  said.</P>  <P>8) Political pressure: concerns that environmental decision-making at  DEP is inappropriately swayed by legislators and the Governor.</P>  <P>9) Funding, a lack thereof and poor allocation of what's left.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The bright spot seems to be the Parks and Recreation people, Ruch allowed.  &quot;That isn't surprising given that their jobs didn't change much if  any as a result of the merger.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Also last month PEER had a series of brown bag meetings at DEP districts  in central and north Florida. Turnout at the meetings by DEP employees  was spotty - high at some, low at others. DEP spokesperson Joy Mills said  the low turnouts were indicative of the fact that DEP employees don't have  many concerns.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Ruch said the opposite has proven to be true.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;Well attended meetings seem to happen in offices that are running  well,&quot; Ruch told EnviroWorld. &quot;On the other hand, at offices  where only a few employees showed up we get horror stories that would curl  your hair later when we talk with employees privately.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Ruch said the complete analysis of the survey will be unveiled at a  Tallahassee press conference on January 22. Following that, PEER will move  to south Florida and visit DEP district offices there.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;We're on step two of about a 30-step process,&quot; Ruch said.  &quot;We want to set up a long term public laundry for dirty linen. It  takes time.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor261016"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor261016">Australian weevil to rid Everglades of invasivetrees</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>FORT LAUDERDALE--(EnviroWorld)-- State and federal officials plan to  release scores of Australian beetles into the Everglades to reduce the  number of invasive trees, The Associated Press reported. Melaleucca weevils  are expected to be released in about three weeks.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Melaleucca trees were imported from Australia in 1906 for use in landscaping.  In the 1930s, a nursery owner flew over the Everglades and dropped thousands  of seeds in hopes of growing trees for lumber. The trees now infest about  500,000 acres of the Everglades, growing so thick in some areas that deer  can not run in between them.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor262709"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor262709">CFCs becoming black market jewel</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WASHINGTON--(EnviroWorld)-- A banned chemical linked to the destruction  of Earth's ozone layer is joining narcotics as the most lucrative contraband  for smugglers, The Associated Press reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Justice Department announced indictments Thursday charging more  than a dozen people in five states with smuggling into the U.S. containers  of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), a refrigerant used in millions of auto air  conditioners. Much of the chemical is smuggled in from Mexico.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>CFCs bring $13 to $20 a pound in the U.S.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The chemical is to be phased out globally under a 1987 treaty, but poor  countries can use the product until 2010.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor264396"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor264396">Net ban arrests increase</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)-- The Florida Marine Patrol has stepped up  arrests of fishermen who violate the state net ban, the Gainesville Sun  reported. FMP has made 610 arrests since the ban took effect July 1, 1995.  More than half of those arrests have been made in the last four months.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>One reason the arrest rate is so high is because November and December  are the peak months for catching mullet filled with eggs. The roe is sold  to Asian countries at a high profit.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Net ban supporters say that the penalties for a conviction should be  stronger. The current penalty is a $500 fine and up to 60 days in jail,  but there are variations in how Florida counties punish for the violation.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Prosecutors now have the option of bringing civil sanctions against  major violators of the net ban. Beginning Jan. 1, prosecutors can punish  offenders with a $2,500 fine and suspension of a saltwater products license  for 90 days.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A second offense within seven years could net violators a $5,000 fine  and a one year suspension of a saltwater products license. A third violation  could result in a $5,000 fine and lifetime revocation of a saltwater products  license.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
