d on the agreement is expected in early 1997 and a Proposed  Rule in the fall.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>If adopted, the standards are expected to reduce hydrocarbon plus nitrogen  oxide emissions by approximately 40 percent from the Phase 1 levels, which  become effective with the 1997 model year.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Manufacturers are putting a special emphasis on cleaner, more durable  engine technology, such as over-head valve (OHV) technology with superior  combustion chamber and cylinder head design to ensure that emission reductions  continue for the life of the equipment.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The EPA has signed a separate agreement with Briggs &amp; Stratton Corp.  and Tecuemseh Products Co., calling for an OHV demonstration program.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The manufacturers also agreed to a voluntary fuel spillage reduction  program that educates consumers about the significant contribution to air  pollution from fuel spillage and develops  technology to reduce spills  by users.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor500911"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor500911">Endocrine disruptors strike again: transsexualfish in Fenholloway</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>PERRY -- Female fish in North Florida's Fenholloway River are developing  male sex organs, and researchers warn it could hurt the food chain, spread  to other species, and affect people who eat fish, The Associated Press  reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The cause, they say, is pollution from an upstream paper mill that may  soon be pumping its wastes directly into the Gulf of Mexico.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Researchers at the University of West Florida and the U.S. Environmental  Protection Agency say the mutations have shown up in three fish species  so far. But what worries EPA and university researchers is a recently announced  cleanup plan.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The mill plans to pump its treated waste through a 15-mile pipeline  to the mouth of the Fenholloway.There, the waste would be diluted as it  flowed into the Gulf of Mexico.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The state has announced its intention to issue a permit for the pipeline.  And now people have two weeks, beginning today, to request a hearing on  the permit by contacting the Department of Environmental Protection.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Piping the plant's waste to the Fenholloway estuary ``could have a very  broad effect,'' said Stephen Bortone, a University of West Florida professor  who has been studying the river for more than a decade.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Bortone and his colleagues have tied the fish deformities to pulp mill  waste, but they do not know which compound causes the phenomenon, and they  do not know what effect it may have in an estuary, which is a marine nursery.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Plant officials say the waste would have less impact on the environment  if it could be diluted. But some critics call the pipeline project a '40s  solution to a '90s pollution problem. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Phil Coram, the state Department of Environmental Protection's permitting  chiefsaid the waste that will coming out of the new pipe will be cleaner  than what flows out of the Fenholloway into the gulf now.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>But researchers studying the deformed fish say that whatever is making  the female fish look and act like males could get into the food chain and  spread to marine species in the gulf.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Wil Davis, a researcher in the Gulf Breeze laboratory of the U.S. Environmental  Protection Agency, calls the pipeline &quot;an out-of-sight, out-of-mind  approach to something that needs close attention.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;If you take 50 million gallons of wastewater every day out of  a river and put it in the gulf, you've just created a new situation,&quot;  Davis said. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor502665"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor502665">Wanted: new chief for Swiftmud </A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>BROOKSVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Southwest Florida Water Management  District may pick a new executive director by Jan. 29 to replace Pete Hubbell,  whose last day was Friday, the Tampa Tribune reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Of 140 applicants for the job, eight finalists have been chosen.Those  finalists are expected to be interviewed Jan. 20 and 21, and the District's  governing board could make a final choice at its Jan. 29 meeting. The choice  would still have to be approved by the state Senate, so the earliest start  date for Hubbell's replacement is March.</P>  <P> </P>  <P>Hubbell and Swiftmud's number two man ,Mark Farrell, both left the agency  to start a private consulting company, Water Resources Associates. Hubbell  worked for Swiftmud for 19 years, and served as executive director for  eight.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor504324"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor504324">Water supplier gets extension to pump stressedwellfield</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>DARBY -- (EnviroWorld) -- West Coast Regional Water Supply Authority  has been granted a third deadline extension to file for a new permit on  the Cross Bar Ranch, meaning that current pumping levels will continue  at the Pasco County wellfield until Feb. 28, the Tampa Tribune reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Southwest Florida Water Management District denied another request  to allow pumping to continue at the wellfield until minimum flows and levels  for that area are set, which is expected in late 1997. Agency officials  also said that additional extensions would not be granted to the Authority.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The District and the Authority are in the midst of a legal battle over  pumping at the Pasco wellfield. District scientists and local residents  blame overpumping for the drying up of local wetlands and other ecological  problems. An Authority spokesman said that cutting pumping levels could  have drastic effects on the humans who now depend on the water.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor505695"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor505695">Miami looks to other countries for beach replenishment</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>MIAMI BEACH--(EnviroWorld)-- Florida may begin importing sand from other  countries to renourish its eroding beaches, the Orlando Sentinel reported.  More than a third of Florida's coastline is classified as &quot;critically  eroding.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Florida's beaches lose sand due to the ebb and flow of water on the  Atlantic and Gulf coasts and direct hits from hurricanes, and as a consequence  of shoreline development. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers periodically  dredges sand from offshore and pumps it back onto the beaches, but offshore  supplies of sand are becoming thin. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Miami is now looking to other countries to supply them with sand for  replenishment. The Turks and Caicos, a British colony south of the Bahamas,  has agreed to sell Miami about a billion tons of sand. The sand is not  an exact match to the sand of Miami Beach, though, and scientists worry  that  it may have disrupting effects.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Nesting sea turtles may not like the different color, texture and temperature  of the foreign sand. Miami Beach is currently testing the sand for compatibility  with the turtles that nest on the beaches each year. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor507830"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor507830">Dead right whale found at Flagler Beach</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>FLAGLER BEACH--(EnviroWorld)-- The carcass of a northern right whale  was found at Flagler Beach Thursday and taken to Marineland for a necropsy,  the Florida Times-Union reported. Scientists believe there are only about  300 right whales alive today.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>This is the first documented death of one of the whales this year in  the winter calving grounds. Biologists found no outer markings that would  indicate the cause of death.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor509671"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor509671">Wildlife Rescue founder in court</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)-- Bert Wahl, founder of Wildlife Rescue, Inc.,  was in court last week on charges that he violated federal animal welfare  regulations, the Tampa Tribune reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The U.S. Department of Agriculture has charged that Wahl violated the  Animal Welfare Act by failing to provide adequate shelter for animals at  Wildlife Rescue, among other things.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Wahl has been cited several times since 1992 for poor record keeping,  inadequate food storage and inadequate facilities. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Wahl has run the nonprofit center out of his home since 1982. Native  wildlife, including bobcats, owls and panthers, are caged in his backyard.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>If Wahl loses the case, he could be fines or his federal license to  care for animals could be revoked.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor513082"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor513082">Conch Republic creating plan to save Keys reef</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>FLORIDA KEYS--(EnviroWorld)-- The Conch Republic is trying to come up  with an alternate plan for protecting the Keys reef as environmentalists  and managers for the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary gear up for  a final pitch to the governor and Cabinet, the Miami Herald reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>In November, Keys voters said by a 55 percent margin that they did not  want a Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary. The governor and the Cabinet  will consider the sanctuary management plan later this month. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Twenty-one groups agreed to attend last weekend's conference including  the Marathon Chamber of Commerce, the Marathon Guides Association, Reef  Relief, the Conch Coalition, and the Key West Chamber of Commerce.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Today, Cabinet aides have a meeting scheduled for 1 to 5 p.m. in Tallahassee  to take public testimony about the sanctuary management plan. The governor  and Cabinet are scheduled to look at the plan Jan. 28.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor514890"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor514890">Windermere residents may be getting new watersupplier</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WINDERMERE--(EnviroWorld)-- Windermere residents with high levels of  radium in their water may be getting a new drinking water supplier, the  Orlando Sentinel reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Orange County commissioners will decide Tuesday whether to sell water  to Utilities Inc. of Florida, the supplier for 41 residents in Windermere.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Utilities Inc. discovered the radium contamination during routine water  testing. It is unknown how long the radium has been present in the water.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>If commissioners approve the plan, Utilities Inc. will take their wells  off line and abandon them, receiving all water from the county.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor517031"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor517031">Renovating phosphate plant receives opposition</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>SUN CITY--(EnviroWorld)-- A phosphate fertilizer plant at Piney Point  that may be renovated instead of replaced has critics of its environmental  record uneasy, the Tampa Tribune reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The environmental group ManaSota-88 is currently reviewing ways to prevent  Piney Point Phosphate from reopening. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The plant closed in 1992. The year before, the plant suffered a sulfur  spill that made many people sick and an acid spill that forced the evacuation  of Port of Manatee, the Manatee County stockade and nearby homes and businesses.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Some environmentalists and county commissioners say they would be more  comfortable with rebuilding the plant instead of renovating the existing  facility. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The plant's owner, Mulberry Phosphates, and the state Department of  Environmental Protection are stalled on permits for a new plant due to  concerns over sulfur dioxide emissions and whether the site's phosphogypsum  stack is leaking radioactive water into groundwater supplies.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Officials from both organizations met last month to begin discussing  the possibility of renovating the plant for $17 million instead of rebuilding  it. <BR>  </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</