<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT> <BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><P><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor338406"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Insurers say soft drinks arepollutants, won't cover damages</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WEST PALM BEACH--(EnviroWorld)--Insurance companies in Palm Beach and  Broward are trying to avoid responsibility for covering damages caused  by many legal substances by classifying them as pollutants, The Associated  Press reported. Included among these substances are household names like  Coca Cola and Clorox.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Although a state appeals court has agreed with insurers in two cases,  attorneys say that by taking the side of the insurance companies, a major  section of most general liability policies for workers, and eventually  homeowners, would be ignored. Attorneys fear that siding with insurance  companies in this case would weaken the security that policyholders think  they are buying when they purchase insurance. Policyholders would then  be more vulnerable to uninsured damage claims based on virtually any substance.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Lawyers for insurance, farming and other interests agree that, if the  issue is not clearly settled in court, the state Department of Insurance  may be forced to ask companies to rewrite their definition of pollution.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Florida Supreme Court plans to review the issue immediately.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor756418"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor756418"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>The other South Florida viesfor ecosystem</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=+2> <B>restoration dollars</B></FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>NAPLES -- (EnviroWorld) -- Projects that restore water flow on the western  side of South Florida are well represented on an initial ranking list for  federal dollars, the Naples Daily News reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Water Resources Development Act authorizes $75 million for South  Florida Ecosystem restoration, and, out of 80 projects, five in Collier  County rank in the top 15.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Some of the money may partially fund the buyout of 38,000 acres of the  uninhabited development Golden Gate Estates. Canals in the area have damaged  the local estuary, and seriously slowed aquifer recharge. The project is  also ranked high to receive some of the $200 million available from the  1996 Farm Bill. Officials said $37.5 million was needed to finish the land  buyout for the project, with $12.1 million needed to restore natural water  flows.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Other high-ranking Southwest Florida projects include phosphorous removal  projects for Seminole reservation water, an impact study of U.S. 41, a  land buyout in Bonita Springs and Belle Meade, muck removal at Lake Trafford,  and exotic plant removal from the Estero Bay Aquatic Preserve.</P>  <P>                                                     </P>  <P>Final project rankings will depend, in part, on the recommendations  of the Governor's Commission for a Sustainable South Florida, which meets  Feb. 4 and Feb. 5 in West Palm Beach to hear public comment.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor758171"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor758171"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Compromise reached on Lake Talquindrawdown</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Florida Game and Freshwater Fish  Commission reached a compromise with local residents and anglers on plans  for a drawdown of a popular bass-fishing lake, the Tallahassee Democrat  reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Commission approved a new plan Friday that reduces the drawdown  from 17 feet to 10 feet. Opponents to the project had argued that past  drawdowns killed many fish in the process and left an ugly lake. But agency  officials said the drawdown would restore natural aquatic vegetation that  creates good habitat to restore populations of bass, bream and crappie.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The drawdown is scheduled to begin Dec. 1, and fishing will be banned  through April 1, 1998. Officials said bass populations could rise by 700  percent as a result of the project. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor759759"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor759759"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Final tally in for sugar taxcampaign spending</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE-- (EnviroWorld) -- Total spending on Florida's sugar tax  passed $37.9 million, more than the estimated $36 million the tax would  have raised annually,The Associated Press reported. The spending on the  sugar tax more than doubled the previous Florida record for campaign expenditures.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A month before Election Day, spending had moved into the record-setting  zone.  Citizens To Save Jobs and Stop Unfair Taxes spent almost $19.4 million.  About 88 percent of the money came from the Sugar industry -- U.S. Sugar  Corp., Flo-Sun Inc. and the Florida Sugar Cane Growers Cooperative.  Save  Our Everglades spent $13.9 million, with $11.5 million coming from Paul  Tudor Jones, a Wall Street commodities trader.  </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor761711"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor761711"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Opposition rises to Georgiatitanium mine</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>GEORGIA -- (EnviroWorld) -- Formal opposition to Du Pont's plan to mine  ore near the Okefenokee Wildlife Refuge was voiced yesterday by a regional  committee of the Sierra Club, The Florida Times-Union reported.  The committee's  major concern is the harmful effect of ground water to the surrounding  wetlands when drilling causes it to surge upward.  </P>  <P><B></B>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Du Pont wishes to begin drilling in 2002 in order to extract titanium-bearing  ore from Trail Ridge, adjacent  to the refugee's eastern boundary. Officials  of Du Pont say that  ground water will fill the pit and a floating dredge  will separate the minerals from the sand.  They claim the sand will immediately  be filled back into the pit and timber companies will begin to replant  trees. However, environmental groups such as the Georgia Chapter Sierra  Club and the Ogeechee Audubon Society argue that it is impossible to predict  the effects that a change in water level will have on the landscape and  plant and animal life. Refuge officials have voiced their concern over  the use of pesticides and herbicides once the trees are replanted.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor763218"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor763218"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Lake Isleworth constructionhalted</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>SOUTHWEST ORANGE COUNTY --(EnviroWorld) -- Orange County's plan to build  a boat ramp on the Butler Chain of Lakes has been halted by three homeowners  in  the neighborhood of Isleworth, the Orlando Sentinel  reported.  The  homeowners claim that the ramp at Keene's Point Park would increase boat  traffic on the small lake, and lead to noise, pollution, and environmental  damage.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The South Florida Water Management District had been expected to approve  a permit Thursday for the boat ramp and other amenities along Lake Isleworth.  Since the Butler Chain of Lakes is listed as an Outstanding Florida Water,  the state cannot permit activity which may harm water quality. It is the  county's responsibility to prove to an administrative hearing officer that  the ramp will not harm the lake.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
