tion over water pumping rights.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Hillsborough County and New Port Richey were expected to vote on the  matter either Tuesday night or today.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The plan calls for the creation of a regional water utility that would  serve Pinellas, Hillsborough and Pasco counties, New Port Richey, Tampa  and St. Petersburg. The new utility would own all the wellfields, all equipment  and pipes, and would supply the three-county area customers with water  at a uniform rate. That rate has not yet been set.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The new plan would largely eliminate local legal battles over water  rights. Pinellas County has spent nearly $4 million in the past three years  to fight water wars.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Pinellas County rates will almost definitely go up. The increased rates  would be discounted for 15 years by credits given to the county for deeding  over its wellfield rights and water supply facilities. But Pinellas, an  area that does not expect much growth in the next few decades, would have  to share in the cost of developing new water facilities for the fast growing  Hillsborough and Pasco counties.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The alternative to the utility is to break up the existing water cooperative  and allow each county to go its own way. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor40726"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor40726">Cement plant opponents continue fight, despitesetbacks</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Although the state Department of Environmental  Protection has given its blessing, a local opposition group will continue  its attempt to block construction of a cement plant in western Alachua  County, the Gainesville Sun reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A lawyer for the Haile Community Association filed an appeal of the  air pollution permit Jan. 6, arguing that hearings for the permit were  unfair to his group. The association has strong local support, and believes  the plant could threaten air and water quality in the environmentally sensitive  area.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The plant's site plan must still be approved by the county. A preliminary  site plan was found unacceptable by county environmental staff, who want  continuous emissions monitoring at the plant.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Opponents of the plant have also gathered enough signatures to place  a clean air ordinance on the 1998 ballot, but whether the law would affect  the proposed plant is in doubt.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor42550"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor42550">Suwannee water district agrees to buy AtsenaOtie Key</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>LIVE OAK -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Suwannee River Water Management District's  board agreed to pay $3.1 million for a group of islands off Cedar Key,  the Gainesville Sun reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The strong ranking of the town and county to receive a Florida Communities  Trust Grant appear to have helped the District's board agree to the purchase.The  District had signed an option to buy Atsena Otie Key in September, but  wants to sell it back to the town of Cedar Key and Levy County. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A private development group now owns the land and has been threatening  to build homes on two of the Key's islands. Water district officials cited  concerns that water pollution would result from residential septic tanks  as the main reason for buying Atsena Otie.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Department of Environmental Protection had previously attempted  to buy the land, but could not come to an agreement with developers. The  $3.1 million purchase price was the highest of three appraisals done on  the land for the water management district.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor49122"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor49122">New Arbor Day slogan: chop a tree today</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Residents of North Central Florida are  being urged to cut down a tree this Arbor Day, specifically the Chinese  Tallow Tree, The Associated Press reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The popular ornamental tree is considered an exotic nuisance here, and  has begun to spread on a state wetlands preserve south of Gainesville.  Paynes Prairie staff kill about 1,000 of the &quot;popcorn trees&quot;  every year, but birds and rainfall continue to bring the tallow's seeds  from urban areas.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The trees grow on open marsh, destroying feeding ground habitat for  bald eagles, wood storks and sandhill cranes. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor50730"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor50730">Jax naval sites nominated for enviro awards</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>JACKSONVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Nominations for 1996 Navy Environmental  awards include several Jacksonville commands. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Naval Air Station Jacksonville will compete for Environmental Quality,  Recycling and Environmental Cleanup awards at the installation level as  a representative of the Atlantic Fleet. NAS Cecil Field will compete for  awards in the &quot;non-industrial installation&quot; category, and Naval  Submarine Base Kings Bay will compete in the &quot;small installation category.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>In addition, Puerto Rico's Roosevelt Roads Naval Station and NAS Key  West, both of which report to Jacksonville, were recognized for  Natural  Resources Conservation and Environmental Cleanup, respectively.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>On the individual level, Frank Space, NAS Jacksonville's recycling manager,  was selected to compete for individual honors.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor52045"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor52045">Engineering company hires additional staff</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WINTER PARK -- (EnviroWorld) -- Louis Berger &amp; Associates, Inc.  is expanding its transportation expertise in Central and South Florida  and, therefore, has added three senior level professionals to focus on  transportation planning, design and construction management.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Frank Caruso,has been named area transportation manager and Orlando  office manager. He has 25 years of management and transportation engineering  experience working in the public and private sectors.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Gerald Warren has been named senior project manager transportation services.   He has 16 years experience with public sector transportation projects  and private land development projects.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Kenneth Dunne has been named senior project manager of construction  services.  He has 20 years of experience in civil and structural engineering  in construction of roads, bridges, railroads, mass transit and marine facilities  projects.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor53169"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor53169">HTI relocates</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>MATLACHA -- (EnviroWorld) -- The corporate headquarters for Horizontal  Technologies Incorporated has relocated to Matlacha, Fla.  The new address  is 4767 Pine Island Rd. NW, Matlacha, FL 33993.  Phone: 941-283-5640, Fax:  941-283-2222, E-mail:  info@horizontal.com.  The company also has recently  opened an office in Oak Ridge, Tenn.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor54526"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor54526">Disney project winds down</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ORLANDO -- (EnviroWorld) --The Berger Group and The Hardaway Company  design team have neared completion of a $12 million contract awarded by  Lake Buena Vista Properties.  The project includes construction of two  1,000-foot-long parallel bridges and one mile roadway to serve as the main  entrance to Disney's Animal Kingdom Park expected to open in 1998.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Berger Group is an international engineering firm specializing in  all areas of engineering, construction management, program management,  planning, environmental sciences, cultural resources, economics and information  services.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Hardaway Company specializes in construction of roads and bridges,  industrial plants, marine facilities and power generation plants.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor55848"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor55848">Conference focuses on sustainable farming</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>GAINESVILLE -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Sixth Annual Southern Sustainable  Agriculture Working Group Conference &amp; Trade Show will be held Jan.  16-18 at the Radisson Hotel in Gainesville, Fla.  Hosted by the Florida  Certified Organic Growers and Consumers, a member of Southern SAWG, this  event will bring together farmers, exhibitors and speakers who are working  to create a more sustainable environment in the South.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The conference begins at 1:00 and an admission fee of $30 is required.   For more information, call the Florida Organic Growers at 352-377-6345.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
