  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor796996"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor796996"><FONT SIZE=+3>OK for Delray to can proposedrecycling center, say judges</FONT></A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>DELRAY BEACH--(EnviroWorld)--Judges decided this week that Delray Beach  has the right to deny the Solid Waste Authority its plans for a new recycling  center, the Ft. Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The site was planned for a 7.5-acre site on Congress Avenue.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The Solid Waste Authority will ask the judges to rehear the case and  reconsider their ruling, but a waste authority attorney was doubtful that  the judges would give the case a second chance.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Discussion about the possibility of a different site have been put off  while the district waits to hear back from the judges.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor801054"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor801054"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Extended deadline for sludgehaulers stands</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>MANATEE COUNTY--(EnviroWorld)--The decision of the Manatee County environmental  management director to extend the permitting deadline for local sludge  haulers was maintained by county commissioners this week, the Bradenton  Herald reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Some commissioners were upset to learn that Environmental Management  Director Karen Collins gave exemptions a new ordinance that was passed  in July to delay the permitting process. However, they decided against  reversing her decision in hopes of avoiding any possible legal action that  might ensue.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Collins told commissioners on Tuesday that her decision to grant the  six-month permit extension was based on concerns about soil contamination  measurement processes. A federal environmental agency recently declared  that contaminants should be measured by phosphorous content, and not nitrogen  content, which was the previously established norm.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Collins argued that because phosphorous occurs naturally in local soils,  using that same chemical to measure contamination could cause big changes  in enforcing the ordinance. Under the  terms of the new ordinance, permits  were due by Jan. 1 but Collins extended the deadline for haulers, making  July the new due date for submitting the plans needed for a permit.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Because county law granted Collins the power to order extensions, commissioners  could not reverse her action.  However, many commissioners felt that Collins'  action attacked the regulatory efforts of the local ordinance.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Commissioners have planned a work session on Jan. 21 to discuss the  implications of the new sludge ordinance. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor803133"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor803133"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Decision on Alachua's cementplant grows closer</FONT></B></A><B>   </B> </P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ALACHUA COUNTY -- (EnviroWorld) -- Alachua County's Development Review  </P>  <P>Committee announced that they will reach the final decision regarding  the building of a controversial cement plant on January 30, the Gainesville  Sun reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Final approval was scheduled to take place on Wednesday but was delayed  due to action taken by the Haile Community Association, a group opposed  to the construction. An attorney for the association said he had not seen  the written opinion of the Environmental Protection Department regarding  the plant until 9 p.m. Tuesday night.   </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Although opponents of the plant wish to continue the hearing in order  to prepare testimony from experts, the committee will allow only written  comments until January 23.  The recommended approval of the plan by the  Environmental Protection Department rests on the company's adherence to  certain testing requirements which the company continues to object to.  These requirements include monitoring for hazardous metals in fuel oil  and additional monitoring for dangerous dioxins in air emissions.  Other  than the site plan approval, the company has received all other necessary  permits to begin construction on the plant. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><B> </B></P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor805205"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor805205"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Graham's opposition to sugartax not forgotten  </FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WEST PALM BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- Sen. Graham won't be asked to make  speeches during a three-day national symposium on the Everglades beginning  today, The Associated Press reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Graham has frequently spoken at the Everglades Coalition's yearly meetings,  and Coalition leaders wanted to invite him to speak again at the 1997 meeting  in Deerfield Beach. But some members objected because of Graham's opposition  last year to the ammendment.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Coalition Chairman Ron Tipton, who favored inviting Graham to the meeting  said he doesn't want to make too much of the split and still plans to work  with the senator on Everglades projects. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor806553"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor806553"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Plans altered to protect Clearwaterbluff</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>CLEARWATER -- (EnviroWorld) -- In order to preserve the downtown bluff,  Clearwater city administrators are planning a new route for the Memorial  Causeway Bridge, the St. Petersburg Times reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The new plan involves rerouting the bridge so that it reaches across  Clearwater Harbor from Court Street . The Court Street alignment is said  to have one of the mildest effects on sea grasses and other vegetation  in the harbor, however the plan is predicted not to run as smoothly as  administrators are hoping. Fearing reduction in their property values,  representatives of the Pierce 100 building and other condominiums near  the site have criticized the plan and have threatened to sue.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The proposed plan will be heard by the City Commission on Feb. 3 and  will be the topic of a public hearing on Feb. 6. At that point, city engineer  Richard Baier anticipates a final decision on the matter.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor812555"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor812555"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Report: Lake Okeechobee is stilltoo polluted</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WEST PALM BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- Phosphorus inputs to Lake Okeechobee  have exceeded state regulations by an average of 100 tons a year during  the last five years, according to a report released Wednesday by the South  Florida Water Management District.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>And in 1995, the lake received 772 tons of the algal-bloom stimulating  element, exceeding levels set by the legislature by more than 300 tons,  according to the Miami Herald. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Swiftmud senior environmental scientist Barry Rosen's report lays much  of the blame for the pollution on dairy and cattle industries north of  the lake, despite cooperation from those businesses in trying to reduce  pollutions. Rosen said high rainfall levels in 1995 were a critical factor  in that year's jump in phosphorus inputs.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Another possible problem is sediment that has collected at the bottom  of some canals draining into the lake, the Ft. Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel  reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>In 1986 and 1987, algal blooms resulting from high phosphorus levels  covered as much as 42 percent of the 448,000-acre lake.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Ironically, Lake Okeechobee was mentioned as a model of environmental  cleanup success by an Egyptian scientist in this month's &quot;National  Geographic&quot; article on the environmental problems of the Nile delta.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><A NAME="anchor814066"></A></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor814066"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>New York firm gets Georgia envirocontract</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=+2> </FONT></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>(EnviroWorld) -- The Georgia Department of Natural Resources, Environmental  Protection Division (EPD) has awarded a contract to the Lancaster, New  York firm Ecology and Environment, Inc. to provide site assessment services  on abandoned or uncontrolled hazardous waste sites in the State of Georgia,  PR newswire reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The one year contract is worth $3 to $5 million and has two one-year  extension options. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor815509"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor815509"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Mine proposed for Everglades</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>MIAMI -- (EnviroWorld) -- Michigan-based Lafarge Corp. is seeking a  permit to mine limestone on land it owns that is part of the Everglades,  the Miami Herald reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Lafarge's 1,131-acre tract of sawgrass prairie is part of the Northwest  Shark River Slough, and will be flooded next century according to Everglades  restoration plans. The government is supposed to acquire the land before  then, so skeptics believe the company's permit request may simply be a  bid to increase the land's value.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>But company officials insist the application is genuine. It comes prior  to the meeting of a state-appointed committee expected to remove the mining  zoning designation from the land to make it part of the Everglades expansion  area.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><A NAME="anchor817008"></A></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor817008"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Keys to vote on septic tankregulations today</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>MONROE COUNTY -- (EnviroWorld) -- Voters in the Keys will vote today  on a proposal aimed at the worst of the area's septic tanks, the Miami  Herald reported. If approved, the ordinance will require homeowners whose  septic tanks have no historical documentation to be first in line to obtain  new operating permits for sewage treatment systems.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>That group is thought to number about 12,000 and many of the homes are  believed to have septic systems that are simply holes in the ground. Septic  tanks are a major source of water pollution in the Keys, and Monroe County  is working on its master plan to correct the problem in the  long term.  Part of Marathon Key is exempt from the ordinance because it may soon get  a central sewage system.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor819324"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor819324"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Columnist endorses Keys Sanctuary</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>MIAMI -- (EnviroWorld) -- Fishing columnist Jim Hardie, who writes for  the Miami Herald, endorsed the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary Plan.  The plan has been the source of much local controversy and was turned down  in a referendum last November.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Hardie argued that the plan should be given a chance, and, if it doesn't  work during a five-year trial, &quot;trash it.&quot; He added that the  best solution to protect fisheries would be for the federal government  to close all U.S. waters in the Gulf of Mexico to fish traps.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Hardie did take state regulators to task for failing to protect queen  conch, and said that federal protection needs to be extended year-round  for a fish-spawning area called &quot;Riley's Hump,&quot; which is southwest  of the Dry Tortugas.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The governor and Cabinet are scheduled to vote Jan. 28 whether to accept  the sanctuary plan.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor822660"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor822660"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>New group aims for regulatory,technological clarity</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>An organization has been formed to assist state governments and business  in dealing with new environmental standards and technologies, according  to the Daily Environment Report. The group, called the Clean States Foundation  is the brainchild of the Association of State and Territorial Solid Waste  Management Officials. It is chaired by Teresa Hay, administrator of waste  management at the Iowa Department of Natural Resources.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
