in a federal investigation of problems  within that agency.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor844784"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor844784">Industry paying the tab for scientific reviewof new EPA rules</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ANNAPOLIS, Md -- (EnviroWorld) -- Concerns have been raised about the  independence of an outside scientific panel reviewing the Environmental  Protection Agency's proposed regulations for particulate matter and ozone,  the Wall Street Journal reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The four-year-old Annapolis Center is a panel of scientists charged  with analyzing the risks and benefits of regulations. The group was scheduled  to meet Thursday to discuss its findings about the new EPA rules, and will  release a pamphlet about those findings that is written for the general  public.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The panel is primarily funded by the National Association of Manufacturers  (NAM), however. That group is strongly opposed to the new air pollution  rules, saying the cost to industry will be an economic hardship. Scientists  at the Harvard University School of Public Health discovered the panels  funding source after they complained in writing about the seemingly-biased  makeup of the panel.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A scientist on the Annapolis Center panel said NAM did not interfere  or influence his work, and an EPA scientist said he welcomed rigorous review  of his research--part of a body of work indicating significant respiratory  health effects are caused by fine-particulate air pollution.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;The general consensus among environmental scientists right now  is that this phenomenon is real,&quot; said agency scientist Dan Costa.  &quot;How important, it is difficult to say. A lot of work has been done  by a limited number of people, and it's important that other people get  into the act and reanalyze the studies. Something out there is happening.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor847938"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor847938">Keys vote to regulate septic tanks</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>KEY WEST -- (EnviroWorld) -- Voters in the Keys approved a controversial  proposal Thursday that targets the area's worst septic tank polluters,  the Miami Herald reported.</P>  <P>Early versions of the proposal had drawn strong opposition in Monroe  County, and some residents believe that changes made in order to get it  passed will unfairly burden less-affluent homeowners.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The new ordinance requires that owners of homes built before 1956, who  do not have any documentation about their septic systems, must get an operating  permit this year. Those homes are considered to have the worst potential  for water pollution, and as many as 12,000 of those homes may have septic  systems that are nothing more than pits in the ground. In contrast, owners  of homes built in the 90's won't have to get a permit for another 10 years.  </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor849978"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor849978">Sharks may find protection under new regulations</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)-- The National Marine Fisheries Service will hold  public hearings next week to hear opinions on proposed shark fishing limits,  the Tampa Tribune reported. The new rules, if adopted, will affect both  recreational and commercial fishermen. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The hearings will be in Tampa and Fort Lauderdale next Wednesday and  Key West next Thursday. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Overfishing has caused the shark population to dramatically decline  over the past 20 years. Sharks are caught for meat and for their fins,  an Asian delicacy.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The proposed regulations include cutting commercial fishing limits in  half, establishing a commercial limit on small coastal sharks, lowering  the recreational limit to two sharks per boat, and banning the deliberate  killing of great white, whale, basking and some tiger sharks. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor851476"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor851476">Insurance company settles with St. Petersburg</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>ST. PETERSBURG--(EnviroWorld)-- City Council members approved a settlement  Thursday with United States Fidelity and Guarantee Insurance Company for  $500,000, the St. Petersburg Times reported.  The city sued the company  in 1993, claiming it should have helped the city defend itself in a 1991  lawsuit.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Workers sued the city of St. Petersburg in 1991, claiming health problems  after working in contaminated soil at what is now Tropicana Field. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The city was cleared of responsibility for the workers' illnesses, but  still incurred $830,000 in legal expenses. The settlement approved Thursday  will help to offset those expenses.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor853127"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor853127">Hillsborough EPC drops wetlands fight</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)-- Hillsborough County's Environmental Protection  Commission agreed Thursday to settle a suit brought by a Northdale developer,  the St. Petersburg Times reported. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Developer Steve Dibbs challenged the EPC's power to protect wetlands.  In exchange for dropping his suit, the EPC will allow him to develop three  acres of wetlands on North Dale Mabry Highway in Northdale. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The EPC settled to avoid the possibility of a court ruling that the  agency lacks the legal authority to prevent developers from destroying  wetlands. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor861406"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor861406">Air-base transfer delayed due to environmentalconcerns</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>HOMESTEAD--(EnviroWorld)-- Transfer of Homestead Air Reserve Base to  a group of developers has been delayed by the Clinton administration to  allow the completion of environmental studies, the Miami Herald reported.  Federal and state agencies are studying the potential environmental impacts  on Biscayne Bay and the Everglades from turning the base into a small commercial  airport with warehouses and offices. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The base is located 10 miles east of Everglades National Park and two  miles west of Biscayne National Park. Environmentalists are concerned that  once the base is converted into a commercial airport, the estimated 200,000  planes it will use will have an adverse effect on the parks. They are also  concerned about increased pollution in runoff water that is directed into  the bay.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor863127"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor863127">SFWMD creating water management areas in theEverglades</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>EVERGLADES--(EnviroWorld)-- The governing board of the South Florida  Water Management District approved the purchase of Land within the Everglades  Agricultural Area for a water management area. The water management area  offers water storage opportunities critical to future restoration of the  Everglades.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The purchase approval consists of 1,233.18 acres of sod farm known as  the Carroll property. The purchase price is $3,043,000. Funds for the purchase  will come from the district and from the federal Farm Bill.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor864819"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor864819">Kamath joins Tomasino</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TEMPLE TERRACE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Dinesh Kamath has joined Tomasino  &amp; Associates, Inc. as  project engineer.  Kamath is a registered professional  engineer in Florida and has been practicing in the state since 1982.  His  also is a member of the American Water Works Association.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor866571"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor866571">ERM receives recognition for contributions</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TAMPA -- (EnviroWorld) -- Environmental Resources Management has been  recognized for its effort, support and financial contributions to the arts  for 1996 by the Tampa Bay Business Committee in the Arts, Inc.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>ERM contributed more than $10,000 and more than $11,000 worth of volunteer  time to art-related activities that deal with environmental issues.  The  donations went to the Museum of Science and Industry, the Tampa Museum  of Art, the Children's Museum, the Tampa Bay Children's Chorus and the  Florida Aquarium.  <BR>  </P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P