<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>fla enews today</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><A HREF="../index.html">Return to Front Page</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT> <BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../Images/EWlogobig.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="353" HEIGHT="104" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></H2><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Today's Florida Environmental News</H1><P ALIGN=CENTER>- News Every Business Day -</P><P><A NAME="anchor338406"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor338406"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Developer plans ecotourism resortfor Everglades City</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>EVERGLADES CITY -- (EnviroWorld) -- A Tampa developer wants to build  a $7 million ecotourism resort and marina in a town that had been dependent  on a fishing economy until the passage of the 1994 net ban, the Naples  Daily News Reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Developer David Peterson's project, &quot;The Lure of the Everglades,&quot;  would span 53 acres next to Everglades City Airport and feature 45 boat  slips and 24 hotel rooms. His most immediate hurdle  is a Jan. 24 recommendation  from the city zoning and planning board to the city council. After that,  Peterson must get approval from the governor and Cabinet to use submerged  state lands under the marina, satisfy the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service  that construction won't interfere with a nesting eagle on the site, and  work out protections for manatees.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor84248"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor84248"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Collier land swap may hurt airboatbusinesses</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>EVERGLADES CITY -- (EnviroWorld) -- The recent trade of Collier Family  land to the National Park Service has angered some local residents, whose  airboat-tour businesses may no longer be able to operate on the new federal  land, the Naples Daily News reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A deal is in the works to allow those tour operators who were in business  before Dec. 18, 1992-- when the land-swap deal began--to stay in business.  But that deal would require that the Seminole and Miccosukee Tribes waive  their rights regarding economic activities on such lands, and it would  also still leave a number of newer businesses out. Some of the tour operators  are former fisherman who gave up fishing after the 1994 net ban and say  they may lose their means of earning a living to the government once again.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor85747"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor85747"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Everglades coalition meetingseeks cooperation</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>DEERFIELD BEACH -- (EnviroWorld) -- The 12th meeting of the Everglades  coalition, a group of 40 state and national environmental groups, focused  on getting everyone who is affected by the restoration of the River of  Grass involved and informed, the Tampa Tribune reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Attendees of the meeting included business, agriculture and aquaculture  interests, but the sugar industry was not represented. Having spent $30  million to fight a state constitutional amendment to tax raw sugar in order  to fund some of the restoration, that industry's absence was conspicuous.  Keynote speaker Kathleen McGinty, chairwoman of the White House Council  on Environmental Quality, said that President Clinton would again support  a penny-per-pound tax on sugar, despite the tax's double rejection by Congress  and Florida voters.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Another sticky issue is the proposed international airport at Homestead  Air Force Base, on which the Miami Sierra Club's Alan Farago vowed to prevent  any work until all environmental issues are resolved.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Participants did agree that a priority was to make all South Floridians  aware that the restoration would have benefits for everyone--primarily  the long-term protection of water supplies for the region--and discussions.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor88141"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor88141"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Group urges more attention toair quality in Polk</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>LAKELAND -- (EnviroWorld) -- The League of Women Voters of Polk County  is leading a movement to get local officials more concerned with air quality  issues, the Tampa Tribune reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The group is hosting a talk entitled, &quot;How Clean is Our Air? How  Much Does Clean Air Cost ?&quot; at 7 p.m. in the Lakeland Public Library's  meeting room. The speaking panel will include members of the phosphate  and electric industries, as well as county officials and environmental  activists.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Ann Brooks, chairwoman of the natural resources committee of the League,  said local politicians needed to be made aware of the need for local attention  to air quality.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;Both times I brought (air quality issues up at candidate debates),  they said DEP has taken care of that and industries are monitoring themselves,&quot;  Brooks told the Tribune. &quot;Well, that's like the fox and the henhouse.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Polk's phosphate plants are major contributors to the county's air pollution,  and U.S. EPA statistics indicate the county's industries are some of the  state's worst toxic-industrial-compound polluters.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor89986"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor89986"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Game Commission appointee facesopposition</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- As confirmation hearings approach, complaints  have surfaced about Joe  Bruner, a hunting buddy of Gov. Lawton Chiles  and the newest member of the Florida Game and Fresh  Water Fish Commission,  The Associated Press reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Chiles named Bruner in June to the five-member panel that oversees hunting  and fishing laws. He faces Senate confirmation this spring.The complaints  accuse him of illegally setting bait and live quail in a public forest,  and chasing other  hunters off state land.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Complaints on file at the game commission say Bruner has harassed wildlife  officers when they  stopped to check his permit. And Bruner and his brother,  former state Sen. Vince Bruner, were arrested for breaking hunting laws  in  Louisiana several years ago.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>But Bruner pointed out that despite the complaints, investigators from  the game commission have never  found probable cause to charge him with  a hunting crime in Florida. Sheriff's deputies and prosecutors who have  reviewed assault complaints against Bruner also have failed  to find reason  to make an arrest.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Chiles backed Bruner in a letter this fall, saying he appointed him  ``because I know him to be an  individual of high caliber ... and one who  has the best interests of the outdoors resources of Florida at  heart.''</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>But Manley Fuller, who heads the Florida Wildlife Federation, said his  group and others will oppose  Bruner's confirmation. And state Sen. Charlie  Crist, R-St. Petersburg, who heads the Senate committee that will handle  the  confirmation, has heard of complaints about Bruner and said he has  &quot;deep concerns&quot; about him as a  commission member.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Bruner says the allegations come from jealous hunters and said he has  high hopes for his Senate confirmation hearing.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor91946"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor91946"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Director named at USGS CaribbeanScience Center</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>Dr. Russell J. Hall has been named Director of the US Geological Survey's  Florida Caribbean Science Center, a biological research facility headquartered  in Gainesville, Florida.</P>  <P>     </P>  <P>Research at the Florida Caribbean Science Center focuses on scientific  information for restoring, enhancing, managing, and protecting living resources  and their habitats in Florida and adjacent States, and the Caribbean region.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Hall will be responsible for the overall administration of the science  center and several field stations, including the Sirenia Project in Gainesville,  which leads Federal research efforts to sustain populations of the Florida  manatee, a station in the U.S. Virgin Islands specializing in conservation  of coral reefs, and several stations in the Everglades National Park and  elsewhere in South Florida that have a leading role in scientific assessments  related to the the Everglades restoration project.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Dr. Hall received his undergraduate degree in biology from St. Bonaventure  University and his master of science and doctorate from the ecology program  at the University of Kansas.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor94804"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor94804"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>EPA seeks comment on enforcement</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) -- EPA's Office of Enforcement and Compliance  Assurance (OECA) will hold a public meeting on Feb. 3, as part of its National  Performance</P>  <P>Measures Strategy. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The meeting will begin at 8:30 a.m. at the Holiday Inn Historic District  Motel in Alexandria, Va.  The purpose of the meeting will be to receive  views on ways to measure the effectiveness of OECA's environmental enforcement  and compliance assurance program</P>  <P>and to accept additional performance measurement proposals. </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Those interested in participating in or submitting comments for the  initial public meeting should contact or fax Michelle Angelich at telephone:  703-821-4432; fax: 703-903-1373 no later than Jan. 24. Additional information  about the meeting, as well as background material, can be obtained in the  Jan. 13 edition of the Federal Register.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor97139"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor97139"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>EPA says its self-audit programis working</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>WASHINGTON -- (EnviroWorld) --The Environmental Protection Agency released  data about its 1995 audit policy Friday, and says it shows that the policy  is having the desired effect on corporate behavior. One hundred and five  companies have disclosed violations at more than 350</P>  <P>facilities under the policy.  EPA already has settled matters with 40  companies and 48 facilities, waiving all penalties in most cases.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>According to the agency, the figures indicate that environmental auditing  can be encouraged</P>  <P>without blanket amnesties or audit privileges that would excuse serious  misconduct, frustrate enforcement, encourage secrecy, boost litigation  and/or lead to public distrust.  The data is contained in the &quot;EPA  Audit Policy Update,&quot; a bulletin published by and available</P>  <P>from  the Office of Enforcement and Compliance Assurance (OECA).</P>  <P> </P>  <P>Both the Audit Policy Update and the Interpretive Guidance can be obtained  by calling the Audit Policy docket at  202-260-7548.  By the end of January,  both documents will be available through OECA's home page on the Internet  at http://es.inel.gov/oeca/epapolguid.html.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor99593"></A></P><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><A HREF="#anchor99593"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>PEER releases first data, slamsDEP &quot;Charm School&quot;</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- As a teaser before Wednesday's Tallahassee  press conference, Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility has  released some results of its survey of Department of Environmental Protection  employees.</P>  <P>According to the survey, 54 percent of agency employees indicated problems  with DEP training. The $1.5 million program called &quot;Charm School,&quot;  brought the most negative comments. According to PEER, one employee wrote,  &quot;Much of the last two days of the course was a series of touchy-feely  seminars taught by a Florida Highway Patrol lieutenant that was a combination  of Ann Landers and Leo Buscaglia.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The intent of the one-week course, held in Tallahassee, is to teach  communication, courtesy and techniques for diffusing hostile situations.  According to PEER, however, many DEP employees felt that the course is  insulting and unproductive.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>PEER is holding a press conference Wednesday to announce further results  of the survey, which is part of the group's investigation of the agency.  About 35 percent of DEP's employees have responded to the survey to date.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H3><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
