NAME="anchor282437"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</H3>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor282437">DEP corruption is widespread, employees say</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>TALLAHASSEE--EnviroWorld)--EXCLUSIVE-- Widespread mismanagement at the
  upper levels of the state Department of Environmental Protection is more
  than rumors and anecdotes and is having a significantly negative affect
  on Florida's environment, according to an DEP worker survey released today
  by an employee watchdog group.</P>
  <P>The survey was conducted by Public Employees' for Environmental Responsibility,
  in response to employee complaints the group received, and indicates that
  a large group of state workers believe their agency is corrupt. The20 question
  survey was mailed to all of all of DEP's personnel, except for those in
  law enforcement, and PEER field director Tom Weis announced the results
  at a Tallahassee press conference Wednesday. More than a third of the surveys
  have been returned so far, Weis said.</P>
  <P>Perhaps the greatest cause for concern are the responses of management.
  Thirty-four percent of the managers responding to the survey agreed with
  the statement, &quot;In the last three years, have you ever been directed
  to ignore an environmental rule or regulation.&quot; Twenty-nine percent
  of regular employees agreed with that statement.</P>
  <P>Weis, whose group has investigated problems at several federal agencies
  and the environmental departments of Virginia and Montana, said the DEP
  had &quot;lower morale than at any state agency PEER has ever reviewed.&quot;</P>
  <P>Weis said the survey results were the first step in his group's investigation.
  PEER is still conducting face to face meetings with DEP employees at branch
  offices throughout the state, and is waiting for a panel of law enforcement
  officers to put together a separate survey for all employees in that branch
  of the agency. The group will now begin compiling evidence that may be
  used for employee lawsuits against DEP.</P>
  <P>Weis said that already more than 50 employees had expressed willingness
  to come forward and help file suits over specific allegations. Two of those
  individuals were present at the press conference. Tom Greenlaugh, a geologist
  who is still employed at the agency, says he is suffering health effects
  from exposure to contaminants in the Dupont herbicide Benlate during a
  1993 site investigation. Greenlaugh believes upper management has conspired
  to cover up harmful health and environmental effects caused by those contaminants.</P>
  <P>Also present was Eugene Breeze, a state park ranger for more than 17
  years, who said his attempts to expose agency misconduct through the federal
  Whistleblower's Act only resulted in his dismissal from the agency.</P>
  <P>A statement was also read from former DEP attorney Lori Battaile.</P>
  <P>&quot;Virgina Wetherell's administration used intimidation and threats
  to accomplish their agenda, &quot; Battaile wrote. &quot;It was made abundantly
  clear that if staff did not 'get on board,' retribution would be at hand.&quot;</P>
  <P>Battaile job was one of the casualties of departmental budget cuts this
  year.</P>
  <P>Weis said employee comments on the survey were mostly negative, and
  tended to focus on Assistant Secretaries Nevin Smith and Kirby Green as
  responsible for agency mismanagement. Secretary Virginia Wetherell, he
  said, seems to be regarded as a figurehead.</P>
  <P>&quot;(The survey results) paint a picture of a sick agency....&quot;
  Weir said. &quot;Florida's environment is suffering greatly under this
  department.&quot; </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H5>&nbsp;</H5>

<H5>&nbsp;</H5>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor338406">PEER probe in Virginia nets federal investigation</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>GAINESVILLE--(EnviroWorld)--On Monday the EPA's Inspector General began
  an investigation into whether the Virginia DEQ has been too lenient on
  air polluters, according to Holland &amp; Knight's Daily Environmental
  Report.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>A finding that the state agency has not been enforcing the federal law
  could result in the EPA taking over the State's air pollution programs.
  Virginia officials claim the investigation is politically motivated.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>The probe is spurred, in part, by an investigation into Virgina's Department
  of Environmental Quality by the watchdog group PEER, Public Employees for
  Environmental Responsibility. That probe began last Spring and led to several
  spin off investigations by various agencies and contributed to the resignation
  of Virginia's top environmental official.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>&nbsp;</H3>

<H3><A NAME="anchor455649"></A></H3>

<H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor455649">EPA offers water grants</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>The EPA issued a notice announcing the availability of competitive grants
  for states that encourage and support the use of voluntary environmental
  management systems using the ISO 14000 standards as a baseline, for facilities
  under state water programs [62 FR 3036], according to Holland &amp; Knight's
  Daily Environmental Update. The EPA anticipates between five and seven
  states will be accepted initially, receiving grants of up to $100,000.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Applications must be received by March 13, 1997. For more information
  contact James Horne, (202) 260-5802.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor398041"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor398041">Bruner still sparks controversy</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)-- Complaints about Joe Bruner, Gov. Lawton
  Chiles' hunting buddy and most recent Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish
  Commissioner, continue to surface as his Senate confirmation looms in the
  near future, The Associated Press reported.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Chiles named Bruner to the five-member panel that oversees hunting and
  fishing laws.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Bruner was arrested in Louisiana several years ago for breaking hunting
  laws and has had several complaints filed against him in Florida. He has
  never been charged with a hunting crime in the state of Florida.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>The most recent incident occurred in November 1996. A rancher has filed
  a complaint with the game commission claiming Bruner drove over his fences
  and threatened him.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>State Sen. Charlie Crist, R-St. Petersburg, who heads the Senate committee
  that will handle the confirmation, has heard of complaints about Bruner
  and said he has &quot;deep concerns&quot; about him as a commission member.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor400139"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor400139">Gypsum stack subject of suit</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>PLANT CITY--(EnviroWorld)-- The owners of a tract of land across from
  a proposed gypsum stack are suing Hillsborough County over actions they
  say allowed the site to be approved, the Tampa Tribune reported.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>CF Industries wants to build a gypsum stack on the property to dispose
  of the byproduct produced their phosphate processing plant.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Arthur and Janice Weiss, owners of 1,960 acres of land across from the
  site, say that the county rezoned the land for the waste facility and the
  consequence will be the devaluing of their land. Their property has been
  approved for a 700 to 800 home development with stables and a golf course.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Environmentalists against the construction of the gypsum stack argue
  that the dump's location is too close to Blackwater Creek, which drains
  into Tampa's water source, the Hillsborough River. Environmentalists also
  say that the development the Weisses plan for their property could pollute
  Blackwater Creek.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>CFI is still seeking state and federal permits to begin the stack.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor401624"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor401624">Development stopped for residents</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>LAND O'LAKES--(EnviroWorld)-- Amid objections from residents and homeowners
  associations, Pasco County officials decided Tuesday to not recommend a
  commercial &quot;node&quot; at Hale Road and Collier Parkway, the Tampa
  Tribune reported. Commercial nodes allow for clusters of businesses to
  be built at crossroads in an attempt to cut down on strip centers.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Residents said they didn't want any of the area developed. The intersection
  is close to pristine Lake Placie and a pond in the area supports a community
  of sandhill cranes.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Residents were pleased that the commission decided to stop the development
  plan.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor403114"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor403114">Swiftmud chooses director</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>TAMPA--(EnviroWorld)-- The Southwest Florida Water Management District
  has picked a new executive director to replace Peter Hubbell, the St. Petersburg
  Times reported. Hubbell will leave to start a private business this month.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Emilio D. &quot;Sonny&quot; Vergara, executive director of the Peace
  River/Manasota Regional Water Supply Authority, will resign his position
  in 30 days and take over as head of Swiftmud. Vergara served as executive
  director of the St. Johns Water Management District in the 80s and was
  a department head at Swiftmud in the 70s.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>One of Vergara's first duties will be to find a replacement for Assistant
  Executive Director Mark Farrell who left Swiftmud to work with Hubbell.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor404743"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor404743">Separated lakes to be rejoined</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>WINTER HAVEN--(EnviroWorld)-- The manager for the Winter Haven Canal
  Commission is seeking funds from Polk County commissioners and the Southwest
  Florida Water Management District to rejoin the Winter Haven Chain of Lakes,
  the Tampa Tribune reported. Roger Griffiths is asking for $150,000 from
  the commission and $200,000 from the water district.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>The chain was split in the 1960s when the canal that connected them
  was filled in, possibly during the widening of U.S. 17.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>The canal commission plans to build a series of locks that would connect
  the two separated halves. Reconnecting the lakes would replenish depleted
  lakes in the chain.</P>
  <P>&nbsp;</P>
  <P>Griffiths has been seeking support of this project for several years.
  Commissioners told him they would need to sell some county lakefront property
  before they could give him the money. The water district has not yet responded
  to the request.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor407224"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor407224">Environmental association in Israel offers business
opportunity</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>HAIFA BAY, Israel -- (EnviroWorld) -- A public invitation for an integrated
  quantitative environmental risk assessment study for the southern region
  of Haifa Bay has been issued by the Environmental Association of Haifa,
  Israel's largest northern city. The Florida-Israel Chamber of Commerce,
  which has an office in Israel, is willing to assist Florida companies pursuing
  this and other business opportunities in Israel. The Chamber can be reached
  at 954-420-5888 or by E-mail at mail@ficc.org.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><A NAME="anchor409438"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3><A HREF="#anchor409438">Former SWFWMD directors open new business</A></H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>TAMPA -- (EnviroWorld) -- Water Resource Associates, a water resource
  planning and engineering firm, recently has opened under the direction
  of Mark Farrell and Peter Hubbell. Both Farrell and Hubbell are former
  directors of the Southwest Florida Water Management District. The company's
  office is located in the Great Western Bank Building at 14502 North Dale
  Mabry Hwy., Suite 330 in Tampa. The phone number is 813-265-3130.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

