lution could be costly forPolk</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>LAKELAND--(EnviroWorld)--Polk County may expand its air pollution monitoring  to protect itself from possible Clean Air Act violations in the future,  the Tampa Tribune reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Although little was resolved at an informal meeting between industry,  government and environmental representatives Tuesday night, the issue of  pollution regulation was of primary concern at the gathering.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>With impending new Environmental Protection Agency clean-air guidelines,  the pressure is on for the county to control the amount of pollution it  produces.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Currently, the state manages two ozone-monitoring sites in western Polk,  but a single county-employee is responsible for all the oversight. Polk  nearly violated federal limits at the sites several times in recent years.  Under the stricter federal regulations, reaching those limits would be  very costly to the county.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Supporters of county-regulation argue that without a new system for  monitoring pollution it seems impossible to foresee potential problem areas.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;If we come under non-attainment there will be a gross impact to  Polk County taxpayers,&quot; said John Ryan, head of the Winter Haven-based  League of Environmental Organizations.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor1764643"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P><A HREF="#anchor1764643"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Wakulla officials rally againstplant expansion</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)--Wakulla County officials went in force to  Tallahassee on Wednesday to tell city officials they are strongly against  the expansion of a 250-megawatt-generating plant, the Tallahassee Democrat  reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Although the plant would provide considerable income for the Tallahassee  government as well as cheaper electricity for its residents, Wyatt Pope,  Wakulla County Commission Chairman, said the plant would also dump more  sludge in the St. Mark's River and pollute the air in southern Wakulla  County.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;They come in, they use our resources, they don't pay us anything  for it and then they say it's going to be for our benefit,&quot; Pope said.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Sam Bell, the Tallahassee assistant city manager for utilities, said  the expansion of the plant is environmentally safe as well as economically  desirable for the area. &quot;The power plant, once that expansion is complete,  will be a lot friendlier to the environment than the one that's there now,&quot;  he said.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor1767439"></A></P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P><A HREF="#anchor1767439"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Survey: more than 100 U.S.coastal sites are cleaner</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>(EnviroWorld)--According to a study by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric  Administration, pollution levels have declined at more than 100 sites along  the U.S. coast, the New York Times reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The federal study reached its findings by monitoring contaminant levels  of 14 chemicals in mussels and oysters. Specimens at 154 sites were monitored  for the study, which found 217 decreases and 41 increases in chemicals.  Most of the cases recorded no changes.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>However, the program maintains that despite a decrease in the levels  of pollutants found in the crustaceans, ocean pollution remains a problem  in coastal areas across the United States. The study found 21 states with  high and rising chemical presence.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor1770263"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P><A HREF="#anchor1770263"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Different name, same battlein Spring Hill utility fight</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Court decisions that should have resulted  in lower water bills for Spring Hill residents have been ineffective so  far, the St. Petersburg Times reported. The problem, residents say, are  the deep-pockets of their utility company, which will not admit defeat  and which continually appeals court rulings.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>But residents hope that a Tuesday vote by the Public Service Commission  that new, lower, rates are in order for the residents, will change the  utility's mind.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>That utility was Southern States Utilities, but has changed its name  to Florida Water Services Corp. The company owns 150 utilities throughout  Florida and is regulated by the Public Services Commission. The company  charges Spring Hills' residents based on a uniform rate formula designed  to subsidize rates for other utilities. The public service commission ordered  the company to end that practice after court rulings against it, but Spring  Hill had previously voted to remove itself from the jurisdiction of the  commission. Other utilities owned by Florida Water Services must be charged  stand-alone rates.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>In an announcement of its name change, Florida Water services pledged  to &quot;do an even better job in the future. ... We must also change our  attitude and direction.&quot; Spring Hill residents are waiting to see  how that new attitude translates in their case, and whether the company  will continue to appeal rulings in the legal battle they have been fighting  since the early 1990's.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The lower rates are expected to save $2.2 million for 25,000 customers  in the Hernando county community.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor1771690"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P><A HREF="#anchor1771690"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>DEP corruption is widespread,employee survey says</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TALLAHASSEE-- (EnviroWorld)--EXCLUSIVE-- Mismanagement at the upper  levels of the state Department of Environmental Protection is having a  significantly negative affect on Florida's environment, according to a  DEP worker survey released Wednesday by an employee watchdog group.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The survey was conducted by Public Employees' for Environmental Responsibility,  in response to employee complaints the group received, and indicates that  a large group of state workers believe their agency is corrupt.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The 20-question survey was mailed to all of all of DEP's personnel,  except for those in law enforcement, and PEER field director Tom Weis announced  the results at a Tallahassee press conference Wednesday. More than 1200  of the 3400 surveys have been returned so far, Weis said.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Perhaps the greatest cause for concern are the responses of management.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Twenty percent of the managers responding to the survey agreed with  the statement, &quot;In the last three years, have you ever been directed  to ignore an environmental rule or regulation.&quot; Eighteen percent of  survey respondents overall agreed with that statement.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Weis, whose group has investigated problems at several federal agencies  and the environmental departments of Virginia and Montana, said the DEP  had &quot;lower morale than at any state agency PEER has ever reviewed.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Assistant DEP Secretary Nevin Smith said that in terms of pure numbers,  the survey didn't necessarily show widespread morale problems. Roughly  speaking, the negative comments came from about one-third of the answers  to a survey answered by one third of employees, or about 10 percent of  the agency's employees.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;Is a 10 percent negative response too high?&quot; Smith asked.  &quot;I think it's within the overall range of what you would expect in  an organizational response.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Smith added that morale problems at the agency were specific to either  location or organization. He cited low pay in areas with a high cost of  living as one cause of low morale, and &quot;the other thing that makes  a difference is supervision,&quot; Smith said.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The office of DEP Inspector General Pinky Hall provided letters from  experts at Florida A&amp;M University and Harvard, both of which concluded  that the survey was statistically unreliable.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Weis said the survey was not intended to be scientific and said that  the results, coupled with written comments that employees included on the  survey, indicated serious problems at the agency, regardless of the unscientific  nature of the questionaire.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Weis added that the survey was only the first step in his group's investigation.  PEER is still conducting face to face meetings with DEP employees at branch  offices throughout the state, and is waiting for a panel of law enforcement  officers to put together a separate survey for all employees in that branch  of the agency. The group will now begin compiling evidence that may be  used for employee lawsuits against DEP.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Hall said her office could not initiate any investigations until specific  allegations were made.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Weis said that already more than 50 employees had expressed willingness</P>  <P>to come forward with specific allegations of misconduct at the department.  Two of those individuals were present at the press conference. Tom Greenlaugh,  a geologist who is still employed at the agency, says he is suffering health  effects from exposure to contaminants in the Dupont herbicide Benlate during  a 1993 site investigation. Greenlaugh believes upper management has conspired  to cover up harmful health and environmental effects caused by those contaminants.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Also present was Eugene Breeze, a state park ranger for more than 17  years, who said his attempts to expose agency misconduct through the federal  Whistleblower's Act only resulted in his dismissal from the agency.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A statement was also read from former DEP attorney Lori Battaile.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;Virginia Wetherell's administration used intimidation and threats  to accomplish their agenda,&quot; Battaile wrote. &quot;It was made abundantly  clear that if staff did not 'get on board,' retribution would be at hand.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Battaile's job was one of the casualties of departmental budget cuts  this year.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Smith said he did not believe that retaliation against employees was  widespread at the agency, adding that public inquiries into agency activities,  such as the PEER survey, were a healthy and beneficial way to keep track  of a public agency.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Weis said employees most often named Assistant Secretaries Nevin Smith  and Kirby Green as specific managers most often as responsible for agency  mismanagement. Secretary Virginia Wetherell, he said, seems to be regarded  as a figurehead.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Smith denied directing anyone to break departmental rules or regulations.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;I've never asked anybody to do that, but I don't deal with permitting.&quot;  he said. &quot;I don't think our agency employees ... give instructions  to field staff to do that.&quot;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&quot;(The survey results) paint a picture of a sick agency....,&quot;  Weis said. &quot;Florida's environment is suffering greatly under this  department.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor1775999"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P><A HREF="#anchor1775999"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Softmud helicopter crashesin Everglades, 4 killed</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>FORT LAUDERDALE -- (EnviroWorld)-- A helicopter on a herbicide-spraying  mission chopped off the top 25 feet of a radio tower today, then crashed  into the Everglades, killing the pilot and all three passengers, The Associated  Press reported.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>A white piece of the tail section was intact on the ground, but the  rest of the helicopter was obliterated. Sheets covered three bodies several  yards from the wreckage. The pilot's body remained inside.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The top of the tower was mangled in the collision, across a tree line  from Sawgrass Recreation Park, a fishing and airboat-tour business on the  edge of the Everglades west of Fort Lauderdale.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>``An airboat captain heard it and ran over to see if he could help,''  said park manager Kelly Smith. ``They were all beyond help. It was too  late.''</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>The helicopter, believed to be under contract to the South Florida Water  Management District, took off from Fort Lauderdale Executive Airport to  hand-spray herbicides on stands of melaleuca trees, an Australian tree  that has displaced acres and acres of native Everglades vegetation.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A NAME="anchor1888677"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P><A HREF="#anchor1888677"><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Blame divided for 1993 Pinellasoil spill</FONT></B></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>TAMPA -- (EnviroWorld) -- Three court appointed arbitrators declared  on Wednesday who is to blame for the oil spill on Pinellas beaches in 1993,  The Tampa Tribune reported. According to plantiff's attorney Roger Vaughan,  the freighter Balsa 37, piloted by Capt. Thomas Baggett, was 65 percent  responsible for the spill, and the tug-barge combination Seafarer/Ocean  255 was 35 percent responsible. The arbitrators also concluded that Capt.  Fred Bouchard of Barge B155, was not at fault. Four seaman who were injured  in the accident are seeking reparations between $115,000 and $200,000.  In addition to the seamen, state and federal environmental authorities,  Pinellas property owners, area business owners, and tourists are also seeking  compensation.  </P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>On Wednesday, the arbitration board listened to attorneys argue for  each of the three shipping companies. After the arbitrators' decision is  filed, both sides have 30 days to decide whether or not they wish to proceed  to court. If not, the current decision stands. The amount of blame placed  on each vessel will help determine who will ultimately be responsible for  the nearly $100 million in environmental, economic, and property damage  caused by the spill. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><BR></P><H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><A HREF="