 about $2 billion in asbestos claims  and has set aside another $2 billion for future claims.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor355244"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor355244">Hillsborough to get tough on water-use abuse</A></H3><DL>  <DD>BRANDON -- (EnviroWorld) -- Hillsborough County is emphasizing that  it will immediately fine people for watering on restricted days, with no  warnings for first-time violators, the Tampa Tribune reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Fines, authorized for first-time violators last month by the County  Commission, start at $35 and can go to $500 for repeat violators. Hillsborough,  Pinellas and Pasco counties are close to averaging 116 million gallons  per day, the limit set by the Southwest Florida Water Management District  for those counties, which are served by the West Coast Regional Water Supply  Authority.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>While the heaviest water use occurs in the summer, the Authority is  urging customers to cut back on lawn watering during the winter, when lawns  need less water, to reduce the annual average water consumption.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor357926"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor357926">Environmental group jumps in to oppose Tallahasseepower plant</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- The list of opponents to a proposed  St. Marks power plant grew Thursday when the Legal Environmental Assistance  Fund (LEAF) asked for permission to intervene in upcoming hearings before  the Public Service Commission, the Tallahassee Democrat reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>LEAF director Gail Kamaras said her organization believes the plant  may cost more than the city has estimated, and that the city has not explored  all of its options regarding future power needs.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The PSC is scheduled to hear the request for a state permit for the  250-megawatt plant April 3.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Wakulla County residents came to the capital Wednesday to voice opposition  to the plant, which they say benefits Tallahassee at their county's expense.  A Tallahassee group has also formed that claims the $600 million plant  is unnecessary and will result in 20 years of higher utility bills.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Assistant City Manager Sam Bell countered that the new plant would  benefit the environment in the long run because it would replace older  plants that generate more pollution.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor359603"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor359603">FSU hires contractor to cut energy use</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE -- (EnviroWorld) -- Florida State University has signed  a $6.7 million contract with Johnson Controls for energy conservation measures  to reduce the school's $16.2 million annual energy bill, the Tallahassee  Democrat reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>FSU will pay Johnson out of its savings from the work over the next  10 years. The savings are guaranteed by the Milwaukee-based company. The  University of Florida has also recently contracted with Johnson Controls,  which has done similar work at Florida International University and 15  school districts statewide.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor361417"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor361417">Study finds endangered species cluster</A></H3><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON--(EnviroWorld)--<B> </B>Scientists have found that most  vanishing plants and animals are clustered in limited areas, The Associated  Press reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The finding suggests it may be possible to protect endangered species  with less extensive impact on human activities than previously thought,  say researchers from Princeton University and the Environmental Defense  Fund, a private environmental group.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt suggested that with a better knowledge  of species concentration it may be easier to reach compromise agreements  for their protection.   <DD>&nbsp;</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor363504"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor363504">Meeting on proposed cement plant</A></H3><DL>  <DD>GAINESVILLE--(EnviroWorld)-- A community meeting will be held Saturday  at 11 a.m. at the Tower Road branch of the Alachua County Library to discuss  potential health problems from the proposed Florida Rock Industries plant,  the Gainesville Sun reported. For more information, contact Terry Blakeslee  at (352)472-4828.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor364859"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor364859">State to pursue higher boat fees</A></H3><DL>  <DD>CLEARWATER--(EnviroWorld)-- The Florida Boating Advisory Council is  requesting that the state Department of Environmental Protection pursue  bills that would raise registration requirements for all boats, including  small craft that currently do not need to be registered, the Florida Times-Union  reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>One proposal would add a second required decal to all boats registered  with the state, at a cost of $2  to $13. That would bring the state an  estimated $4 million a year.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>A second proposal suggests that all vessels, even those not powered  by motors like kayaks and canoes, be registered. This would earn the state  as much as $3 million a year.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The additional state income would be used to add more water officers,  said Florida Marine Patrol Commander Micky Watson. </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor366474"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor366474">Jacksonville seeks ways to spend state allotment</A></H3><DL>  <DD>JACKSONVILLE--(EnviroWorld)-- Boat ramps and recreational parks are  about to be the center of a $5 million dispute in Jacksonville, the Florida  Times-Union reported. Politicians are trying to decide how to divide up  an allotment from the state for the defunct Cross-Florida Barge Canal project.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The mayor of Jacksonville has selected the following projects to be  funded by the allotment: the purchase of properties for the Southeast Regional  Park in Mandarin for $2.4 million; the purchase of Dutton Island for a  park for $257,500; $335,000 for trails, boardwalks and other improvements  at Blue Cypress Park; $489,755 for the Beaches and Baldwin; the purchase  of property next to the Tree Hill Nature Center for $178,500. </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><A NAME="anchor367817"></A></P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor367817">Rivals band together to fight water war</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TAMPA BAY--(EnviroWorld)--Rival Republicans Jack Latvala and Carl Littlefield  will cosponsor legislation to help settle the ongoing water wars, the Tampa  Tribune reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The bill will allow companies to pursue desalination plants without  Public Service Commission regulation.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor369346"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor369346">Investigation begins into helicopter crash</A></H3><DL>  <DD>EVERGLADES--(EnviroWorld)-- Investigators of Thursday's helicopter  crash will spend today inspecting the radio tower involved in the crash,  the Miami Herald reported. The pilot and all three passengers of the aircraft  were killed when it hit the tower and crashed.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Broward County Hazardous Materials Team will be on alert in case  the herbicide is too toxic for investigators at the scene.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The helicopter was transporting workers to the Everglades to kill melaleuca  trees with a method called hack and squirt; the workers cut the tees with  machetes then spray herbicide on the wound. Aquagenix Governmental Services  of Fort Lauderdale, who won the spray contract from the South Florida Water  Management District in 1996, was overseeing the trip.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
