s tried  to work out an agreement with the state to jointly manage a coral reef  sanctuary off the Florida Keys.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The efforts could bear fruit Tuesday when the Florida Cabinet votes  on the joint-management plan to protect the nation's only near-shore network  of living reefs.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Salvage operators, the boating industry, fishermen and local residents  have been especially vocal in their opposition to the plan--accusing Washington  of trying to take over their tropical paradise.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The 3,500-square-mile sanctuary stretches 120 miles from north of the  John Pennekamp Coral Reef State Park in the upper Keys to west of the Dry  Tortugas, some 80 miles south of Key West.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The management plan bans fishing and imposes other restrictions on  boaters and divers in 0.5 percent of the sanctuary, said Billy Causey,  the sanctuary's superintendent.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Boaters and divers still will be allowed in these protected areas,  but they cannot disturb the coral by touch or by boat propellers. Outside  of these protected areas, nothing much will change when the new management  plan take effect, Causey said.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The plan also provides millions of dollars to clean up sewage pollution  in Florida Bay and the Straits of Florida; there has been speculation that  the sewage may be killing off corals and spawning diseases.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor356709"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor356709">First manatee tally of the year is in</A></H3><DL>  <DD>ST. PETERSBURG -- (AP) -- Scientists plan two additional surveys after  the year's first aerial population count of manatees revealed 2,229 of  the gentle giants in Florida waters.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD> The first survey, done last weekend, spotted 900 manatees on the east  coast and 1,329 on the west coast.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD> The number was lower than the 2,639 manatees found in February 1996  -- the highest number since the state began keeping manatee population  records in 1974.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD> The additional surveys will be conducted as soon as weather permits,  scientists said.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor357926"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor357926">Benlate complaints won't go away</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TAMPA -- (EnviroWorld) -- The fungicide Benlate DF was pulled off the  market in 1991, but complaints are still surfacing over the DuPont chemical.  Now, Roger and Linda King, who live next to Gator Slough Nursery in North  Fort Myers, are blaming contaminants in the pesticide for the breathing  difficulties, rashes, allergies and chemical sensitivities they have experienced  since 1990, the Tampa Tribune reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Based on 1994 research report that the radioisotope Carbon-14 was used  to mark two of the known contaminants in Benlate, the Kings have requested  that the Department of Environmental Protection test the soil and water  at the abandoned nursery. The nursery owners, Randall and Shirley Smith,  and their family, have also been suffering from medical problems they believe  are linked to Benlate and have a lawsuit against DuPont that is set for  trial in June.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>A DEP statewide investigation of sites connected with Benlate is expected  to begin in April.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Two DEP worker complaints in relation to health effects of the fungicide  have also been in the news recently. The workers are appealing the denial  of their Workers Compensation claims arising from exposure to Benlate.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor359731"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor359731">Park fees may be raised</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE-- (EnviroWorld)-- The Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish  Commission is suggesting a daily fee for all visitors at some state wildlife  management areas, the Gainesville Sun reported. Currently, only hunters  are required to pay $25 a year to use the wildlife areas.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The proposed fee of $3 a person or $6 a carload would apply to birdwatchers,  hikers and bicyclists at Andrews Wildlife Management Area and four others.  This fee would include camping.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Two years ago a $25 annual usage fee for non-hunters was proposed and  met with strong opposition. This year's proposal will likely face the same  opposition.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The fee will be considered at the commission's workshop and meetings,  March 6-7 in Tallahassee.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>NOTE: The Sun informed EnviroWorld that the proposed fee is $3, not  $2 as had been reported.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor360978"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor360978">Water Project 2000 means better water for Orlando</A></H3><DL>  <DD>ORLANDO-- (EnviroWorld)-- The Orlando Utilities Commission's newest  plant will be the first in North and Central Florida to produce ozone-cleaned  water, the Orlando Sentinel reported. The process, common in Europe and  California, produces clean water without chlorine.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>In ozone-cleaned water, air is combined with an electrical current  in a chamber and bubbled through water from the aquifer. Bacteria is removed  the instant it is struck with ozone. OUC will still have to inject a small  amount of chlorine into the water to insure it does not pick up any bacteria  while traveling though pipes.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The $27 million plant will produce water some compare to the taste  of mountain spring water. OUC began considering the process when they discovered  that more than one-third of their customers drink bottled water because  they do not like the taste of their tap water.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The southwest plant will begin providing the new water to Universal  Studios and surrounding businesses and homes no later than March. By the  year 2000, OUC plans to have expanded the new process to Orlando and Orange  County.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The typical monthly bill will go from about $10 a month to $14.42 a  month.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor362368"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor362368">Water authority members pick apart the new plan</A></H3><DL>  <DD>BROOKSVILLE-- (EnviroWorld)-- Today's West Coast Regional Water Supply  Authority meeting in Clearwater will discuss the proposal that was to end  the water wars, the Tampa Tribune reported. The proposal calls for all  members to give their wellfield rights to the authority and for the expansion  of the voting board from five to nine members.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Pinellas and Hillsborough counties have approved the plan. Pasco has  agreed, but wants to make some changes. The St. Petersburg City Council  is deferring a decision until next month and Tampa has not considered it  at all.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Pasco's desired change to the plan would allow any county where a new  wellfield is to be built to seek an administrative hearing independent  of the West Coast Authority. Hillsborough County is in favor of this change.  Pasco and Hillsborough counties are the only places a new wellfield could  be built.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Pinellas County and St. Petersburg are concerned about the new distribution  of votes. Currently, each has one in five votes. Under the new nine member  board plan, Pinellas would have two votes and St. Petersburg would have  one, shifting their voting power from 40 percent to about 33 percent.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Another issue is the worth of wellfields. Consultants value them at  $2 for every gallon the wellfields can produce daily and $2,000 an acre  for the property. Bill Johnston, director of St. Petersburg utilities,  says that the price is low, especially for the 584 acres at the corner  of Dale Mabry Highway and Van Dyke Road. If it wasn't a wellfield, he says,  it would be a subdivision.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor364023"></A></H5><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5><H3><A HREF="#anchor364023">Collier County tries for water restrictions</A></H3><DL>  <DD>COLLIER COUNTY-- (EnviroWorld)-- The executive director of Big Cypress  Basin, Clarence Tears, plans to lobby county commissioners to impose a  daytime watering ban on Collier County, the Naples Daily News reported.  Collier County is currently the only coastal county in the South Florida  Water Management District without such a ban.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The ban prevents watering from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., the times when water  evaporation is the highest.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The idea of imposing the restrictions has been discussed for several  years without any action. This year's dry weather may be the push the county  commission has needed to pass the resolution.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Collier County's average rainfall for 1996 was nearly seven inches  below the average of 55 inches per year. The West Tamiami Aquifer, a crucial  water supplier for Collier County, is 3.68 inches below last year's level.  <DD>&nbsp;</DL><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
