s.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Most interesting is that two boards will try to establish alternative  ways to measure compliance and enforcement at the DEP. DEP officials have  complained that the effectiveness of the agency's new &quot;culture&quot;  of cooperation cannot be measured with traditional enforcement statistics,  such as fines. One of the boards will develop methods of measuring environmental  improvement; the other will figure out what data is needed for those measures  and to assess management  quality.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The last board  is charged with eliminating unnecessary paperwork between  DEP and EPA.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5><A NAME="anchor441820"></A></H5><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor441820">South Florida to store water in undergroundwells</A></H3><DL>  <DD>MIAMI -- (EnviroWorld) -- The Miami-Dade Water and Sewer Department  announced a $4.5 million project Tuesday that will store up to 15 million  gallons of water in deep wells by next year, the Miami Herald reported.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The water would be reserved for use when water demand peaks during  dry seasons. The wells are an improvement to storing water in open canals,  which lose water to evaporation.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Miami-Dade project consists of three wells as much as 1,300 feet  deep, and will be located near the Everglades National Park in West Dade.  The system works by pumping fresh water from the shallow Biscayne Aquifer  into wells in the deeper Floridan Aquifer. In South Florida, the Floridan  normally contains brackish water; pumping fresh water in displaces that  brackish water and creates a natural cell for water storage.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Similar wells are being planned throughout South Florida, and it was  predicted that as much as 900 million gallons of water will be stored in  such wells within 10  years.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><P><B></B>&nbsp;</P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><P><A NAME="anchor443533"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor443533">Keys sanctuary plan approved</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)-- Gov. Lawton Chiles and the Cabinet have  approved a management plan for the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary,  the Miami Herald reported.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The plan institutes new safety rules to reduce reckless boating, establishes  research teams to investigate why the reefs are dying, makes 19 areas off-limits  to fishing vessels, improves channel markers and increases protection of  sea grass beds. The only issue left unresolved by the plan is the governing  of treasure salvage .  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Sanctuary opponents were concerned that the federal government would  take over control of the keys. Under the plan adopted by the governor and  Cabinet, federal agencies need state approval to impose user fees on boats  and will not be able to either block building permits or impose emergency  rules.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><P><A NAME="anchor445398"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor445398">New CARL acquisitions</A></H3><DL>  <DD>TALLAHASSEE--(EnviroWorld)-- The Belle Meade project in Collier County,  number three on the CARL priority list, has been expanded by the addition  of two parcels of land, the Department of Environmental Protection reported.  One parcel, 42.6 acres, was purchased for $73,700. The second parcel, 39.9  acres and a single-family residence, was purchased for $245,000.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The addition of these lands to the Picayune Strand State Forest will  protect Florida panther, Florida black bear and red-cockaded woodpecker  habitat. The property will be managed by the Department of Agriculture's  Division of Forestry.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Crystal River State Buffer Preserve will receive an additional  515.7 acres as part of the Florida Springs Coastal Greenway. The property  was approved for acquisition at $3,900,000.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The project protects water quality in the springs where manatees congregate,  preserves natural lands that link with conservation lands and provide fishing  and hiking availability.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The area will be managed by the DEP's Division of Marine Resources.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><P><A NAME="anchor446713"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor446713">Jacksonville buys parks with canal refund</A></H3><DL>  <DD>JACKSONVILLE--(EnviroWorld)-- The Jacksonville City Council has approved  $3.7 million for the creation of two new parks, the Florida Times-Union  reported. The money for the Parks will come from a $5 million reimbursement  from the state for the defunct Cross-Florida Barge Canal.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Southeast Regional Park in Mandarin will be the largest park in  the city at 630 acres. The purchase price of the park is estimated at about  $6 million. The council has approved $2.4 million for initial acquisition.    <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The council agreed also to purchase the Sisters Creek Marina for $1.3  million. The site is north of Joseph Carlucci State Park and is one of  the most-used boat ramps in the city. </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><P><A NAME="anchor448019"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor448019">Keys residents object to missile launch</A></H3><DL>  <DD>KEY WEST--(EnviroWorld)-- The military is considering launching dummy  missiles from the Keys to be shot down by defensive missiles from Eglin  Air Force Base in Pensacola, the Miami Herald reported. Residents of the  Keys are displeased with the idea, citing the environmental sensitivity  of the area as a main concern.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The Air Force claims that the Pensacola-Keys plan is the only way they  can test midrange defense missiles. They can now test their missiles within  190 or over 620 miles, but launching from the Keys is the only way they  can test in between.   <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Officials from Eglin have set up exhibits giving information on the  tests and a video showing the environmental cautions that will be taken.  A decision on the site is expected by the middle of 1998.</DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><P><A NAME="anchor449496"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor449496">Plastic surplus drops prices</A></H3><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON--(EnviroWorld)-- A surplus of virgin plastic resin has caused  the prices of polyethylene terephthalate(PET) to drop, according to the  Daily Environment Report.  The drop in prices has lead recycling advocates  to push for minimum content legislation in some states. The legislatures  in California, Wisconsin, and New York are starting new sessions and may  look at bills that require plastic bottle manufacturers to make products  that contain a certain amount of recycled PET.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>A bill being considered in Wisconsin would require plastic bottles  sold in the state to include 25% recycled content; after five years the  bottles would be required to contain 50% recycled content. Wisconsin's  current minimum content law allows manufacturers to be in noncompliance  if the state has a 10% recycling rate, but under the new law noncompliers  would be fined.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>The recycling rate dropped from 34% in 1994 to 32% in 1995. The rate  is expected to drop below 30% for 1996. </DL><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><H5>&nbsp;</H5><P><A NAME="anchor450632"></A><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><H3><A HREF="#anchor450632">EPA to decide criminal prosecution in DC</A></H3><DL>  <DD>WASHINGTON D.C.--(EnviroWorld)--The EPA has announced that its Washington  office, rather than the agency's field and regional offices, will decide  whether to pursue a criminal investigation against a company which discovers  possible criminal behavior through a voluntary audit, according to the  Holland &amp; Knight Daily Environmental Report.  <DD>&nbsp;  <DD>Field and regional offices are responsible for enforcement decisions  regarding other types of violations uncovered through an audit.<BR>  </DL><H5><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="../index.html">Return to today's headlines</A></FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></H5></BODY></HTML>
