n to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor367355">Comish threatens suit against DEP workers</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE><STRONG>NORTH FLORIDA </STRONG>county commissioner has askedthe state Department of Environmental Protection to fire one of its employeesand vowed to sue several DEP workers in federal court for alleged harassmentand unfair treatment. <BR>Gregg Diehl, a Wakulla County commissioner, asked the state to fire DonnaPope, an environmental specialist responsible for permitting in WakullaCounty, after she criticized him in a letter to the editor published in<CITE>The Wakulla News.</CITE> The DEP is reviewing the charges by Diehl,the owner of a liquor store and a developer, that Pope, a six-year employeewho lives in Wakulla County, has allowed her personal opinions to influenceher work. <BR>Pope, who could not be reached by FE for comment, told a reporter for the<CITE>Tallahassee Democrat</CITE> that, &quot;I do have a life outside ofDEP. I believe as long as the First Amendment is up and running, I do havea right to express my opinion.&quot; Diehl said that Pope and other DEPemployees began &quot;holding Wakulla County to a higher (environmental)standard&quot; after commissioners approved a controversial developmentadjacent to Wakulla Springs, a pristine, state-run park.<BR>The building of a country store and RV park has been held up by an injunctionissued by Circuit Court Judge Phil Padovano. Diehl also said he intendsto sue Pope and several other DEP employees he refused to name when histerm expires in November. He said he will sue them in federal court for&quot;harassment and failure to provide equal protection under the law.&quot;<BR>&quot;I have been physically accosted, I have been verbally accosted&quot;by DEP employees, Diehl said. &quot;I have had my personal development heldup.<BR>&quot;They are like dealing with a bunch of jack-boat thugs. That's howDEP employees have acted in our community. It's time for somebody to takethem to task.&quot;<BR><A NAME="anchor1268654"></A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1304373">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor1268654">Florida legislators get failing grade fromdoctors worried about enviro votes affect on children</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE><STRONG>MOST OF FLORIDA'S</STRONG> congressional delegationshould have gotten coal in their stockings for Christmas, according to ananalysis by a physicians group of how well lawmakers protected America'schildren from health hazards in their food, air, water, homes and schools.<BR>&quot;Their voting records on key legislation affecting environmental, healthand safety regulations show that most members do not consider our childrento be this country's most vulnerable and valuable natural resource,&quot;said Dr. Bill Slayton, a Gainesville pediatrician and member of Physiciansfor Social Responsibility. <BR>&quot;We must demand that Congress do all it can to protect our children.&quot;<BR>Of Florida's 25 congressmen and women reviewed by the doctors' group, sevenwere issued an &quot;A&quot; (all were Democrats); 10 received &quot;F&quot;(all were Republicans); and eight others were given grades ranging fromB to D. &quot;We are talking a lot these days about saving money and balancingthe budget, but we need to do it in a way that is going to allow us to protectwhat's important,&quot; said Dr. Jake Taylor, one of the founding membersof the University of Florida's medical school. &quot;It takes a lot moremoney to treat cancer than to prevent it from occurring from environmentalhazards.&quot; <BR>In the 11 Senate votes and 22 House votes analyzed, more than 100 membersof the 104th Congress failed to vote to protect children even once, physicianswith the 20,000 member, non-partisan group said. The doctors issued failinggrades to the majority of Florida's delegation in December after reviewinghow lawmakers voted on these issues: </BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><UL><LI>Pesticides and other contaminants in food. Kids eat more (by weight)of fewer types of food than adults, and are more vulnerable to toxic pesticidesand potentially deadly food-borne bacteria, doctors said. Nearly half ofthe food kids eat includes detectable residues of one or more pesticides- almost none of which have been fully tested for their effects on children,doctors said. <LI>Lead, asbestos, pesticides and second-hand smoke in homes and schools.Nearly 10 percent of all children (and more than one-third of African Americanchildren) have elevated blood lead levels. Lead poisoning can cause irreversiblelearn disabilities. Doctors also noted that the walls and ceilings in morethan 30,000 schools nationwide still have deteriorating asbestos, long linkedwith lung damage. <LI>Air pollution. Again, children are particularly threatened by air pollutionbecause they breath more air (by weight) than adults. Cases of childhoodasthma have increased by 40 percent between 1982 and 1990, doctors said.&quot;Many believe, again, that this increase is from air pollution,&quot;Taylor said. Researchers suspect that children may also be more vulnerableto the emerging effects of global climate change, which is increasinglylinked to air pollution. <LI>Bacteria, lead, pesticides and other contaminants in drinking water.Children drink more than twice as much water (by weight) as adults do andare more vulnerable to a wide range of health problems from water pollution.&quot;I know a lot of parents now who are using bottled water because theydon't trust the water out of their taps,&quot; Taylor said. </UL>&quot;Twenty years from now, I think state-to-state we will be fightingover water as some states pollute their water and come looking for cleanwater.&quot; <BR>&quot;This score card is a very, very meaningful tally,&quot; Taylor toldreporters at a news conference. <BR>&quot;The voters in this state should keep it in mind when they go to thepolls.&quot; &quot;Voters might want to recommend detention and study hall,&quot;said Monte Belote, executive director of Florida Consumer Action Network,a grassroots statewide advocacy group which helped sponsor the news conferenceand distribute the physicians' findings. <BR><A NAME="anchor1274271"></A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1304373">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor1274271">Recycle markets look calmer this year</A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE><BR><STRONG>AFTER A ROLLER </STRONG>coaster year for recyclers, experts predicta calmer year in 1996--maybe.<BR>&quot;I think we are still going to have volatility,&quot; said Ed Hurley,manager of legislative affairs for Jefferson Smurfit, one the country'sbiggest paper recyclers. &quot;But I don't think you will have a big swing.&quot;<BR>Barbara Drake, president of Jacksonville-based Southland Recycling Services,agreed.<BR>&quot;I think we are going to have a good steady demand and prices willincrease to a reasonable price,&quot; Drake said. &quot;I don't think wewill see the spikes.&quot; <BR>Prices for recycled glass, traditionally a less volatile commodity thanpaper, will probably continue as they have in the past, said Dave Baker,regional director for the Glass Packaging Institute, a trade association.<BR>&quot;Over the last several years, we have seen it remain pretty steady,&quot;Baker said.<BR>An estimated 40 percent of Florida's municipal waste was recycled in 1995,up from 15 percent in 1990, according to the state Department of EnvironmentalProtection. And as recycling has increased, the number of municipal solid-wastelandfills in the state has dropped from about 500 in 1980 to about 100 today.<BR>Yet despite the positive outlook for the recycling market, some environmentalistsworry that when Florida lawmakers meet again in March, they will rollbackstate recycling mandates.<BR>&quot;Right now, I'm concerned about the funding,&quot; said Suzi Ruhl,president of the Legal Environmental Defense Fund.<BR>Currently, the state mandates that counties with populations greater than50,000 strive to recycle 30 percent of their overall municipal solid wasteand 50 percent of each of these five materials: newspaper, glass bottles,aluminum cans, plastic bottles and steel cans. <BR><BR><B>Soaring paper prices</B><BR>During 1995, Drake and others said, the price for recycled paper rocketedfrom $30 to $40 per ton to $200 a ton.<BR>&quot;During this last year, it spiked for maybe six months,&quot; Drakesaid. &quot;I've never seen it spike like that before.&quot; <BR>&quot;That's a pretty dramatic swing in the price,&quot; agreed Steve Levetan,the chairman for Florida's Recycling Markets Advisory Committee. &quot;Marketprices have seen some all-time highs. But whether it's low or it's high,it's a function of where you are in the market place. It's strictly an issueof supply and demand.&quot; <BR>The demand for recycled paper has continued to grow as more pulp and papermills invest in manufacturing process that use recyclables. About a thirdof the nation's 600 pulp and paper mills now use 100-percent recovered fiberin their manufacturing processes; another third use all virgin products;and the final third use some combination of virgin and recovered fiber,Levetan said. <BR>What happened in 1995 to cause the cost of paper to soar, according to Hurley,was that &quot;We had a domestic imbalance and the export market heatedup.&quot; <BR>If buyers of recycled paper for mills think they may not be able to getthe amount of recycled paper their mills need, they can panic. They neverwant to come up short, experts said.<BR>&quot;When you're a buyer, your job is to buy the best quality at the lowestprice - but don't you ever shut the mill down,&quot; Hurley allowed.<BR>Drake said she hopes the price of recycled paper will swing back up fromits current $30 to $40 a ton price to what she says is a more fair one ofabout $80 to $100 a ton.<BR><BR><B>Possible recycling setbacks</B><BR>A bill may surface in the upcoming session to rollback the state's mandated30-percent goal for all municipal wastes, and 50-percent goal for the bigfive recyclables.<BR>That would be a mistake, environmentalists said.<BR>&quot;Communities are very much supportive of it and they want to do it,&quot;Ruhl said. Others, however, say such a rollback won't change much.<BR>&quot;We want to see those programs continue because, obviously, from theindustry viewpoint, we want the materials,&quot; Levetan said. &quot;Butthe sorts of things you are seeing out there now have become pretty institutionalized.<BR>&quot;We have got over 3 million households in the state of Florida thathave curbside recycling programs. Take away a mandate that was frankly neverenforced, and I think you will see very little impact.&quot; <BR>Levetan notes that the paper industry has sunk &quot;billions of dollars&quot;into using recovered paper, and that the glass industry &quot;has also builtup a considerable infrastructure for recyclables.&quot; To Drake, however,the biggest potential impact on the recycling market comes from consumers.&quot;The real support comes from the people,&quot; she said. &quot;If peoplewant to buy recycled materials, that demand for the product will pull recyclingalong. But you have got to have that demand.&quot; <BR><A NAME="anchor1282907"></A></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1304373">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor1282907">Water <STRONG>district legislation to get considerableattention this year</STRONG></A></H3><BLOCKQUOTE><STRONG>GOV. LAWTON </STRONG>Chiles will have final say overthe state's five water-management districts' budgets if the Legislatureadopts the recommendations made by a review commission created by lawmakersin 1994. <BR>The 21-member panel did not, however, recommend that the Florida Legislaturehave final say-so over the water-management districts millage rates, assome critics of the current water-management system have advocated.<BR>&quot;There are those who are going to think we didn't go far enough,&quot;said Philip Lewis, chairman of the Water Management District Review Commissionand a former Florida senator from 1970 to 1980. <BR>&quot;There are those who would like to see the water-management districtsdone away with. Some would like to see them put under one commission ordistrict.&quot; <BR>But, Lewis added, &quot;I think the commission did a good job. We put infar more accountability. ...Now that we have pinpointed the responsibility,the governor needs to get a water czar to advise him.&quot; <BR>Like Lewis, Sen. John McKay, R-Bradenton, one of the 21 members of the commission,said he was also pleased with the panel's work. But he advocates makingstill more changes in the way the districts, created by the Legislaturein 1972, do business. <BR>&quot;My primary focus all along has been on governance and accountability,and one of the things I think is very important is that some elected boardbe responsible for approving their (water-management districts') budgets,&quot;said McKay, who sponsored the legislation that created the commission aftersome citizens and lawmakers complained that the districts were too arrogantand confusing to deal with. <BR>To make the districts more accountable, McKay said, he would like to seethe Legislature control their millage rates. &quot;We would like to captheir millage rates at the current level and let them come to the Legislaturefor approval of any further increases in millage,&quot; McKay said. <BR>Since the commission did not include such a proposal among its 80 recommendations,McKay said he will file legislation to establish such caps during the nextsession. Lewis and others, however, say that would be going to far.<BR>&quot;You control their millage, you control their life,&quot; Lewis said.&quot;I feel strongly that that would be a bad idea.&quot; But, he added,&quot;I suspect it would pass.&quot; <BR>And if it did, he said, &quot;It would probably be one of the most divisivethings that could be passed. I think that John is trying to swat at antswith an ax.&quot; T<BR>he problem, Lewis said, is that would be nearly impossible to get the entireLegislature's approval of even a much-needed tax increase, especially inan election year. <BR>A final report of the commission's proposals should be available sometimein early January, said Sally Bond Mann, the executive director of the panel.(<B>For more information about the final report, call Mann at (904) 922-0981.)</B><BR>More commission recommendations and Florida water wars While the commissionleft the water-management districts intact, it did make several recommendationscommissioners hope will make the districts more user friendly, Mann said.<BR>Those include: </BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><UL><LI>Issuing, where appropriate, 20-year water-use (consumption) permits.&quot;They can be issued for up to 20 years now, but none of the districtsdo it,&quot; Mann said. <LI>Adding an ombudsman office to each district whose &quot;sole purposein life is to answer questions about permitting,&quot; Mann said. <LI>Doing water-supply research. &quot;We've asked the Legislature to directthe water-management districts to focus on water supply development research,&quot;Mann said. </UL>The commission also recommended that each water-management governing boardshould inventory its surface and ground waters and decide on a date by whenit can establish minimum flows and levels. <BR>Some, like engineer Bart Bibler, formerly with the state Department of EnvironmentalProtection and now a private consultant, say the commission went too farwith that and several other recommendations. &quot;Instead of that levelbeing based on science and resource protection, they want to change it toreflect economics,&quot; Bibler said. &quot;I think the commission was largelydriven by agricultural issues.&quot; <BR>Because Florida's water policies and institutions are being scrutinized,and sometimes changed, Bibler is proposing each county engage in a &quot;Florida water dialogue,&quot; involving the Florida Advisory Council onEnvironmental Education, the University of Florida and Florida State University.<BR>&quot;I think we have a tremendous need for such a dialogue,&quot; Biblersaid. &quot;Are we headed toward water wars in Florida? I think we're alreadythere. Tampa's a mess.&quot; <BR><B>(For more information on the water dialogue Bibler is proposing, callhim at (904) 386-2721.) </B>McKay says commission has changed districts'attitude Whether lawmakers adopt all of the commission's proposals or not,said McKay, just the formation of the commission has caused districts tochange their attitude. <BR>&quot;One of the things that strikes me as ironic is that when you heardpeople talking about water-management districts, whether you would classifythose people as environmentalists or representative of agricultural interests,there seemed to be universal frustration with the activities of the water-managementdistricts,&quot; McKay said. &quot;They were more concerned about theirself-preservation and expansions&quot; than anything else. <BR>Lewis blames some of the fire the districts have drawn on the maze of paperworkrequired for many projects. <BR>&quot;It has gotten totally out of hand,&quot; Lewis said. <BR>&quot;The killing of trees to fill out paperwork is incredible.&quot; <BR>But, Mann noted, water-management districts have in many cases been unfairlyslammed. <BR>&quot;They are not out there undertaking things they are not authorizedto do,&quot; she noted. <BR>&quot;I think at least some of those who have been complaining the loudestabout the water-management districts have come to understand that they arenot the water culprits they've been made out to be.&quot;</BLOCKQUOTE><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1304373">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR></BODY></HTML>
