<H3><A HREF="#anchor244958">Florida's DEP is alienating its historic friends</A></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>One top DEP official says the agency's current disfavor among
traditional allies is a case of public policy in stereo: if both sides are
loud you can hear the message well. But with the volume of discontent about
Florida's environmental protection efforts reaching new highs, a message
that was once in stereo is now in suround-sound.<BR>
<BR>
Florida's Department of Environmental Protection has now, it seems, alienated
most of its historic friends. The grousing has transcended the normal criticism
that comes with telling a given special interest group &quot;no.&quot; The
complaints now even come from within Governor Chiles Administration, from
the federal EPA, from Florida's local environmental regulatory officials,
and from every single environmental group in the state. <BR>
<BR>
Perhaps only time will tell, but DEP is either doing something very right--or
very, very wrong. Either way, they clearly are alone in the wilds of the
environment-and whether they are protecting it or not remains a hotly debated
issue.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Breaking ranks<BR>
</B><BR>
It's bad enough at DEP that even the head of Florida's chief environmental
rulemaking body is publically campaigning for reforms. In meetings with
Florida Environments' editorial staff last month, Environmental Regulation
Commission chairman Dick Batchelor detailed his concerns over the direction
and management at DEP-and concerns that Chiles needs to take a tougher environmental
stand.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Some in the department think I'm singing off key,&quot; Batchelor
said. &quot;But I'm encouraging the Governor to take a stronger stand on
the environment. I am urging him to make a serious commitment to stronger
environmental protection efforts in his State of the State speech [March
6th].&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And as for DEP's leadership, Batchelor said that &quot;many times I've found
myself at odds with Secretary Wetherell.&quot; Batchelor, a Chiles' appointee,
is particularly concerned that the Ecosystem Management program championed
by Chiles and Wetherell lacks teeth. According to Batchelor, this feel-good
form of environmental regulation needs to have more bite.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;At some point [DEP] has to be able to say, 'we're not going to allow
that' to a polluter,&quot; Batchelor said.<BR>
<BR>
DEP assistant secretary Dale Patchett would not comment on Batchelor's position,
saying only that the Governor and Batchelor &quot;need to discuss the issues.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The DEP's lack of teeth of late is directly linked to the outward migration
of several of its top staffers. In the last year, DEP's highly respected
assistant secretary Dan Thompson left the agency for a private law practice,
water facilitiy chief Richard Harvey took a private sector job, and now
manatee-program champion Pat Rose is headed for Audubon's Save the Manatee
program. <BR>
<BR>
None of these officials would publically condemn DEP's brass although Pat
Rose spoke in the code of the disaffected: &quot;I need to re-evaluate if
I'm in the professional environment where protecting and preserving ecosystems
can best be served.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Rose's comments typified the between the lines comments Florida Environments
has heard from other top-level staffers. Privately, several sources have
indicated first-hand knowledge that Thompson and Harvey's departures were
almost entirely driven by disenchantment with DEP's effectiveness. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Underbelly of the beast</B><BR>
The fact that a sitting ERC chairman is publicly criticizing his boss is
unprecedented and, according to the state's top environmentalist, illustrates
the gravity of the situation at DEP.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Traditionally, the ERC is the [DEP] Secretary's support mechanism,&quot;
says Florida Audubon Society president Clay Henderson. &quot;For Batchelor
to be saying these things is really indicative of the seriousness of the
problems at DEP.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Henderson puts responsibility for the decline in DEP's environmental performance
on two factors:<BR>
the as yet unsuccessful DER/DNR merger that formed the state's super environmental
agency, and &quot;that we have a number of former legislators [in DEP's
leadership] . . . politicizing everything. We don't have the type of people
in charge there that we've had in the past.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Henderson sides with Batchelor over concerns that DEP's enforcement has
waned-and that ecosystem management will only worsen the situation. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;One thing about Audubon,&quot; says Henderson, &quot;is that we have
eyes and ears all over the state. And I can tell you that during the three
week [federal] shutdown the phone started ringing. People saw more environmental
violations. Well, we stopped calling DEP because they aren't going to do
anything about it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Other environmental enforcers underwhelmed too<BR>
</B><BR>
At a retreat last month to discuss partnerships between federal, state and
local environmental regulators, Florida's top environmental officials sent
only words, not staff. <BR>
<BR>
The EPA and Florida's Local Environmental Resources Agencies held a &quot;Partnership
Conference&quot; near Jacksonville aimed at better cooperation between the
agencies in order to reduce government duplication while increasing environmental
protection. (FLERA is formed of the directors and top staff of Florida's
local environmental agencies.)<BR>
<BR>
But Florida's DEP was scarcely present at the meeting-saying legislative
committees kept them in Tallahassee. The EPA, however, on the eve of another
possible federal shutdown, flew in at least seven of its top officials for
the two-day meeting. EPA staff at the meeting included Regional Administrator
John Hankinson, his first deputy, four Division directors, a senior attorney
and the local program liaison. <BR>
<BR>
DEP, on the other hand, asked District Director Ernie Frey to drive 20 minutes
from his office in Jacksonville to the meeting. This has infuriated Florida's
local environmental program officials.<BR>
&quot;It's more than disappointing, it's sad,&quot; said FLERA president
Karen Collins, who is also the director of Manatee County's environmental
program. <BR>
<BR>
Collins and other FLERA officials feel that DEP is not asking for or listening
to FLERA's input on the important environmental issues of the day. &quot;And
we're the ones out there, on-site, working with the regulated community,&quot;
Collins said. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It boils down to power and money: DEP's got it and doesn't want to
give any of it to our programs even though we're doing many of their functions,&quot;
Collins told FE.<BR>
<BR>
DEP counters that a meeting the week before the workshop between Wetherell
and top FLERA officials was productive and informative. And DEP has made
a commitment to work more closely with FLERA staff during the session.<BR>
<BR>
As for only sending Frey to the meeting, DEP's spokesperson Lea Crusberg
says the issues were local issues and so Frey's presence was appropriate.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Federal fallout<BR>
</B><BR>
The retreat was to have increased inter-agency dialogue and set the stage
for increased federal-state-local program delegation of environmental programs.
The delegation issue is a top priority for EPA administrator Carol Browner.<BR>
<BR>
EPA officials were more guarded in their analysis of DEP's absence. &quot;We're
going to keep hammering at them [DEP],&quot; said EPA local program liaison
Tom Moore. &quot;Right now, we have more of a dialogue with Florida's local
programs than with the state.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
EPA is trying to work with Florida to set up a Project XL program here that
would allow the state greater flexibility in implementing and enforcing
certain EPA programs. The notion that DEP would get more discretion has
given many observers the jitters.<BR>
<BR>
For instance, &quot;some of the choices that DEP made of rules targeted
for elimination was very arbitrary,&quot; said FLERA's Collins.<BR>
<BR>
Patchett countered that rules reduction was a process that was &quot;not
any more comfortable for us than for [FLERA].&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Batchelor seemed to feel that Tallahassee's softening on the environment
was a result of the &quot;Newt ether&quot; which has largely worn off-or
should have.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'm concerned about the new political environment in Tallahassee,&quot;
says the former legislator. &quot;It's time to swing back towards where
the polls say Americans want their government: enforcing strong environmental
regulations.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Chiles' spokesperson April Herrle says that, despite Batchelor's comments,
the Governor is still behind DEP.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;DEP is trying to solve problems, not point fingers,&quot; Herrle told
FE.<BR>
<BR>
<B>My Secretary, right or wrong<BR>
</B><BR>
Herrle's response is just what Henderson might have predicted.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's clear that the DEP has the complete support of the Governor,&quot;
Henderson allowed. &quot;But it's equally clear that DEP does not speak
with one voice. Performance is spotty. And that has put them at odds with
each other-not just the environmental community-over certain issues.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Audubon's vice-president Charles Lee put a positive spin on the situation.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The fact that a key leader like Dick Batchelor is beating the drum
is a very hopeful sign. We'll find out how well he's done on the sixth of
March.&quot;</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor797149"></A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to State
News Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="../News/FlaEnewsToday.html">Return to today's
headlines</A><HR> 
<H3><A HREF="#anchor797149">State spends millions on enviro projects--but
not water dialogue</A></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>More than $1.1 million will be doled out this year to bankroll
30 environmental projects, thanks to money collected from the sale of Florida
manatee and panther license plates. The council that selects the projects,
however, has found itself saddled with controvery and allegations that its
selection process is politically tainted.<BR>
<BR>
In a year when the council's very existance is up for grabs in the Legislature,
several of the proposals approved for funding went to state agencies--including
a $70,280 award to the Department of Corrections, so that it may develop
an environmental-education program for youthful offenders &quot;focusing
on Florida's unique environments and employability skills.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Critics say the Florida Advisory Council on Environmental Education is playing
to the politicians in an effort to stay alive in the law-and the budget.<BR>
<BR>
Bart Bibler, a Tallahassee engineer who says he submitted a proposal in
good faith to the Florida Advisory Council on Environmental Education, has
charged that the council denied his proposal to hold statewide &quot;water
dialogues&quot; because of politics. <BR>
<BR>
The program, co-sponsored by the University of Florida and FSU, would have
funded 67 public meetings statewide where citizens could have learned of
and commented on water-related legislation that will be considered this
year.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They really are not too excited about having a public dialogue on
water issues,&quot; said Bibler, whose $95,000 proposal was shot down by
the council earlier this year. &quot;I think it (the council) is being politically
controlled.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The council's executive director, Madeline Strong, said Bibler is dead wrong.
Council members did have concerns about Bibler's project, she said, but
they centered around duplication of efforts, the competitive process used
to select projects, and that some local governments did not want to participate
in Bibler's project. <BR>
<BR>
Bibler, however, pointed to letters from FACEE members Sen. George Kirkpatrick,
D-Gainesville, and Estus Whitfield, the governor's environmental policy
advisor, as signs that his project was shot down for political reasons.
And he said the council gave him the green light in December, then killed
it a month later.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We went forward with those directions from the council, only to come
back in January and be told that 'You don't deserve the money because you're
out of cycle,'&quot; Bibler said. &quot;That, on its face, is being misled.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
FACEE was created by the Legislature in 1989 to promote environmental education.
Council members include appointees from the Florida Senate and House of
Representatives; the Governor and the Executive Office; the Department of
Education; DEP; Game &amp; Fresh Water Fish Commission; and the Environmental
Education Foundation of Florida.<BR>
<BR>
Like all of the state's trust funds, the one which pays for FACEE must be
periodically reviewed by the Legislature. This session, if the Legislature
does not renew the environmental education trust fund, it will no longer
exist. Last year, the House passed a bill to get rid of the trust fund,
while the Senate passed one to re-create it. The issue then stalled and
eventually died.<BR>
<BR>
Bibler said FACEE's uncertain future this legislative session is another
reason why council members did not want to fund any project, such as his,
that might ruffle any political feathers.<BR>
<BR>
But Strong said that Whitfield was concerned only that Bibler's project
did not follow the normal competitive process - &quot;Estus is a stickler
for not funding projects outside the competitive process. (and) was not
convinced that this was an emergency situation ...&quot; - and that Kirkpatrick's
letter only &quot;raised the issue of duplication of effort and that it
be discussed at the meeting. ... He did not ask the council to vote against
it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
However, Kirkpatrick's letter to FACEE Chairman and fellow lawmaker, Rep.
John Rayson (D-Pompano Beach), specifically statres &quot;I believe it is
imperative that the council avoid funding projects that would be a duplication
of effort...&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Likewise, a letter from Sally Bond Mann, executive director of the Legislature's
Water Management District Review Commission, wrote FACEE that Bibler's project
was &quot;wholly unnecessary, duplicative, poorly designed and impossible
to accomplish within the timeframes indicated and budget proposed.&quot;
She also described the timetable as &quot;laughable.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
State officials hold that the public meetings run by the Water Management
Review Commission<BR>
have given Florida citizens a place to be heard. Bibler counters that those
meetings &quot;were a sham. The special interests that dominated the [WMD]
Review Commission meetings don't want the citizens to have a voice in the
future of Florida's water resources,&quot; Bibler told FE.<BR>
<BR>
This year, FACEE's biggest grant went to beef up the state's efforts at
manatee education. The council awarded $107,280 to the Department of Environmental
Protection's Bureau of Protected Species Management's Manatee Education
and Information Project.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They had an unexpected hit after the legislative session,&quot; Strong
said of the DEP's grant. &quot;Their budget got cut.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
FACEE gets its money from the Save Our State Environmental Education Trust
Fund, which is funded with money from the state's manatee and panther tags.
Because of its money source, the council is very responsive to good projects
promoting manatee and panther education, Strong said.<BR>
<BR>
While the council receives a sufficient number of manatee proposals each
year, panther-oriented ones are not as common, Strong said. Since its creation
seven years ago, the council has awarded $954,279 on 19 projects that focused
either exclusively or in part on educating the public about manatees, she
said.<BR>
<BR>
The DEP's manatee project will be used to help produce a video and print
and reprint boaters' guides, brochures, and posters. A manatee education
video targeting Dade County will also be made, both in English and Spanish.<BR>
<BR>
The second largest grant - $82,632 - went to the state's Division of Forestry
to educate 36 teachers, 30 forestry employees and 300 kids about Florida's
forests.<BR>
<BR>
The third largest grant - $76,505 - also went to the DEP. This money will
be used to produce a video and teacher's guide on why the earth's foundation
is a critical component of Florida's ecosystems. The video will be used
in both classrooms and by some Florida Public Television stations.<BR>
<BR>
Next in line came the $70,280 award to the Department of Corrections.<BR>
<BR>
The fifth largest grant, $64,555, was given to Florida State University's
&quot;Saturday at the Sea&quot; program. The money will be used to expand
this marine environmental education program to elementary and high school
kids in the Big Bend Region of North Florida.<BR>
<A NAME="anchor825687"></A></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to State
News Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="../News/FlaEnewsToday.html">Return to today's
headlines</A><HR> 
<H3><A HREF="#anchor825687">State Ag' inspections flunk growers' pesticide-worker
safety practices</A></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>By Kathleen Laufenberg<BR>
Tallahassee bureau<BR>
<BR>
Despite tougher pesticide regulations, state inspections show worker-safety
violations continue to occur in the agricultural and nursery industry. A
major problem, some say, is that the regulations are not taken seriously.<BR>
&quot;There are enough idiots out there who would not take any precautions
unless forced to, that we think (today's worker-protection standards) are
doing more to make things better than they are to make things worse,&quot;
said a second-generation nursery grower in Central Florida who asked that
his name not be used. The situation, he said, is one where, &quot;some crazy
things [are] going on.&quot;<BR>
Those &quot;crazy things&quot; include growers allowing employees and family
members to apply pesticides without protective clothing, he said. &quot;These
guys grew up with it, and that's the way they've done it all their lives,&quot;
he said of some growers' disregard for protective measures. <BR>
Others, including those who work with migrant farm workers, criticize the
system for its continued lack of any real accountability. There is no adequate
reporting system to track pesticide-related illnesses, said Andrew Reich,
a state manager of environmental toxicology, and Sister Gail Grimes, a Catholic
nun who works with Florida farm workers. <BR>
&quot;I think it's a real shame, even a travesty, in a state where one of
the main industries is agriculture, that there is no record kept of pesticide
poisonings,&quot; said Sister Grimes, who works with Apopka farm workers
and the Farm Workers of Florida. &quot;It tells me that somewhere, there
is a lack of care for the results of agriculture on workers, that the important
thing is perhaps the industry.&quot;<BR>
According to the Florida Statistical Abstract, 59,001 workers were employed
in agricultural crop production in 1987. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Tougher rules, or toothless rules? </B><BR>
During the last several years, the US Environmental Protection Agency beefed
up pesticide-handling regulations in hopes of reducing the risk of poisoning
among agricultural workers and other pesticide handlers. Federal regulations
require warnings about pesticide applications, pesticide-safety training,
and the use of personal protective equipment. <BR>
They also restrict entry into treated areas (often for 48 hours); require
workers be provided with sanitary toilets and ample water for washing off
pesticides; and mandate the posting of the nearest medical facility's location
and that employers provide transportation if needed. <BR>
But inspections by the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services,turned
up numerous worker-safety violations. <BR>
DACS conducted 518 inspections during the April-June 1995 quarter, uncovering
196 violations - a non-compliance rate of 38 percent. <BR>
One hundred of the violations were for lack of central posting; 47 were
training infractions; 29 were for not correctly following decontamination
procedures. There were 11 safety-equipment violations; six improper re-entries
into sites sprayed by pesticides; and three worker-requirement violations.<BR>
&quot;By and large, the vast number of growers are doing their best to comply,&quot;
said Perry Sparkman, chairman of the state's Pesticide Review Council and
an industry representative. <BR>
But Kerry Dressler, vice-chair of the same council representing environmental
groups, sees things differently. <BR>
&quot;It's a big step forward,&quot; Dressler said of today's more stringent
worker-protection standards. Yet even now, &quot;as it's just beginning
to be implemented, they are already trying to put exceptions in right and
left.&quot; Inspection results are &quot;something I will be looking at.
It still needs to be checked regularly.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Workers have little choice<BR>
</B>The tougher regulations are needed, according to the fernery grower,
because many Mexican farm workers will voluntarily take health risks. <BR>
&quot;The Mexicans are fearless, and it's not because they don't know,&quot;
the grower said. &quot;Basically, they are so grateful to have a job that
makes this much money that if you told them to go back into a field that
was just sprayed, they would not hesitate to do it.&quot; <BR>
In visits to Latin America, Dressler saw similar signs of fearlessness among
workers.<BR>
&quot;I've been to places in Latin American where they still mix pesticides
with their arms,&quot; she said. <BR>
&quot;That's true,&quot; said Sister Grimes of the fern growers' description
of some Mexican workers. &quot;I agree with him. These regulations would
not be needed if there were not such situations.&quot; <BR>
As for the federally mandated worker-protection standards, Sister Grimes
said, &quot;Where they are enforced, they are helping. ...(but) There needs
to be extremely good enforcement.&quot; <BR>
Said Jay Feldman, director of the Washington, D.C.-based National Coalition
Against the Misuse of Pesticides, &quot;Typically workers are not adequately
trained before they go into the field. Training is a big part of the regulations.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>No accounting of illnesses<BR>
</B>The bottom-line-whether the new worker-protection standards reduce the
risk of pesticide poisonings and illnesses-is not being measured, officials
said.<BR>
&quot;We just don't know,&quot; said Reich, with HRS. &quot;There is no
real good surveillance programs by (HRS) or the Department of Agriculture
and Consumer Services. We don't have a good way to monitor if the illnesses
are going up or down.&quot; What is known, he said, is that &quot;We have
a fair amount of farm workers, a lot of picking done by hand, and a fairly
high use of pesticides.&quot; <BR>
Dr. James Hillman, a member of the Pesticide Review Council and a doctor
with Tampa General Hospital's Poison Information Center, agreed with Reich.
Although there is a form physicians are supposed to fill out to report pesticide
poisoning, many doctors have never heard of it, Hillman and Reich said.
And the form requires doctors to be 100-percent certain that the medical
problem is due to pesticide poisoning. <BR>
But many cases are not 100-percent clear-cut. &quot;Are there many acute
poisonings? Probably not,&quot; Hillman said. &quot;Are there many chronic
and sub-acute poisonings? Probably so.&quot; <BR>
Pesticide council chairman Sparkman, who owns a small orange grove, said
many of today's growers are using less pesticides than in the past. &quot;I
can tell you that 20 years ago, I routinely sprayed four times a year,&quot;
Sparkman said. &quot;Now I spray once a year.&quot; That's partly because
of the rising cost of pesticides, he said. <BR>
Yet the fernery operator said that a very common abuse among otherwise responsible
growers is an overuse of pesticides. &quot;One of the biggest abuses is
the thinking among some growers that if the (pesticide) bag says one teaspoon
per gallon, let's go ahead and use two,&quot; he said. <BR>
The reason that tradition continues, he said, is because &quot;It creates
really good foliage, and that's what the people want.&quot; </BLOCKQUOTE>
<A NAME="anchor817213"></A><BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to State
News Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="../News/FlaEnewsToday.html">Return to today's
headlines</A><HR> 
<H3><A HREF="#anchor817213">1996 Florida Legislative update</A></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Lawrence E. Sellers &amp;<BR>
Larry Curtin<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<I>This report is contributed by the environmental law specialty group at
the law firm of Holland &amp; Knight. Messrs. Curtin and Sellers are partners
in the firm's Tallahassee office.<BR>
</I><BR>
Legislators continued to prepare for the 1996 Regular Session by holding
another two rounds of interim committee meetings last month. Committees
in both houses are next scheduled to meet during the weeks of February 5
and 19. The 60-day regular legislative session opens on March 5. The environmental
agenda continues to develop. Here is an update on some of the issues that
are currently receiving attention:<BR>
<B>Water.</B><BR>
The staff of the House Select Committee on Water Policy released a draft
bill that would address water supply policy issues in Florida. The bill,
which would establish several water allocation areas within the state where
water allocations would be made, and which would require the setting of
minimum flows and levels for water bodies throughout the state, appears
to be very controversial. The bill will continue to evolve in the coming
weeks.<BR>
DEP is also putting together a bill to address various aspects of water
policy. This bill, expected to be markedly different from the staff proposal
that has already been released, will likely be discussed at the February
6, 1996 meeting of the House Select Committee on Water Policy. DEP is in
the process of meeting with various interest groups and receiving input
on its concepts.<BR>
<B>Petroleum Cleanup Reimbursement Programs<BR>
</B>The legislation enacted in 1995 has resulted in a significant decrease
in the number of cleanups being conducted. Legislators are continuing to
look for ways to reduce costs and to insure that the large backlog of reimbursement
claims is promptly paid. [see related story]<BR>
<B>Environmental Self Audit Privilege<BR>
</B>A bill that would establish a limited privilege and immunity from certain
penalties and litigation resulting from conducting an environmental self
audit will be pursued by regulated interests during the 1996 session. Although
some form of the environmental self audit privilege has been adopted in
some 14 states nationwide, the effort to pass this legislation was unsuccessful
in 1995 and will be very controversial again during the 1996 session. Opponents
include the environmental community and the Attorney General's office. Expect
this to be a very controversial issue.<BR>
<B>Ecosystem Management<BR>
</B>Work continues at DEP on the ecosystem management concept. To date,
no legislation that would divide the state into a number of ecosystem management
areas is circulating. The pilot programs that were authorized by the 1995
legislature appear to be moving along well. It is unlikely that significant
legislation will be adopted prior to the completion of the pilot programs.<BR>
<B>Wetlands/Glitch Bill<BR>
</B>Expect a bill to correct glitches in the ERP/wetlands programs for this
session. Some modifications likely will be made to the grandfather provisions
and there may be a few other minor changes. Wholesale revisions to wetlands
regulation programs are unlikely.<BR>
<B>Wetlands/Melaleuca</B><BR>
Representative Sembler has again filed a bill that would permit the disturbance
of wetlands that are infested with a certain percentage of melaleuca without
requiring mitigation. The bill, which was proposed last session and did
not pass, would encourage the removal of this exotic species. Expect this
bill to be very controversial again this session.<BR>
<B>Environmental Equity<BR>
</B>The Environmental Equity and Justice Commission is studying whether
there is a disproportionate and cumulative concentration of environmental
hazards in communities of people of color and low-income. The Commission
is to assess how Florida may best address these inequities, if any. The
Commission was to issue a final report with recommendations by the end of
1995; however, the Commission has just begun to hold the required public
hearings, and it now seems unlikely that it will complete its work this
year. The Commission last met on December 13; additional public hearings
are now scheduled for January 29-30 (Dade County), February 7-8 (Hillsborough
County) and February 26-27 (Duval County).<BR>
<B>Recycling Goals/Grants<BR>
</B>Most counties met the 30 percent waste reduction goal by the end of
1994. Some therefore have suggested that the state should declare a victory
and use the $20-25 million now spent each year on recycling grants or other
purposes. On the other hand, other states have higher recycling goals, so
others want to increase Florida's goal to insure that the state continues
to be a leader in solid waste management. On January 10, the Senate Committee
on Natural Resources reported a bill, SB 120, that would replace the 30
percent county recycling goal with a 50 percent state goal, phase-out the
recycling grant program and use some of these funds instead for exotic plant
control.<BR>
<B>Exotic Plant Control<BR>
</B>Non-native, invasive plants are one of the greatest threats to Florida's
biodiversity. These plants include exotic aquatic plants (like Hydrilla)
and exotic upland plants (like Melaleuca). On January 24, the House Natural
Resources Committee reported a bill, PCB NR 96-03, on this subject.<BR>
<B>Preservation 2000<BR>
</B>The Florida Preservation 2000 Act was created in 1990 to provide $300
million a year to various land acquisition agencies to purchase pristine
lands. The funding program is scheduled for legislature review this year.
On January 24, the House Natural Resources Committee reported a bill, PCB
NR 96-2, on this subject.<BR>
<B>APA Reform<BR>
</B>Governor Chiles vetoed the Administrative Procedure Act reform bill
(SB 536) and appointed his own study commission to develop recommended reforms.
This commission has been meeting since October. The commission has addressed
a number of key issues, including: whether agencies should be authorized
to grant variances or waivers to agency rules; whether agencies should be
required to codify their policies through the rulemaking process, as is
presently required; whether certain presumptions should attach to proposed
or adopted agency rules; whether one agency should be allowed to rely on
another agency's policies or guidelines in taking action on a license or
permit. The next meeting of the commission is set for February 8.<BR>
<B>Rule Reduction Initiative<BR>
</B>DEP has identified a number of legislative changes it believes are necessary
in order to implement Governor Chiles' rule reduction initiative. On Wednesday,
January 24, the Senate Committee on Natural Resources voted to introduce
a proposed committee bill, PCB HR 96-10, that would allow DEP to repeal
a number of rules.<BR>
<B>Cabinet Reform<BR>
</B>On January 24, 1995, the Florida Cabinet passed a motion to establish
a Citizens Commission on Cabinet Reform, and charged the group with conducting
a review of the responsibilities and functions designated by statute for
the Governor and Cabinet sitting as a collegial body. The Commission has
met periodically over the past year and has compiled and released its final
report. The report contains 46 recommendations and contains drafts of implementing
legislation. Several of the recommendations involve environmental and land
use regulation, not all of which would result in changes. It is likely that
at least some of these recommendations will be considered during the 1996
legislative session.<BR>
<B>Marine Fisheries Commission<BR>
</B>Representative Safley has filed HB 367 which would eliminate Governor
and Cabinet approval of the Marine Fisheries Commission rules and place
the Commission in the Department of Environmental Protection. This consolidation
will draw a significant amount of attention.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>
