<A NAME="anchor244958"></A><BR>
<HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to State
News Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="FlaEnewsMonthMarch96.html">Return to this
month's headlines</A><HR><B><A HREF="#anchor244958">Enviro-business group
opens doors with state officials</A></B><BR>
TALLAHASSEE--The state's top environmental official last month opened the
doors to better business relationships for an emerging state enviro business
group by offering to host discussions on issues of mutual concern.<BR>
<BR>
Florida Department of Environmental Protection secretary Virginia Wetherell
told 50 top executives from the environmental engineering and consulting
industry that they should form a work group to discuss issues with her top
staff. Wetherell suggested a time line for the discussions with representatives
of the Southern Environmental Business Council and promised to listen closely
to their input.<BR>
<BR>
According to comments from several enviro business leaders, this development
reverses a perceived two year decline in the standing enviro industry officials
have felt related to issues they bring before the Department.<BR>
<BR>
The occasion for the dialogue between regulators and business people was
a breakfast meeting hosted by SEBC in Tallahassee last month. Wetherell
and Florida House Natural Resources Committee chairman Everett Kelley spoke
at the meeting.<BR>
<BR>
SEBC's legislative affairs committee met after the breakfast and began refining
the agenda for discussion with DEP. Talks concerning next year's legislative
session will be scheduled in April or May.<BR>
<BR>
An April SEBC breakfast meeting will also feature an opportunity for enviro
industry officials to help dictate their business future. The featured speaker,
Dr. James Morris, is an international marketing and trade expert. Morris,
from South Carolina, was instrumental in such recent international developments
as the Mercedes-Benz plant siting program.<BR>
<BR>
The meeting will be held at the University of Florida TREEO Center on April
18th at 8am. For further information, contact SEBC executive director Judy
Foster at 813-725-8202.<BR>
<BR>
<I>--Florida Environments Publisher Dave Newport is a member of the SEBC
interim Board of Directors.</I><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor213611"></A><BR>
<HR><A HREF="../News/statenews.html">Return to State News Cover Page</A>
| <A HREF="FlaEnewsMonthMarch96.html">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR>
<H3><A HREF="#anchor213611">Session opens with a spotlight on the environment
</A></H3>
<BR>
Lawrence E. Sellers &amp;<BR>
Larry Curtin, contributing columnists<BR>
<BR>
<I>This report is contributed by the environmental law specialty group at
the law firm of Holland &amp; Knight. Messrs. Curtin and Sellers are partners
in the firm's Tallahassee office.<BR>
</I><BR>
TALLAHASSEE--Legislators continued to prepare for the 1996 Regular Session
by holding another two rounds of interim committee meetings last month.
Committees in both houses are next scheduled to meet during the weeks of
February 5 and 19. The 60-day regular legislative session opens on March
5. The environmental agenda continues to develop. Here is an update on some
of the issues that are currently receiving attention:<BR>
<B>Water.</B><BR>
The staff of the House Select Committee on Water Policy released a draft
bill that would address water supply policy issues in Florida. The bill,
which would establish several water allocation areas within the state where
water allocations would be made, and which would require the setting of
minimum flows and levels for water bodies throughout the state, appears
to be very controversial. The bill will continue to evolve in the coming
weeks.<BR>
DEP is also putting together a bill to address various aspects of water
policy. This bill, expected to be markedly different from the staff proposal
that has already been released, will likely be discussed at the February
6, 1996 meeting of the House Select Committee on Water Policy. DEP is in
the process of meeting with various interest groups and receiving input
on its concepts.<BR>
<B>Petroleum Cleanup Reimbursement Programs<BR>
</B>The legislation enacted in 1995 has resulted in a significant decrease
in the number of cleanups being conducted. Legislators are continuing to
look for ways to reduce costs and to insure that the large backlog of reimbursement
claims is promptly paid. [see related story]<BR>
<B>Environmental Self Audit Privilege<BR>
</B>A bill that would establish a limited privilege and immunity from certain
penalties and litigation resulting from conducting an environmental self
audit will be pursued by regulated interests during the 1996 session. Although
some form of the environmental self audit privilege has been adopted in
some 14 states nationwide, the effort to pass this legislation was unsuccessful
in 1995 and will be very controversial again during the 1996 session. Opponents
include the environmental community and the Attorney General's office. Expect
this to be a very controversial issue.<BR>
<B>Ecosystem Management<BR>
</B>Work continues at DEP on the ecosystem management concept. To date,
no legislation that would divide the state into a number of ecosystem management
areas is circulating. The pilot programs that were authorized by the 1995
legislature appear to be moving along well. It is unlikely that significant
legislation will be adopted prior to the completion of the pilot programs.<BR>
<B>Wetlands/Glitch Bill<BR>
</B>Expect a bill to correct glitches in the ERP/wetlands programs for this
session. Some modifications likely will be made to the grandfather provisions
and there may be a few other minor changes. Wholesale revisions to wetlands
regulation programs are unlikely.<BR>
<B>Wetlands/Melaleuca</B><BR>
Representative Sembler has again filed a bill that would permit the disturbance
of wetlands that are infested with a certain percentage of melaleuca without
requiring mitigation. The bill, which was proposed last session and did
not pass, would encourage the removal of this exotic species. Expect this
bill to be very controversial again this session.<BR>
<B>Environmental Equity<BR>
</B>The Environmental Equity and Justice Commission is studying whether
there is a disproportionate and cumulative concentration of environmental
hazards in communities of people of color and low-income. The Commission
is to assess how Florida may best address these inequities, if any. The
Commission was to issue a final report with recommendations by the end of
1995; however, the Commission has just begun to hold the required public
hearings, and it now seems unlikely that it will complete its work this
year. The Commission last met on December 13; additional public hearings
are now scheduled for January 29-30 (Dade County), February 7-8 (Hillsborough
County) and February 26-27 (Duval County).<BR>
<B>Recycling Goals/Grants<BR>
</B>Most counties met the 30 percent waste reduction goal by the end of
1994. Some therefore have suggested that the state should declare a victory
and use the $20-25 million now spent each year on recycling grants or other
purposes. On the other hand, other states have higher recycling goals, so
others want to increase Florida's goal to insure that the state continues
to be a leader in solid waste management. On January 10, the Senate Committee
on Natural Resources reported a bill, SB 120, that would replace the 30
percent county recycling goal with a 50 percent state goal, phase-out the
recycling grant program and use some of these funds instead for exotic plant
control.<BR>
<B>Exotic Plant Control<BR>
</B>Non-native, invasive plants are one of the greatest threats to Florida's
biodiversity. These plants include exotic aquatic plants (like Hydrilla)
and exotic upland plants (like Melaleuca). On January 24, the House Natural
Resources Committee reported a bill, PCB NR 96-03, on this subject.<BR>
<B>Preservation 2000<BR>
</B>The Florida Preservation 2000 Act was created in 1990 to provide $300
million a year to various land acquisition agencies to purchase pristine
lands. The funding program is scheduled for legislature review this year.
On January 24, the House Natural Resources Committee reported a bill, PCB
NR 96-2, on this subject.<BR>
<B>APA Reform<BR>
</B>Governor Chiles vetoed the Administrative Procedure Act reform bill
(SB 536) and appointed his own study commission to develop recommended reforms.
This commission has been meeting since October. The commission has addressed
a number of key issues, including: whether agencies should be authorized
to grant variances or waivers to agency rules; whether agencies should be
required to codify their policies through the rulemaking process, as is
presently required; whether certain presumptions should attach to proposed
or adopted agency rules; whether one agency should be allowed to rely on
another agency's policies or guidelines in taking action on a license or
permit. The next meeting of the commission is set for February 8.<BR>
<B>Rule Reduction Initiative<BR>
</B>DEP has identified a number of legislative changes it believes are necessary
in order to implement Governor Chiles' rule reduction initiative. On Wednesday,
January 24, the Senate Committee on Natural Resources voted to introduce
a proposed committee bill, PCB HR 96-10, that would allow DEP to repeal
a number of rules.<BR>
<B>Cabinet Reform<BR>
</B>On January 24, 1995, the Florida Cabinet passed a motion to establish
a Citizens Commission on Cabinet Reform, and charged the group with conducting
a review of the responsibilities and functions designated by statute for
the Governor and Cabinet sitting as a collegial body. The Commission has
met periodically over the past year and has compiled and released its final
report. The report contains 46 recommendations and contains drafts of implementing
legislation. Several of the recommendations involve environmental and land
use regulation, not all of which would result in changes. It is likely that
at least some of these recommendations will be considered during the 1996
legislative session.<BR>
<B>Marine Fisheries Commission<BR>
</B>Representative Safley has filed HB 367 which would eliminate Governor
and Cabinet approval of the Marine Fisheries Commission rules and place
the Commission in the Department of Environmental Protection. This consolidation
will draw a significant amount of attention.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor212141"></A><BR>
