| <A HREF="FlaEnewsMonthMarch96.html">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="#anchor212141">Agriculture officials delay pesticide contamination
rule</A></B><BR>
By Nanette Holland, FE Correspondent<BR>
<IMG SRC="/EZ135/Web%20Site/gif%20-%20web%20site%20files/Images/pesti.gif"
WIDTH="136" HEIGHT="117" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="1">TALLAHASSEE
-- Progress in crafting a state rule to address contamination from pesticide
mixing and loading sites has slowed because state agriculture officials
say they need to gather additional information on the extent of the problem.
<BR>
A report conducted last year by two state agencies found widespread contamination
of soils at sites used to mix and load pesticides for agricultural application.
Cleanup and maintenance of the mix/load sites were to be regulated by the
Florida Department of Environmental Protection through its proposed wellhead
protection rule. However, a compromise reached last spring shifted the regulatory
burden to the Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services. <BR>
DACS was supposed to report on its progress to the state Environmental Regulation
Commission last November, but that meeting was canceled. That report is
now slated for April or May.<BR>
In the meantime, DACS has formed a working group composed of representatives
from its agency, as well as DEP and agriculture trade organizations. That
group is developing a survey to better assess current pesticide mixing and
loading practices at farms. Golf courses, pest control companies and other
facilities that routinely handle pesticides also will be surveyed.<BR>
That survey - which likely will be distributed by the trade associations
to their memberships sometime this spring - will help officials gauge how
many pesticide applicators are using improper practices, and what the level
of risk is from those operations. <BR>
Although ERC members expressed strong concerns about the soil contamination
revealed by the joint DEP-DACS study, agriculture officials now say they
are not sure a rule is needed to address the problem.<BR>
&quot;In this climate of 'no new rules,' we have to carefully weigh whether
a rule is needed to regulate what may be a small sector of the agricultural
community,&quot; said Marion Fuller, chief of DACS' bureau of pesticides.
&quot;If the risks do warrant regulatory action, we want to make sure we're
taking advantage of what people are already doing right, and that we don't
preclude them from doing those things.&quot;<BR>
The studies conducted by the two agencies suggest that at least half of
the state's 40,000 small farms may have contaminated soils resulting from
spills of pesticides during mixing and loading into spraying equipment.
Similar contamination was found at mix/load sites on University of Florida
Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences' research centers throughout
the state.<BR>
Some of the contamination is severe enough to trigger formal hazardous waste
cleanups.<BR>
Agricultural representatives contend that the worst contamination generally
results from the historic use of pesticides such as DDT and toxaphene that
have been banned for decades.<BR>
But DEP program administrator David Vogel said that a &quot;healthy percentage&quot;
of the contamination detected in the study comes from currently used pesticides.<BR>
&quot;We wouldn't be seeking to draft a rule asking them to change their
practices if the only problem was with pesticides that are no longer being
used,&quot; he said.<BR>
Any rule that is developed likely will include flexibility - another tenet
of current government philosophies. That flexibility, Vogel said, may involve
incentives allowing farm operators with minor soil contamination to obtain
a general permit with less stringent cleanup requirements. The rule also
could take into account the varying potential for contamination, depending
on soil types. For instance, Vogel said, pesticides spills are less likely
to persist in the sandy soils along the Highlands Ridge than they are in
organic muck.<BR>
&quot;We need to come up with a management approach that is both affordable
and makes environmental sense. We need to have a big, big list of options
for people,&quot; said Charlie Matthews of the Florida Fruit and Vegetable
Association.<BR>
Agriculture representatives said they began educating their members about
the potential hazards of pesticide mix/load sites long before the state
study clarified the problem. Most growers now are more careful about their
pesticide handling practices, they said, and those changes have been fueled
not only by environmental concerns, but also by the high cost of the chemicals
and the potential for environmental audits when farmlands are sold.<BR>
Instead of a single mixing and loading area, said Pat Cockrell of the Florida
Farm Bureau, many farmers now mix chemicals in their fields to avoid a concentrated
area of contamination, and use nurse tanks to dilute the chemicals with
water.<BR>
&quot;We feel like we're seeing a real behavioral change in people and we'd
hate to see a regulation come about that creates more problems than it's
worth,&quot; he said.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor210932"></A><BR>
<HR><A HREF="../News/statenews.html">Return to State News Cover Page</A>
| <A HREF="FlaEnewsMonthMarch96.html">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="#anchor210932">No liability exemptions (yet!) for dry cleaners
in Dade County</A></B><BR>
by Matt Coglianese<BR>
<BR>
With the establishment of the state's Dry Cleaning Solvent Program, business
owners who believe they are eligible for the program may think their operations
are now exempt from punitive enforcement actions. This is not the case.<BR>
<BR>
Dade county's DERM has continued its regulatory enforcement because the
agency believes that, until rules to determine program eligib ility are
in place, no business is necessarily qualified for a liability exemption.<BR>
<BR>
Though the Court upheld DERM's position in a suit filed by the Neighborhood
Cleaner's Association, a more recent Court decision has m uddied the waters.<BR>
<BR>
The case involves a Dade County complaint against dry cleaners and landowners
it claimed were responsible for perc contamination in the Suniland area.
The County sought injunctive relief requiring the defendants to properly
assess and remediate the property. The C ounty also wanted payment for costs
of installing and connecting drinking water mains to residences, as well
as civil penalties, admi nistrative costs and investigative expenses.<BR>
<BR>
The State Court's decision in this case was more favorable to the defendants.
The Court stayed the action until April 3, 1996 to all ow DEP to set eligibility
rules and determine which businesses qualify. If, by April 3, the defendants
submit to the Court a declara tion of eligibility or documentation demonstrating
entitlement to protection of the voluntary cleanup immunity provision, the
case wi ll be dismissed with prejudice.<BR>
<BR>
As did it in the Neighborhood Cleaners Association case, the Court looked
at the immunity provisions of the statute, and found that a ll enforcement
actions, including actions to compel assessment and cleanup and claims for
civil penalties, attorneys fees and costs, are prohibited, provided the
party is eligible under the Dry Cleaning Act. The Court also held that the
County was precluded from re covering the costs of installing the public
water system. <BR>
<BR>
The defendants' motions to dismiss the complaint were based on the immunity
provisions of Section 376.3078(3), Florida Statutes. The property owners
argued further that the 1995 amendments to the Dry cleaning Solvent Cleanup
Program went even further by providing p rotection for real property owners
where contamination was due to gross negligence which occurred prior to
January 1, 1990. Finally, the defendants argued that Section 3765.3078(9)
precluded a suit against parties which were actively conducting remediation,
which i s the case with several of the Suniland defendants.<BR>
<BR>
Business as Usual<BR>
<BR>
So, have DERM's enforcement efforts against dry cleaners now come to a grinding
halt as a result of the Court's order? Not at all.<BR>
<BR>
First of all, the Court specifically stated that Dade County could re-plead
its complaint to pursue a claim for on-site containment o f dry cleaning
solvents. And that is precisely what the County intends to do, according
to Tom Robertson, assistant county attorney, and Bob Johns, Chief of DERM's
Hazardous Waste Section.<BR>
<BR>
Secondly, although the Court's decision may prohibit DERM from taking action
against parties involved with the contamination at Sunil and, it does not
affect DERM's efforts with other dry cleaners. According to Bob Johns, it
is still &quot;business as usual&quot; at DERM. If DERM finds a problem,
it will issue a Notice of Violation and require some type of action at a
site. Mr. Johns indicated that DERM has almost completed its sampling at
all active dry cleaners in Dade County. If the results indicate a groundwater
violation, that f acility will get a Notice of Violation.<BR>
<BR>
DERM's has two legitimate concerns with the Dry Cleaners Cleanup program:
the delays in program startup and underfunding that could bog down program
function and clean-ups. DERM believes that the program will probably have
to be &quot;fixed&quot; at some point in the initia l year and adequate
funds will not be directed to cleanup of sites anytime soon. Also, DERM
is concerned about legislative attempts to gut the program this term, though
the chance of success is considered remote. In the meantime, contaminated
sites continue to exi st, and some have off-site migration of problematic
contaminants. So, DERM's philosophy has been that while the program is developin
g, DERM will continue to enforce against dry cleaners on a case by case
basis in an attempt to contain and reduce groundwater contami nation.<BR>
<BR>
According to Mr. Johns, DERM's philosophy has been vindicated. At one of
the Suniland locations, the groundwater treatment system ha s been shut
down because contamination levels in groundwater has been reduced below
detection limits. DERM says that demonstrates th at if you catch it quickly,
you can clean up groundwater contamination.<BR>
<BR>
The bottom line is that, unless DERM is told to do otherwise, as it was
in the Suniland case, it will continue to take action against specific dry
cleaners, at least until the site is declared eligible for the cleanup program.
Because the program is currently underf unded, DERM may be correct in its
belief that an eligibility determination may not even result in cleanup
of a site, but DERM has con ceded that official program eligibility precludes
enforcement. <BR>
<BR>
The good news is that eligibility determinations may be a little bit closer.
The new Dry cleaning Solvent Cleanup Program Rule (Rule 62-781, Florida
Administrative Code) was published in the Florida Administrative Weekly
on December 22, 1995. The word at DEP is tha t the rule will be adopted
in February 1996. Once it is adopted, DEP will begin accepting applications
to the program. Under the ru le, the Department has 120 days to make an
eligibility determination once the application is complete.<BR>
<BR>
