ly96/071196.html">7-11-96</A>| <A HREF="../July96/071596.html">7-15-96</A> | <A HREF="../July96/071696.html">7-16-96</A>| <A HREF="../July96/071796.html">7-17-96</A> | <A HREF="../July96/071896.html">7-18-96</A>| <A HREF="../July96/071996.html">7-19-96</A> | <A HREF="../July96/072296.html">7-22-96</A>| <A HREF="../July96/072396.html">7-23-96</A> | <A HREF="../July96/072596.html">7-25-96</A>| <A HREF="../July96/072696.html">7-26-96</A> | <A HREF="../July96/072996.html">7-29-96</A>| <A HREF="../July96/073096.html">7-30-96</A> | <A HREF="../July96/073196.html">7-31-96</A>| </UL><B>Monthly news archives</B> <A NAME="anchor1151438"></A><UL>  <LI><A HREF="../Jan96/FloridaEnewsMonthJan96.html">January 1996</A> |<A HREF="../Feb96/FlaEnewsMonthFeb96.html">February 1996</A> | <A HREF="../Mar96/FlaEnewsMonthMarch96.html">March,April, May 1996</A> | <A HREF="FlaEnewsMonthJune96.html">June, July 1996</A></UL><A NAME="anchor244958"></A><BR><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1151438">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor244958">Climate changes could affect insurance rates</A></H3><BR>By NANETTE HOLLAND/Correspondent<BR><BR><BR>LONGBOAT KEY -- Jeremy Leggett is as passionate about his cause as a reformedsmoker is about cigarettes. In Leggett's case, the comparison is tingedwith irony, for his mission is reducing global dependence on oil, an industrythat once helped support him. But unlike many environmental activists, Leggetthasn't turned his back on the corporate world. They are his primary audience.As director of Greenpeace International's solar energy campaign, Leggett,42, uses his pin-striped image and academic credentials to convince theinsurance and banking executives that global warming is a real threat thatcould bankrupt their industries. And they're starting to listen. <BR><BR>So far, 60 European and Asian insurance companies-- including industry giantssuch as Swiss Re, General Accident and Sumitomo Marine and Fire -- havesigned a United Nations accord pledging to consider the effects of climatechange and other environmental problems in their business practices. NoAmerican insurers or banks have yet signed the pact, although Leggett strucka chord last month with Florida's top insurance regulator. Joining Leggettin speaking at a Sarasota conference last month on climate change and thefinancial sector, Insurance Commission Bill Nelson said the devastationcaused by Hurricane Andrew serves as a warning of the type of catastrophesthat global warming and associated sea level rise might bring. He said insurancecompanies in Florida can't afford to ignore scientific warnings about climatechange any longer. Florida, with half the nation's $2 trillion in coastalproperty value, &quot;is the most vulnerable of all the 50 states to thepotential impacts of climate change,&quot; Nelson said. &quot;Our statewould suffer relentless heat waves, beaches being submerged by rising seas,contaminated drinking water and more severe and damaging hurricanes. Obviously,the insurance industry has a big stake in all this.&quot; Andrew was themost costly natural disaster in modern history, resulting in insurance lossesof $17 billion. Insurance claims filed after the storm were so astronomicalthat several companies went bankrupt and others pulled out of the home insurancemarket in Florida altogether. Although Nelson has led the fight to preventinsurance companies from abandoning Florida homeowners, he acknowledgedthat Andrew may be a sign of things to come and that insurance companiesshould take global warning into account when assessing risk. He said hewould share Leggett's information, and the results of an international panelof scientists convened last fall by the U.N., with the state's top insurers,including Allstate and State Farm. <BR><BR>&quot;I can guarantee you that I will be sharing this information with theirvery top executives,&quot; he said. After years of bickering over the magnitudeand effects of climate change -- and despite some scientists' assertionsthat it is merely a figment of their colleagues over-active imaginations-- the U.N. panel offered the strongest consensus to date that global warmingis indeed occurring. The panel concluded that &quot;the balance of evidencesuggests a discernible human influence on global climate.&quot; Scientistsserving on the panel even went so far as to predict the extent of climatechange. Those estimates project that global temperatures will rise anywherefrom 1 to 3.5 degrees Celsius, or 2 to 6 degrees Fahrenheit, in the nextcentury. That could leave Dallas sweltering in 78 days of 100-degree heat,compared with the 20 days it now experiences. In fact, 1995 was the warmestyear worldwide since record-keeping began 130 years ago, according to areport just issued by the Washington, D.C.-based Worldwatch Institute. TheU.N. panel also predicted that sea level will rise by as much as 55 centimeters,or nearly 22 inches, in the next 100 years. Among the results of this doublewhammy: Droughts will become more frequent in some places, while floodswill increase in others. Tropical storms and other extreme weather eventswill become more common, in fact, some researchers say, the bitterly coldweather that plagued the U.S. Northeast this year may be related to globalwarming, since changes in ocean currents fueled by climate change are coolingwaters in the North Atlantic as they are heating waters in other oceans.Beach erosion will accelerate and wetlands throughout the world will beinundated as seas rise. If the wetlands are prevented from retreating landwardby human developments such as coastal resorts and power plants, vast nurseryareas for fish will be lost. A 55 centimeter sea level rise in Louisiana,for instance, would submerge half the state's existing coastline. Entireecosystems that are attuned to specific climatic requirements may vanish.This is especially true for forests, according to U.S. Environmental ProtectionAgency senior scientist Cory Berish. Dramatic changes are predicted forthe forests along the Mississippi River and the southern U.S. as a resultof higher temperatures that allow tropical diseases and pests to invade.Salt water intrusion into groundwater supplies may increase, contaminatingirrigation and drinking water. <BR><BR>The source of these potential calamities are so-called &quot;greenhousegases&quot; such as carbon dioxide that trap heat escaping from the earth'satmosphere. The burning of fossil fuels is the largest source of these gases.&quot;We have the warmest global temperatures coming that have been seenon earth in the last 100,000 years. Never before in the history of the globehave we had billions and billions of people using fossil fuels and puttinggases into the atmosphere,&quot; Berish said. &quot;This is a tremendouslylarge experiment.&quot; Leggett is employing a distinctly different approachto the problem from most environmental activists. He is targeting top executivesof the banking and insurance companies, which bankroll most residentialand industrial development in the world, and which stand to lose the mostif those investments are lost or devalued by the ripple effects of climatechange . An Oxford graduate with a Ph.D. in earth sciences and a formerprofessor at London's Imperial College of Science and Technology, Leggettonce jetted around the world as an oil industry consultant. But he saysthe mounting evidence linking climate change with fossil fuel combustionchanged his outlook. He joined Greenpeace in 1989, providing the group witha credible mainstream advocate for their solar energy campaign. Althoughmany industry executives view Greenpeace as radical fringe organization,Leggett and his mountain of statistics has earned their respect. &quot;Wehave to be concerned and we most recognize that the financial markets willbe affected by climate change,&quot; said Sven Hansen, vice president ofthe Union Bank of Switzerland. By &quot;following the money,&quot; Leggettis gaining a warmer reception, and better results, for his anti-fossil fuelmission than he likely would have found simply by lobbying governments ororganizing environmentalists. &quot;These private organizations, if theychoose to become involved, can have an enormous influence in solving theproblem,&quot; he said. &quot;Just in America, more than half the countryis owned by banks, insurance companies and pension funds.&quot; In the lastdecade, natural catastrophes have far exceeded all other categories of insurancelosses. Insurance industry payouts for weather-related damage have reached$48 billion so far in the 1990's, compared with $16 billion for all of the1980's. According to the Worldwatch Institute report, the world's grainharvest in 1995 was the smallest since 1988 and grain reserves were at anall-time low. <BR>Nelson's acknowledgment that worldwide climatic patterns are shifting representsan important turning point for Greenpeace's American campaign, Leggett added.So do alternative energy initiatives like the solar energy technology nowbeing developed by Amoco-Enron. But despite the fact that the U.S. contributesmore greenhouse gases than any other nation, Leggett admits that findingconverts in America is tough. &quot;In Europe, climate change is acceptedby and large as a great threat, but in America the influence of what wecall the &quot;Carbon Club&quot; -- the oil industries and their lobbyists--is much more powerful and it's difficult to make headway,&quot; he said.<BR>Even attempts to promote energy conservation with existing fuels are beingstalled. In Florida, for instance, state legislators this year amended the1980 Florida Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act to exempt most of thestate's utility companies from establishing conservation goals.<BR><BR><BR><BR><A NAME="anchor1559044"></A><BR><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1151438">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor1559044">DEP resists NOx ruling's affect on air regulations</A></H3>by Mitchell Gibbs, News Editor<BR><BR>THE MIND SET of regulatory agencies is to box pollutants as either a waterproblem or an air problem, with little recognition that those boxes couldspill into one another. But a growing body of evidence is showing that thewell-studied air pollutant NOx is a major source of nitrate pollution incoastal waters. <BR>The issue seemed to have broken that regulatory barrier in a recent landmarkdecision by Florida's Governor and Cabinet. Yet, a top Department of EnvironmentalProtection official said that the agency still has no intention of regulatingNOx based on its threat to water.<BR>April 23, the Governor and Cabinet, acting as the Siting Board, set a legalprecedent when it turned down Florida Power and Light's application to burnthe tar-based fuel Orimulsion at its Manatee Plant. That decision hingedlargely on the fact that FP&amp;L's plans included an 85 percent increasein NOx emissions. <BR>But Howard Rhodes, the DEP's Director of Air Resources Management, toldFE that the decision of the Siting Board will have no effect on DEP actions.<BR>That response surprised attorney Tom Reese, whose arguments led to the SitingBoard's decision.<BR>&quot;The (Siting Board ruling) is equivalent to a final order of the Departmentof Environmental Protection,&quot; Reese said. &quot;So, DEP should beginto be consistent with (that ruling).&quot; <BR>Rhodes sees no such mandate.<BR>&quot;I think there is validity to the fact that NOx comes out of the air,&quot;he said, &quot;(But) there is a more tenuous connection between what goesup comes down and what the impact is. ... It's hard as the devil to tracesources.&quot;<BR>Rhodes said that until scientists could definitively link the NOx comingout of a smokestack with the nitrate in a body of water, the DEP would sittight. &quot;I don't think the science is there, yet,&quot; Rhodes added.<BR>The sky IS falling<BR>In some ways, Rhodes is correct. NOx is released into the air by humansthrough the burning of fossil fuels (Power plants and cars vie for the topspot in nationwide NOx releases). But once in the air, a NOx molecule maytravel hundreds of miles and go through numerous chemical reactions beforeultimately falling back to earth as nitrate (in the form of nitric acid).<BR>While several different studies of major waterways along the east coastof the U.S. have found that NOx emissions account for 10 to 40 percent ofthe nitrogen go going into the water, parceling out the blame has been aneglected, and until now, an unneeded task.<BR>Yet, according to statistics compiled by the Natural Resources Defense Council,Florida's top 20 polluting power plants emitted 259,035 tons of NOx lastyear. Since Florida's total yearly output of NOx from all direct human sourcesis about 766,000 tons, wouldn't reducing power-plant outputs lower coastalnitrogen loading? <BR>&quot;Clearly, It's a good idea to reduce nitrogen loading,&quot; Rhodessaid paradoxically. &quot;It's (already) had a dramatic impact on (Tampa)Bay.&quot;<BR>The improvements in Tampa Bay have been obvious. The Tampa Bay NationalEstuary Program (the NEP) reports that reductions in the levels of nitratesin sewage effluent over the past 20 years have resulted in the regenerationof 4,000 acres of sea grasses in the bay, and water clarity has markedlyimproved. <BR>The improved water treatment has dropped sewage's contribution to TampaBay's nitrogen inputs from 40 percent in the 1970's to 8 percent now. Meanwhile,the NEP estimates that NOx accounts for 28 percent of the bay's nitrogen.<BR>But nitrogen isn't just a problem in Tampa Bay. The nutrient has been implicatedas a factor in the rapid deterioration of Florida Bay, and is thought tobe a major contributor to the seasonal blooms of algae that lead to redtide outbreaks.<BR>That NOx in the air is a major source of nitrate pollution in the wateris not a far-fetched or even new theory. The problem is simply that thepollution to water is not as direct. While it is easy to determine thata wastewater treatment plant is discharging nitrate-rich water into a bay,and logical to deduce that fertilizers and animal wastes dissolved in runofflend to nitrate pollution, it is harder to hammer down the point that NOxreleased into the air undergoes chemical reactions and is redeposited onthe earth's surface as nitrate.<BR>Yet, the 1978 text, &quot;Nitrates: An Environmental Assessment&quot; (publishedby the National Academy of Science) laid the facts out plainly: &quot;Humanactivity adds NO to the troposphere principally by combustion ... UltimatelyNO is converted to nitrogen dioxide, nitric acid, and nitrate aerosols bya complex series of photochemical reactions; the nitrate is removed fromthe troposphere by rainfall and dry fallout.&quot;<BR>Along with phosphorous, nitrogen is a primary limiting nutrient for mostalgae. That means that algal growth is kept in check as long as these nutrientsare not overly abundant. Along coasts and in estuaries, nitrogen is themore important limiting nutrient. Thus, nationwide, the impacts of nitratesfrom NOx emissions to economically valuable estuaries are a concern.<BR>In fact, the water body most heavily researched for NOx effects is probablyChesapeake Bay. As part of several federally-funded programs, researchershave extensively modeled NOx outputs that load nitrogen into the bay. AMay 6 article in the Bureau of National Affairs' Daily Environment Reportreported that Environmental Protection Agency officials connected with ChesapeakeBay research were actively seeking ways of forcing reductions in NOx emissions.<BR>The Chesapeake Bay research also reveals that the NOx problem extends beyondstate borders. Models of the &quot;airshed&quot; for the bay indicate thatits area is 5.5 times larger than the bay's watershed, and covers most ofthe northern United States east of the Mississippi River. Thus, NOx emissionsfrom the heavily industrialized Midwestern states can wind up in ChesapeakeBay.<BR>The extent of Florida's &quot;airshed&quot; is much less clear. The DEP'sRhodes said that modeling it would be a multimillion dollar task, thoughhe did not believe the state was &quot;drastically impacted by externalsources.&quot;<BR>No NOx is good NOx<BR>Other sources in the DEP said that, given the possibilities for long-rangetransport of NOx, the most effective regulation of emissions is likely tocome from federal agencies. <BR>Tom Seal, a DEP biologist and geologist with the Surface Water Improvementprogram, has seen first-hand the destruction of forests in the Adirondackmountains as a result of acid rain that was generated far away.<BR>&quot;There's no way we can control air mass systems from Alabama and WestGeorgia,&quot; Seal said. &quot;That's why we have to have federal control.The Clean Air Act is the best solution to control NOx deposition.&quot;<BR>Still, Tom Reese is baffled by the DEP's attitude toward the Siting Boardruling.<BR>&quot;Basically the ruling came down to FP&amp;L saying the NOx inputs werenot going to be biologically significant, but the Tampa Bay people (regulators)are saying 'We've already got too much nitrogen in Tampa Bay and we're tryingto bring it into compliance. If (FP&amp;L is) going to dump 20 tons morenitrogen in, then that's just 20 tons more we've got to get out.&quot;<BR>In other words, the Siting Board decided that it doesn't matter how muchpower plant NOx winds up as nitrate in Tampa Bay, any additional nitrateis too much.<BR>&quot;Howard (Rhodes) doesn't want to implement it (the Siting Board's decision)because it's going to have an impact.&quot; Reese said. &quot;(But) he cannotignore the interpretation that's on the books.&quot; <BR>Rhodes' logic seems to be similar to the utility-industry position citedin the Bureau of National Affairs report: that NOx only accounts for roughly25 percent of nitrogen loading, and power plants are only a third of that,so regulating the plants won't result in much improvement.<BR>&quot;If you control one (NOx source) does it solve the problem?&quot; Rhodesasked. <BR>But in economic terms, tightening rules on the power plants could be thesmart course. According to figures by the Tampa Bay National Estuary Program,NOx reduction equipment for some area plants (&quot;wet bottom&quot; or&quot;cyclone&quot; group 2 boilers) would result in a cost of $2,000 to$4,500 per ton of NOx. In contrast, the NEP estimates that more sophisticatedemission controls on automobiles, coupled with the cost of reformulatedfuel, would cost $30,000 per ton of NOx saved. <BR>However, Rhodes gave no indication that DEP is willing to budge from itsstance. The likely outcome then, said Reese, will be more law suits. Reesesaid the next round is likely to be over TECO's Tampa Bay NOx outputs, orpossibly the emissions from the proposed Piney Point Phosphate plant inManatee County. Given the precedent, DEP seems destined to have anotherof its decisions hammered. Reese did suggest one way the outcome could bealtered: <BR>&quot;Maybe Howard should run for governor if he doesn't like it.&quot;<BR><A NAME="anchor1562630"></A><BR><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1151438">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor1562630">Lot's of enviro bills pass, await Governor'spen</A></H3>by Lawrence E. Sellers and Lawrence N. Curtin, columnists<BR><BR><BR>THE FLORIDA Legislature concluded its 1996 Regular Session on May 3. Duringthe 60-day session, the Legislature considered a number of bills affectingFlorida's environment. Here's a brief summary of the key measures that passed.Next month we'll look at some of the failed bills that are likely to beseen again. (Remember: &quot;S&quot; refers to Senate bill, and &quot;H&quot;refers to House bill.)<BR>WATER<BR>Water Supply. Combined H 2385 and H 2399 are the only water bills to comeout of the session. This legislation applies to Pasco, Pinellas, and HillsboroughCounties within the Southwest Florida Water Management District (SWFWMD).Under the bill, SWFWMD will submit to the Department of Environmental Protection(DEP) by July 1, 1996 a list of water bodies for the establishment of minimumflows and levels. The levels must actually be established by October 1,1997. The list development process is not subject to an administrative hearing.The legislation subjects the methodology for establishing minimum flowsand levels to scientific peer review prior to implementation. No additionalfunds are given to the West Coast Regional Water Supply Authority, but theAuthority is directed to do a study to report on utilization of increasedfunding is that funding is provided. The Governor's office will approveor disapprove the budgets of each of the five water management districts.<BR>Water Policy/Wetlands/ERP Glitch. H 1887 is the so-called wetlands glitchbill. The bill clarifies the application of grandfather provisions for wetlandspermitting within the Northwest Florida Water Management District so thatthose provisions are the same as in the rest of the state. An exemptionfrom environmental resource permitting for already permitted projects ismodified to allow a two-year extension. Permit processing provisions thatwere inadvertently repealed when the dredge and fill and the managementand storage of surface water programs were combined are restored. The billalso provides a clarification of the applicability of grandfather provisionsfor certain areas subject to petitions for jurisdictional declaratory statements.<BR>Mitigation Banking. H 2241 addresses issues concerning wetlands mitigationand mitigation banking. The legislation amplifies on what is acceptablemitigation by specifically including on-site mitigation, off-site mitigation,off-site regional mitigation, and the purchase of credits from mitigationbanks. DEP and the water management districts are authorized to accept thedonation of money as mitigation in certain cases. Criteria for establishingmitigation banks will apply equally to public and private entities, withexceptions relating to financial responsibility and provisions relatingto appropriate legal interests in the mitigation banks. Requirements forobtaining permits for operation of mitigation banks are specified.<BR>Mangroves. S 508 amends the 1995 law to impose more stringent requirementsfor trimming mangroves. Among other things, the bill provides that no mangrovesmay be cut lower than six feet under an exemption or general permit, thatmangroves over 16 feet must be cut in stages, and that a permit is requiredto trim mangroves more than 50 feet into the water. The bill also providesgreater protection for red mangroves.<BR>Lake Apopka. S 2954 provides approximately $20 million for the acquisitionof agricultural lands adjacent to Lake Apopka. The bill also requires theSt. Johns River Water Management District to adopt a rule establishing aphosphorous criterion for Lake Apopka and certain other waters.<BR>Coastal Construction. H 2241 provides an exemption from certain design andsiting criteria for construction located seaward of an established coastalconstruction control line and landward of existing armoring under certainconditions. The bill also is designed to streamline the permitting processfor certain coastal construction activities located seaward of an establishedcoastal construction control line.<BR>Boating Safety. Boating safety has been extremely controversial over a numberof years, and efforts to regulate boat operators have largely been unsuccessful.This will change somewhat with the adoption of S 336. Persons 16 years ofage and under would not be permitted to operate a vessel of 10 horsepoweror more unless they have completed an approved boating education course,an equivalency exam, or received a temporary certificate. Persona 21 yearsof age and younger will be subject to these restrictions beginning October1, 2001. DEP is authorized to appoint marinas, liveries and other personsto act as the agent to administer the course and give equivalency exams.<BR>TANKS<BR>Petroleum Cleanup Reimbursement Program. Legislation enacted in 1995 didnot prove successful in balancing the need to continue to provide for thecleanup of contaminated sites with the need to make the program financiallysound and economically efficient. H 1127 provides for the financing of thebacklog, a new petroleum cleanup participation program, a new voluntarycleanup program, and the incorporation of risk-based corrective action (RBCA)principles in establishing cleanup criteria. The new legislation also allowsthe state to continue to spend between $60-70 million a year to continuecleaning up new sites, subject to procedures designed to ensure that theworst sited are cleaned up first.<BR>SOLID AND HAZARDOUS WASTE<BR>C&amp;D Debris Landfills. H 1905 establishes more stringent standards forconstruction and demolition debris landfills. Most of these landfills nowwill be required to obtain an individual (rather than a general) permit,and they will be required to install groundwater monitoring wells. Theyalso may be required to install liners and leachate collection systems,in certain cases.<BR>Cattle Dipping Vats. S 956 provides private landowners with immunity forthe cleanup of contamination associated with the historic operation of cattledipping vats.<BR>Hazardous Materials Fees. H 1271 continues the fee mechanism used to implementthe Florida Hazardous Materials Emergency Response and Community Right toKnow Act of 1988. This act was adopted in response to federal requirementsto establish hazardous materials emergency planning processes and to collectinformation from facilities subject to the federal legislation. Severalproposals dealing with this program were considered during the session.These ranges from abolishing the program entirely, to cutting the fees andappropriations associated with it. Regulated interests, however, believethat the program is necessary and were able to convince the Legislatureto continue the fees.<BR>Biomedical Waste. H153 transfers the oversight of off-site biomedical wastetransportation, storage and treatment to DHRS. DEP retains authority overthe permitting of incinerators that process biomedical waste. The bill alsoensures that all forms of biomedical waste treatment, including mobile treatmentunits, are subject to regulation.<BR>AIR<BR>Ozone. H 1887 contains a provision that prohibits the DEP from enteringinto interagency agreements relating to the transport of ozone precursorpollutants or changing its rules for these pollutants based on recommendationsfrom the Ozone Transport Assessment Group or similar organization withoutspecific legislative approval.<BR>Title V Permits. H 1887 provides that for pulp and paper mills, chemicalfacilities and sugar processing plants, issuance of the Title V operatingpermit will not be subject to delegation to local governments. This provisionwas included in the original legislation implementing the Title V operatingpermit program, but was set to expire in 1997. The expiration date is deleted.<BR>GROWTH MANAGEMENT<BR>Growth Management. Growth management was an issue that received a substantialamount of attention during the session. The Legislature passed H 2705 containingsignificant growth management legislation. The bill repeals much of thecomprehensive planning Intergovernmental Coordination Element (ICE) programthat required local governments to identify the impacts of developmentswithin their boundaries and could have required them to propose mitigation.The bill continues the Development of Regional Impact (DRI) program, whichwas scheduled to expire in 1999. The bill also addresses comprehensive planamendments related to DRIs and quality developments.<BR>MISCELLANEOUS<BR>Preservation 2000. S 770 reenacts the funding for this land acquisitionprogram. The bill makes substantial revisions to the rails to trails programto allow the use of P2000 funds for greenway purchases. The bill also encouragesthe water management districts and DEP to explore alternatives to fee simpleacquisition of property.<BR>Access to Public Officials. Last year, the Legislature enacted a law toaddress the decision in the Jennings case by describing those circumstancesunder which persons mat have ex parte contacts with public officials. S524 amends this law to provide for additional access to public officialsin quasi-judicial proceedings of local government land use matters.<BR>ERC Confirmations. The Environmental Regulation Commission serves as thestandard-setting head of the DEP. The Commission is comprised of seven laypersons appointed by the Governor. The appointments are subject to confirmationby the Senate. The Senate confirmed five of the seven appointments, buttemporarily deferred action on the nomination of Chairman Dick Batchelor.(Another appointee resigned.) The Governor may nominate Chairman Batchelorfor another year, and he is expected to do so.<BR>DEP Reorganization. Late in the legislative session, language surfaced intwo pieces of legislation that, if implemented, will have a dramatic impacton the way that environmental resource permitting is handled by the DEP.The first provision is included in the appropriation proviso language forspecific DEP appropriations. This required DEP to report by January 1, 1997on plans for a reorganization and to develop draft legislation necessaryto implement the changes. Additionally, DEP is directed to transfer theEnvironmental Resources Division permitting functions to the district offices.S 38, initially dealing with the repeal of a number of DEP trust funds,also touches on this issue by directing the transition of positions involvedin permit processing from the Environmental Resources Division to the districtoffices beginning July 1, 1996. If fully implemented, this will result inthe elimination of the Environmental Resources Division. It has been controversialand it is unclear what action the Governor will take.<BR>That's a brief summary of what passed. Check this space in the next issuefor a brief report on those bills that died.<BR>For copies of House bills, call 904-488-7475. For copies of Senate bills,call 904-487-5285. Bills also are available via the internet at http://www.scri.fsu.edu/fla-leg/.<BR><A NAME="anchor1575455"></A><BR><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1151438">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR><H3><A HREF="#anchor1575455">FE Editorial: Wetherell should resign</A></H3><BR>THIS IS NOT AN EDITORIAL WE write lightly. Over the years, we have observed<BR>the pressures and divergent forces that act upon environmental regulators<BR>and tried, with varying degrees of success, to cut them some slack.<BR>But of late, too many decisions have been made at the highest level of the<BR>state's top regulatory agency that betray an agenda not consistent with<BR>sound environmental protection. The latest decision seals the deal.<BR>At issue is why the leadership at the Department of Environmental<BR>Protection orchestrated the fragmentation of the Environmental Resources<BR>Permit program?<BR>The story goes like this:<BR>In the waning hours of the legislative session, DEP's leaders ghosted an<BR>amendment that eliminates the 180-person Tallahassee-based ERP divisionby<BR>moving rank-and-file permit staff out to DEP's district offices and laying<BR>off top staffers.<BR>This is the same ERP program that DEP fought so hard to protect only months<BR>ago. DEP Secretary Ginger Wetherell last Fall proudly unveiled new ERP<BR>program elements that &quot;provide applicants with one location to receive<BR>their permit reviews, and increases agency accountability and efficiency<BR>without loss of environmental protection.&quot;<BR>Now, ERP division chief Jeremy Craft wonders how decentralization will<BR>erode permit quality given that his staff is in a state of &quot;manageable<BR>hysteria.&quot;<BR>Craft, who will be trying to hold things together while they are literally<BR>coming apart, says the whole staff &quot;is pretty depressed.&quot;<BR>The party line-one that even DEP loyalist Craft espouses-is that a $4<BR>million shortfall in ERP revenues was leveraged against the Department by<BR>big bad Senators who threatened outright elimination of the ERP this year.<BR>So, Ginger &quot;Joan of Arc&quot; Wetherell cut the best deal she could,staving off<BR>the bad guys and giving the Department a &quot;year in which to make rational<BR>choices,&quot; according to Craft.<BR>Trouble is, none of the big bad politicians knew anything about this<BR>gambit. The usual suspects like Senators Diaz-Balart and Latvala were<BR>clueless about this maneuver until reporters started calling them. And<BR>there's no record of any of these kinds of discussions during any committee<BR>meeting.<BR>Senate Natural Resources chairman Rick Dantzler, whose committee blindly<BR>sponsored the amendment late on the session's last night, said &quot;that'sa<BR>big policy decision that should not be made on the last night of the<BR>session.&quot; We agree.<BR>DEP's leadership says it all came out of nowhere-&quot;it happened verylate<BR>Friday night,&quot; Deputy Secretary Kirby Green told the St. PetersburgTimes.<BR>That's just not the case.<BR>DEP leaders were laying the groundwork for this maneuver at least one month<BR>before the end of the session, according to internal memos obtained by<BR>Florida Environments [see related story, page 8].<BR>Moreover, if big bad politicians were trying to push the Department around,<BR>why didn't DEP enlist the Governor in their defense? Nobody in the<BR>Governor's office knew about it, his staff confirms. And Governor Chiles<BR>wants to know why. &quot;Before it's over, we will know what happened andwhy,&quot;<BR>Chiles top enviro advisor said.<BR>Indeed, why gut the ERP program?<BR>It was clearly a policy decision reached by Wetherell and her Praetorian<BR>Guard: Kirby Green, Dale Patchett, and Nevin Smith. Wetherell's memo to<BR>staff on the matter cites the purported revenue shortfall but then states<BR>&quot;we can no longer afford [emphasis added] to transfer money to coverthe<BR>permit fee deficit.&quot;<BR>That's an important admission because it confirms DEP's leaders made a<BR>voluntary choice not to fund the program. They weren't leveraged into it,<BR>they wanted it that way. It got prioritized out. They couldn't afford it.<BR>Why? Is it some sort of internal power play? We know that Craft is on the<BR>outs with some of Wetherell's Praetorian Guard. But would top staffers put<BR>turf ahead of environmental protection? That would be a pity.<BR>In the end, why it happened is less important than the fact it happenedat all.<BR>For whatever reason, Wetherell made a unilateral decision that's fraught<BR>with monumental ramifications, back doored it through the Legislature, kept<BR>her boss out of the loop, and then spun a story that clouds the issue. No<BR>wonder Chiles is said to be livid. We all should be.<BR>This is not how to run the state's environmental protection agency. At<BR>worst, this is emblematic of a disdain for the environment and its<BR>protectors, smacks of an arrogance of power and is a malicious abuse of<BR>process. At best, it was just gross incompetence.<BR>Either way, Florida's environment needs better.<BR>So, we don't write these words without serious consideration and objective<BR>review of both perspectives; however, we feel it is now time for Virginia<BR>Wetherell to resign as Secretary of Florida's Department of Environmental<BR>Protection. Florida's environment clearly needs more than she can give.<BR><BR><BR><HR><A HREF="http://www.enviroworld.com/statenews.html">Return to StateNews Cover Page</A> | <A HREF="#anchor1151438">Return to this month's headlines</A><HR></BODY></HTML>
