,  July 1996</A> |</UL><P><A NAME="anchor244958"></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <H2><A HREF="#anchor467384">Demise of Florida's ADF led the nation--down  the tubes</A><A NAME="anchor467384"></A></H2>  <P><I>by Mitchell Gibbs</I></P>  <P><FONT COLOR="#006600">THE NATIONWIDE</FONT> market for recycled PET  plastic has ruptured this year, and recycling industry experts are saying  it's no coincidence that the bust comes after the sunsetting of Florida's  Advance Disposal Fee (ADF) last fall. Though recycled materials markets  have a reputation for volatility, PET - polyethylene terephthalate - has  experienced such a nose dive that your plastic soda bottles may soon be  making a trip straight from the recycling bin to the landfill.</P>  <P>The latest reports indicate that Wellman, Inc. , the nation's largest  plastic reclaimer, was paying as little as one cent a pound for baled PET  scrap. Only a year ago the same material was fetching as much as 40 cents  per pound, and news reports were glowing over the future of recycled plastics.</P>  <P>The Advance Disposal Fee may seem like a dim light in the corner to  cause national repercussions. And certainly a glut of cheap virgin resin  is a primary cause of recycled PET's price slide. But to recycling businesses  the market value isn't the problem, it's that the recycling infrastructure  may be crumbling along with it. And it's that infrastructure that the ADF,  which was a major player in a tiny league of states that passed similar  laws, helped to expand.</P>  <P>In it's September issue, Resource Recycling's Plastics Recycling Update  reported that the number of PET reclaimers - the middlemen who are key  to market stability - was rapidly dwindling. Last year, there were 24 reclaiming  companies. That number now stands at 12 and may soon drop to six, according  to Steve Apotheker, editor of the Portland, Ore. based Update. Apotheker  said that the loss of infrastructure could keep the recycled PET market  bottomed out for a long times.</P>  <P>Though representatives of the plastics industry downplay the role of  Florida's Advance Disposal Fee in this situation, trade journals and state  officials repeatedly point to the ADF's demise as a key factor.</P>  <P>&quot;When the Advance Disposal Fee was going into effect in 1993, one  of the things we heard from industry folks was that 'We're doing this anyway,'&quot;  said Ron Hendricks, administrator for the waste reduction section at the  Department of Environmental Protection. &quot;Then the ADF sunsets in '95  and the market goes to hell in a handbasket.&quot;</P>  <P>&quot;That's a little naive. ... Florida is such a niche market,&quot;  said Roger Bernstein, the Senior Director of Government Affairs for the  American Plastics Council. &quot;If you talk to economists, and we have,  they would say it's an incredible stretch.&quot;</P>  <P>That would seem to match conventional thinking, but market insiders  say Florida's ADF was much more than a law applying only to a niche market.</P>  <P>&quot;Johnson Controls (a major national plastic product manufacturer)  told us they were on the fence - ADF gave them the extra incentive,&quot;  said Russ Martin, a DEP environmental manager in its waste reduction section.</P>  <P>The beauty of the ADF was that it truly worked as an incentive and was  not viewed as a punitive fee, said Martin, who was perhaps more closely  tied to the evolution and implementing of the ADF in the 90's than anyone.  Manufacturers could get exemptions from the fee in two ways: by incorporating  a certain level of recycled material into their packaging, or by adopting  &quot;takeback&quot; policies that found other homes for their used containers.</P>  <P>Martin said that a number of companies viewed an exemption as a competitive  advantage, so that the ADF became a decisive factor for them to plunge  into recycling.</P>  <P>More importantly Florida's law was considered a harbinger for other  states, an omen which some companies actively resisted.</P>  <P>&quot;There was a lot of pressure to kill the ADF in Florida to keep  it from spreading to other states,&quot; said Martin.</P>  <P>That pressure was strongest in the late 80's, when the ADF was getting  fine-tuned. Not surprisingly, many trade and manufacturing groups lobbied  against it, including representatives of the brand-name labels, supermarket  chains, glass packagers, and plastics manufacturers. But strong forces  existed on the other side of the fence. Solid waste issues, especially  dwindling landfill space were popular, and bottle-bill proponents, though  viewing the ADF as a compromise, supported the fee.</P>  <P>When the bill finally went into effect, in 1993, it had been so fine-tuned  as to almost guarantee success.</P>  <P>But for one flaw - the sunset provision.</P>  <P>Though required to have one, the date for sunsetting, when legislators  would review the bill, had not been updated from the original 1988 version.  When 1995 rolled around, and the sunset review came up, Martin and others  who had spent so much time on the bill uttered a collective, &quot;Duh.&quot;</P>  <P>Interestingly, by 1995 the ADF had won over many companies originally  aligned against the the fee.</P>  <P>&quot;There was a lot of quiet support,&quot; said Martin, adding that  the fee won over the National Association for Plastic Container Recovery,  which at least in principal opposes market regulation.</P>  <P>&quot;Especially toward the end, they were fighting to keep it,&quot;  said Martin.</P>  <P>Not all the opposition went away, however.</P>  <P>&quot;Yes. We were opposed to the ADF in Florida,&quot; said the American  Plastic Council's Bernstein. &quot;We support the concerns of plastics  industries that are telling us these kinds of legislation are hurting them.&quot;</P>  <P>In addition to that formidable lobby, in 1995 the ADF faced a fickle  legislature, too pleased that overall recycling goals were being met. And  while the ADF was a glittering success from a recycling viewpoint, legislators  gauged it by the revenue it produced. By that measure, the ADF was a dismal  failure. Because so many companies won exemptions based on recycling revenues  had dropped precipitously.</P>  <P>Some of the results of the ADF's demise were quick. A Florida Pepsi  bottling cooperative immediately stopped buying a patented post-consumer  PET resin from a Shell Oil Co. plant. The bottler was a major buyer, and  the Shell plant shut down. But a Washington bottler had also been buying  the resin, so the sunsetted ADF effectively took recycled Pepsi bottles  off the shelf in another state. Likewise, the end of the ADF is credited  with spurring Johnson Controls, Inc. and Wellman to move their production  of two recycled PET plastics from the U.S. to Europe.</P>  <P>According to a report in the June 1996 issue of Bottlemaking Technology  and Market News, &quot;On the day that Florida's ADF was dropped, demand  for food-contact recycled content vanished overnight.&quot;</P>  <P>Marilyn Bakker, editor of that newsletter, argues that government regulation  is critical to &quot;leveling the playing field&quot; in the plastic bottle  business</P>  <P>&quot;If there are laws, people have to use it, even without the economic  incentive,&quot; said Bakker. &quot;The sunset of the ADF was a major blow  to the recycled PET industry...As long as there was legislation, then everybody  had to work in that direction...As soon as Florida went away, that was  the first big blow.&quot;</P>  <P>Since then, the remaining players, California and Oregon, have seen  their laws thwarted. A dismayed Bakker said that &quot;most of my subscribers  are tickled that all of the legislation is gone.&quot;</P>  <P>But while Bakker says the list of lobbyists opposing such legislation  is long, one name stands out - the American Plastics Council. In the May  issue of her newsletter, the plastics industry is given credit for defeating  &quot;the passage of more than 165 bill proposed in 33 states to ban or  tax plastic products.&quot; As part of that lobbying effort, the council  adopted its own goal of achieving a 25 percent recycling rate across the  board in the plastics industry, a goal it now says is not possible with  today's technology.</P>  <P>&quot;If anyone thinks it's easy for food and beverage container makers  to incorporate recycled PET, it's not,&quot; said Bernstein. &quot;It has  the greatest technical hurdles, the greatest safety hurdles.&quot;</P>  <P>Susan Kissler, the American Plastic Council's media relations director  said the PET downturn was nothing unusual. &quot;It's a commodity like  anything else. It's just a market.&quot;</P>  <P>That isn't exactly true because it is impossible to rid the market of  government influence at the critical level of waste production. And that  may send some soda bottles to the landfill because many local governments,  wooed by predictions of a rosy market, demanded that PET be included in  long-term waste recycling contacts. So while PET collection continues to  increase, places to put it are getting scarce.</P>  <P>The outlook for PET isn't totally dark. The material has become widely  used in a number of products, and an up cycle is bound to come again. The  real issue is that getting recycled PET into food and beverage containers,  by far the largest use of the plastic, would generate exponential market  growth. For ambitious companies that anticipated that growth, Florida's  ATF was a big tease, with a giant disappointment.<BR>  </BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
