ml">12-17-96</A> | <A HREF="121896.html">12-18-96</A>  | <A HREF="121996.html">12-19-96</A> | <A HREF="122096.html">12-20-96</A>  | <A HREF="122396.html">12-23-96</A> | Dec. 24-26, not published | <A   HREF="122796.html">12-27-96</A> | <A HREF="123096.html">12-30-96</A> |</UL><P><A NAME="anchor244958"></A></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <H2><A HREF="#anchor467384">Demise of Florida's ADF led the nation--down  the tubes</A><A NAME="anchor467384"></A></H2>  <P><I>by Mitchell Gibbs</I></P>  <P><FONT COLOR="#006600">THE NATIONWIDE</FONT> market for recycled PET  plastic has ruptured this year, and recycling industry experts are saying  it's no coincidence that the bust comes after the sunsetting of Florida's  Advance Disposal Fee (ADF) last fall. Though recycled materials markets  have a reputation for volatility, PET - polyethylene terephthalate - has  experienced such a nose dive that your plastic soda bottles may soon be  making a trip straight from the recycling bin to the landfill.</P>  <P>The latest reports indicate that Wellman, Inc. , the nation's largest  plastic reclaimer, was paying as little as one cent a pound for baled PET  scrap. Only a year ago the same material was fetching as much as 40 cents  per pound, and news reports were glowing over the future of recycled plastics.</P>  <P>The Advance Disposal Fee may seem like a dim light in the corner to  cause national repercussions. And certainly a glut of cheap virgin resin  is a primary cause of recycled PET's price slide. But to recycling businesses  the market value isn't the problem, it's that the recycling infrastructure  may be crumbling along with it. And it's that infrastructure that the ADF,  which was a major player in a tiny league of states that passed similar  laws, helped to expand.</P>  <P>In it's September issue, Resource Recycling's Plastics Recycling Update  reported that the number of PET reclaimers - the middlemen who are key  to market stability - was rapidly dwindling.